sts times, amount of likes and comment totals and then once everything was loaded, refresh the custom scroll bar height. The scroll lock button paused new comments from auto-updating which was also quite difficult to get working seamlessly.\r\n\r\nConnecting people with their friends was an important part of the app. We kept a database record of the Facebook ID\'s of everyone who logged into the app against a timestamp and if you\'d polled our server in the last 30 seconds we considered you to be in current use of the app. We then would look at the logged in users friends list and cross section that with the people who are currently logged in and display their profile picture and a link to their profile in a grid under the X Friends Watching heading. From here you could also invite your friends to watch the show through the Ulive app and this was done with the Facebook API\'s App Invite functionality.\r\n\r\nThe CMS was relatively straight forward, once a comment was approved to go to air it would be sent via a CURL request to an API at the TVNZ studio. This would then run through their system and be put up on the screen along with the users Name, Profile pic and Age which we got from their Facebook profile.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project turned out to be a great piece of programming. The integration of so many technologies ended up seeming pretty smooth despite having to do a lot of bug fixing and tying up loose ends. Integrating a Facebook app with a live TV show was a first for me and actually a world wide first which caught the attention of a lot of people in technology sphere.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis app was featured on the Facebook developer blog and was also featured on quite a few online newspapers and blogs.\r\n<h3>Additional</h3>\r\nThe site has undergone a design overhaul since we launched it back in 2010 but its still up and running: <a title=\"Ulive facebook app\" href=\"https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive/\" target=\"_blank\">https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive/</a>', 'Ulive', 'This project encompassed a wide range of web technologies. It was the first facebook app to allow users to interact with live television and was featured on facebook\'s developer blog.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '337-revision-33', '', '', '2013-01-13 22:11:25', '2013-01-13 10:11:25', '', '337', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/337-revision-33/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('408', '1', '2013-01-14 19:12:50', '2013-01-14 07:12:50', '', 'saveseven-screen2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'saveseven-screen2', '', '', '2013-01-14 19:12:50', '2013-01-14 07:12:50', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('409', '1', '2013-01-14 19:12:51', '2013-01-14 07:12:51', '', 'saveseven-screen3', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'saveseven-screen3', '', '', '2013-01-14 19:12:51', '2013-01-14 07:12:51', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen3.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('410', '1', '2013-01-14 19:12:51', '2013-01-14 07:12:51', '', 'saveseven-screen4', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'saveseven-screen4', '', '', '2013-01-14 19:12:51', '2013-01-14 07:12:51', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('411', '1', '2013-01-14 19:12:51', '2013-01-14 07:12:51', '', 'saveseven-screen5', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'saveseven-screen5', '', '', '2013-01-14 19:12:51', '2013-01-14 07:12:51', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('412', '1', '2013-01-14 19:12:52', '2013-01-14 07:12:52', '', 'saveseven-screen6', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'saveseven-screen6', '', '', '2013-01-14 19:12:52', '2013-01-14 07:12:52', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('413', '1', '2013-01-14 19:15:08', '2013-01-14 07:15:08', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could watch the womens stories about breast cancer and leave comments\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-408\" alt=\"saveseven-screen2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then choose friends to share the video with via facebook or email\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-410\" alt=\"saveseven-screen4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could choose 7 women to share it with from facebook through my custom friend picker\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-411\" alt=\"saveseven-screen5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The 7 women would then be displayed with their profile pictures\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-412\" alt=\"saveseven-screen6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to reach every woman in New Zealand with the message that early detection via breast screening is the best way to save the lives of the women we care about. The main driving force behind the online campaign was for users to watch the compelling stories of 7 quite different women who have beaten breast cancer and then share them on facebook with 7 women they care about.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThe main nav of the videos was built in flash while the rest of the site was built on top of the Zend Framework. The site uses the Youtube API for video events to trigger an overlay screen over the video. It also used the facebook API, Facebook Open Graph, JQuery and a bit of fancy HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nOne of the main challenges was to build a friend picker that deviated from the standard facebook functionality. We wanted to be able to only show the users friends who are listed as female on the facebook graph. We also wanted the  video to be posted the wall of the 7 women and make sure the audience is more relevant and also to help gain traction and visibility for the campaign.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThe standard facebook friend picker was not enough, it only sends out app invites rather than wall posts and could not be customized to show different data sets. After we had app permissions granted to look at the users friends list, used FQL and the Facebook PHP API to query graph and return all the users friends listed as Female. From that data set I was able to look up those users facebook IDs on the Open Graph and get their Name, Profile Picture and used these to build the layout of the custom friend picker. Although it has a different color scheme, we tried to make it as close to the native facebook friend picker in terms of functionality. You could select up to 7 friends, then when the user clicked send the facebook app would post the video they selected on the site to all the women they had selected which could be watched straight on the facebook news feed along with a link to the site.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nSave Seven had a great core idea and a unique way of spreading its message. The friend picker ended up being such a hit that I packaged it up to be added to our code library for future projects and it has been re purposed many times since it was built. Its always great to try something you haven\'t done before, especially when it works great and is for a great cause.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nAxis 2012: Gold - Charity &amp; Appeals', 'Save Seven', 'Seven women every day are diagnosed with Breast Cancer in New Zealand. Our mission was to encourage people to reach out to seven women they care about and spread the message of how early detection saves lives. This a won Gold Axis for best Charity campaign of 2011 ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'save-seven', '', '', '2014-05-29 21:56:25', '2014-05-29 09:56:25', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=413', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('552', '1', '2013-02-26 20:30:23', '2013-02-26 08:30:23', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could watch the womens stories about breast cancer and leave comments\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-408\" alt=\"saveseven-screen2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then choose friends to share the video with via facebook or email\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-410\" alt=\"saveseven-screen4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could choose 7 women to share it with from facebook through my custom friend picker\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-411\" alt=\"saveseven-screen5\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The 7 women would then be displayed with their profile pictures\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-412\" alt=\"saveseven-screen6\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to reach every woman in New Zealand with the message that early detection via breast screening is the best way to save the lives of the women we care about. The main driving force behind the online campaign was for users to watch the compelling stories of 7 quite different women who have beaten breast cancer and share them on facebook with 7 women they care about.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThe main nav of the videos was built in flash while the rest of the site was built on top of the Zend Framework. The site uses the Youtube API for video events to trigger an overlay screen over the video. It also used the facebook API, Facebook Open Graph, JQuery and a bit of fancy HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nOne of the main challenges was to build a friend picker that deviated from the standard facebook functionality. We wanted to be able to only show the users friends who are listed as female on the facebook graph. We also wanted the  video to be posted the wall of the 7 women and make sure the audience is more relevant and also to help gain traction and visibility for the campaign.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThe standard facebook friend picker was not enough, it only sends out app invites rather than wall posts and could not be customized to show different data sets. After we had app permissions granted to look at the users friends list, used FQL and the Facebook PHP API to query graph and return all the users friends listed as Female. From that data set I was able to look up those users facebook IDs on the Open Graph and get their Name, Profile Picture and used these to build the layout of the custom friend picker. Although it has a different color scheme, we tried to make it as close to the native facebook friend picker in terms of functionality. You could select up to 7 friends, then when the user clicked send the facebook app would post the video they selected on the site to all the women they had selected which could be watched straight on the facebook news feed along with a link to the site.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nSave Seven had a great core idea and a unique way of spreading its message. The friend picker ended up being such a hit that I packaged it up to be added to our code library for future projects and it has been re purposed many times since it was built. Its always great to try something you haven\'t done before, especially when it works great and is for a great cause.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nSave Seven won a Gold Axis for best Charity Campaign at the Axis Awards in 2012 and has won a few awards overseas as well.', 'Save Seven', 'Seven women every day are diagnosed with Breast Cancer in New Zealand. Our mission was to encourage people to reach out to seven women they care about and spread the message of how early detection saves lives. This a won Gold Axis for best Charity campaign of 2011 ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '413-revision-13', '', '', '2013-02-26 20:30:23', '2013-02-26 08:30:23', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/413-revision-13/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('353', '1', '2013-01-12 21:44:36', '2013-01-12 09:44:36', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Comments made on facebook would appear on live TV.\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Ulive comments page\" src=\"http://localhost/techb