red on the Facebook developer blog and was also featured on quite a few online news papers and blogs.', 'Ulive', 'This project encompassed a wide range of web technologies. It was the first facebook app to allow users to interact with live television and was featured on facebook\'s developer blog.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '337-revision-18', '', '', '2013-01-13 12:37:05', '2013-01-13 00:37:05', '', '337', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/337-revision-18/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('361', '1', '2013-01-13 12:37:14', '2013-01-13 00:37:14', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Comments made on facebook would appear on live TV.\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Ulive comments page\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could vote in polls which would be discussed by the presenters\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Ulive voting page \" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could stream Ulive from within the app\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Ulive streaming page\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could invite their friends to take part in the discussions\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Ulive invite page\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Purpose</h3>\r\nThe goal of this project was to create a Facebook app housed on the TVNZU page which allowed facebook users to watch the live show. It was to allow the users to get involved in the discussions the presenters were having and even get their comments to appear in real time on live TV. It was also to create a sense of community within the users friends by allowing them to invite their friends to watch the show and also display a list of which of your friends were currently tuned in via the app.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built on the Zend Framework and implements the Facebook API, JQuery, AJAX, a custom scroll bar JS library and of course HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenge</h3>\r\nThe discussion feed needed to have the same user experience as Facebook but the feed functionality isn\'t part of the Facebook API and it needed to poll the server to add new comments without refreshing. The voting section needed to display comments in two columns depending on what you voted for and also auto-update. The video stream of the show needed to only be active when the show was on but also automatically load the show when the show started if the user had the window open. The app had to integrate with the users friends list and keep a track of who was online so we could display if any of your friends were watching and also have an invite mechanic. There was also the archiving of old discussions and polls as well as the feed moderation for the comments that went to air and CMS for the app.\r\n<h3>Method</h3>\r\nWe had to recreate the Facebook feed\'s functionality from scratch with the added ability to flag posts for moderator review. This became a very difficult task when there\'s so much integration. Every time we AJAX\'d in a new set of posts we had to bump the same number off the bottom so the pagination was intact while