developer blog and was also featured on quite a few online newspapers and blogs.\r\n<h3>Additional</h3>\r\nThe site has undergone a design overhaul since we launched it back in 2010 but its still up and running: <a title=\"Ulive facebook app\" href=\"https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive/\" target=\"_blank\">https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive/</a>', 'Ulive', 'This project encompassed a wide range of web technologies. It was the first facebook app to allow users to interact with live television and was featured on facebook\'s developer blog.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '337-revision-30', '', '', '2013-01-13 14:40:39', '2013-01-13 02:40:39', '', '337', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/337-revision-30/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('371', '1', '2013-01-13 13:14:07', '2013-01-13 01:14:07', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Comments made on facebook would appear on live TV.\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Ulive comments page\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could vote in polls which would be discussed by the presenters\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Ulive voting page \" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could stream Ulive from within the app\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Ulive streaming page\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could invite their friends to take part in the discussions\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Ulive invite page\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe goal of this project was to create a Facebook app housed on the TVNZU page which allowed facebook users to watch the live show. It was to allow the users to get involved in the discussions the presenters were having and even get their comments to appear in real time on live TV. It was also to create a sense of community within the users friends by allowing them to invite their friends to watch the show and also display a list of which of your friends were currently tuned in via the app.\r\n<h3>Technologies</h3>\r\nThis project was built on the Zend Framework and implements the Facebook API, JQuery, AJAX, a custom scroll bar JS library and of course HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe discussion feed needed to have the same user experience as Facebook but the feed functionality isn\'t part of the Facebook API and it needed to poll the server to add new comments without refreshing. The voting section needed to display comments in two columns depending on what you voted for and also auto-update. The video stream of the show needed to only be active when the show was on but also automatically load the show when the show started if the user had the window open. The app had to integrate with the users friends list and keep a track of who was online so we could display if any of your friends were watching and also have an invite mechanic. There was also the archiving of old discussions and polls as well as the feed moderation for the comments that went to air and CMS for the app.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWe had to recreate the Facebook feed\'s functionality from scratch with the added ability to flag posts for moderator review. This became a very difficult task when there\'s so much integration. Every time we AJAX\'d in a new set of posts we had to bump the same number off the bottom so the pagination was intact while keeping their indexes for the likes and times all correct. We had to update the posts times, amount of likes and comment totals and then once everything was loaded, refresh the custom scroll bar height. The scroll lock button paused new comments from auto-updating which was also quite difficult to get working seamlessly.\r\n\r\nThe polls worked in much the same way but with the added complication that you couldn\'t comment until you\'d voted and that your vote was displayed under the option you voted for. This meant that if a lot more people voted and commented on 1 option than the other, we\'d get into a situation where if we were a few pages back in the comments, we end up with just 1 column displaying on the page which needed to be accounted for.\r\n\r\nThe video stream was implemented with a 3rd party flash video streamer. It\'s controls were pretty basic and this was one of the easier things to implement. We had a few problems around the video continuing to play after the slide down was closed or not starting when the shows start time clicked over. Some browsers seemed to continue the streaming even if the object was removed from the DOM, so it was important to get the video actually stopped and unloaded before hiding it or removing it from the DOM.\r\n\r\nConnecting people with their friends was an important part of the app. We kept a database record of the Facebook ID\'s of everyone who logged into the app against a timestamp and if you\'d polled our server in the last 30 seconds we considered you to be in current use of the app. We then would look at the logged in users friends list and cross section that with the people who are currently logged in and display their profile picture and a link to their profile in a grid under the X Friends Watching heading. From here you could also invite your friends to watch the show through the Ulive app and this was done with the Facebook API\'s App Invite functionality.\r\n\r\nThe CMS was relatively straight forward, once a comment was approved to go to air it would be sent via a CURL request to an API at the TVNZ studio. This would then run through their system and be put up on the screen along with the users Name, Profile pic and Age which we got from their Facebook profile.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project turned out to be a great piece of programming. The integration of so many technologies ended up seeming pretty smooth despite having to do a lot of bug fixing and tying up loose ends. Integrating a Facebook app with a live TV show was a first for me and actually a world wide first which caught the attention of a lot of people in technology sphere.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis app was featured on the Facebook developer blog and was also featured on quite a few online newspapers and blogs.\r\n<h3>Additional</h3>\r\nThe site has undergone a design overhaul since we launched it back in 2010 but its still up and running: <a title=\"Ulive facebook app\" href=\"https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive/\" target=\"_blank\">https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive/</a>', 'Ulive', 'This project encompassed a wide range of web technologies. It was the first facebook app to allow users to interact with live television and was featured on facebook\'s developer blog.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '337-revision-27', '', '', '2013-01-13 13:14:07', '2013-01-13 01:14:07', '', '337', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/337-revision-27/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('372', '1', '2013-01-13 13:42:27', '2013-01-13 01:42:27', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could take a picture using their webcam\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Webcam\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site used NEC facial recognition software to scan the users facial features\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Image Processing\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"NEC\'s results were used to pair the user with a dog from the SPCA\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Results\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could share their results on Facebook\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Share \" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nCannes 2011: Gold Lion.\r\n\r\nAxis 2012: Grand Axis.\r\n\r\nSpikes Asia 2011: Digital Grand Prix.\r\n\r\nCaples 2011: Gold.', 'Doggelganger', 'Doggelganger used security grade facial recognition software to match your face with a dog who is up for adoption from the SPCA animal shelter. Its won a Gold at Cannes, the Grand Axis award and many more.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'doggelganger', '', '', '2014-05-29 21:55:31', '2014-05-29 09:55:31', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=372', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('407', '1', '2013-01-14 19:12:50', '2013-01-14 07:12:50', '', 'saveseven-screen1', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'saveseven-screen1', '', '', '2013-01-14 19:12:50', '2013-01-14 07:12:50', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen1.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('374', '1', '2013-01-13 13:37:44', '2013-01-13 01:37:44', '', 'Doggelganger Web Cam Page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'doggelganger-screen1', '', '', '2013-01-13 13:37:44', '2013-01-13 01:37:44', '', '372', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('375', '1', '2013-01-13 13:37:45', '2013-01-13 01:37:45', '', 'Doggelganger Scanning Page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'doggelganger-screen2', '', '', '2013-01-13 13:37:45', '2013-01-13 01:37:45', '', '372', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('376', '1', '2013-01-13 13:37:46', '2013-01-13 01:37:46', '', 'Doggelganger Results Page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'doggelganger-screen3', '', '', '2013-01-13 13:37:46', '2013-01-13 01:37:46', '', '372', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('377', '1', '2013-01-13 13:37:47', '2013-01-13 01:37:47', '', 'Doggelganger Share Page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'doggelganger-screen4', '', '', '