tion', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '5-revision-9', '', '', '2013-01-07 22:48:19', '2013-01-07 10:48:19', '', '5', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/5-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('262', '1', '2013-01-07 22:48:24', '2013-01-07 10:48:24', 'Vestibulum vel lorem nunc, in lobortis nunc. Class aptent taciti sociosqu ad litora torquent per conubia nostra, per inceptos himenaeos. In cursus iaculis rutrum. Integer at sapien et velit porta euismod. Sed at libero ligula. Sed viverra porttitor nisl ut vulputate. Nam ac volutpat risus. Integer pretium libero a quam aliquet in auctor diam ultricies.', 'Portfolio', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '6-revision-8', '', '', '2013-01-07 22:48:24', '2013-01-07 10:48:24', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/6-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('337', '1', '2013-01-12 21:19:57', '2013-01-12 09:19:57', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Comments made on facebook would appear on live TV.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Ulive comments page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could vote in polls which would be discussed by the presenters\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Ulive voting page \" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could stream Ulive from within the app\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Ulive streaming page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could invite their friends to take part in the discussions\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Ulive invite page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a Facebook app housed on the TVNZU page which allowed facebook users to watch the live show. It was to allow the users to get involved in the discussions the presenters were having and even get their comments to appear in real time on live TV. It was also to create a sense of community within the users friends by allowing them to invite their friends to watch the show and also display a list of which of your friends were currently tuned in via the app.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built on the Zend Framework and implements the Facebook API, JQuery, AJAX, a custom scroll bar JS library and of course HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was that discussion feed needed to have the same user experience as Facebook but the feed functionality isn\'t part of the Facebook API and it needed to poll the server to add new comments without refreshing. The app also had to integrate with the users friends list and keep a track of who was online so we could display if any of your friends were watching and also have an invite mechanic. There was also the archiving of old discussions and polls as well as the feed moderation for the comments that went to air and CMS for the app.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWe had to recreate the Facebook feed\'s functionality from scratch with the added ability to flag posts for moderator review. This became a very difficult task when there\'s so much integration. Every time we AJAX\'d in a new set of posts we had to bump the same number off the bottom so the pagination was intact while keeping their indexes for the likes and times all correct. We had to update the posts times, amount of likes and comment totals and then once everything was loaded, refresh the custom scroll bar height. The scroll lock button paused new comments from auto-updating which was also quite difficult to get working seamlessly.\r\n\r\nConnecting people with their friends was an important part of the app. We kept a database record of the Facebook ID\'s of everyone who logged into the app against a timestamp and if you\'d polled our server in the last 30 seconds we considered you to be in current use of the app. We then would look at the logged in users friends list and cross section that with the people who are currently logged in and display their profile picture and a link to their profile in a grid under the X Friends Watching heading. From here you could also invite your friends to watch the show through the Ulive app and this was done with the Facebook API\'s App Invite functionality.\r\n\r\nThe CMS was relatively straight forward, once a comment was approved to go to air it would be sent via a CURL request to an API at the TVNZ studio. This would then run through their system and be put up on the screen along with the users Name, Profile pic and Age which we got from their Facebook profile.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project turned out to be a great piece of programming. The integration of so many technologies ended up seeming pretty smooth despite having to do a lot of bug fixing and tying up loose ends. Integrating a Facebook app with a live TV show was a first for me and actually a world wide first which caught the attention of a lot of people in technology sphere.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis app was featured on the Facebook developer blog and was also featured on quite a few online newspapers and blogs.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"U Live\" href=\"https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive\" target=\"_blank\">https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive</a>', 'Ulive', 'This project encompassed a wide range of web technologies. It was the first facebook app to allow users to interact with live television and was featured on facebook\'s developer blog.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'ulive', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:23:52', '2014-05-28 10:23:52', '', '1004', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=337', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('338', '1', '2013-01-12 21:16:01', '2013-01-12 09:16:01', '', 'Live Commenting', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'ulive-screen1', '', '', '2013-01-12 21:16:01', '2013-01-12 09:16:01', '', '337', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('534', '1', '2013-02-25 21:08:21', '2013-02-25 09:08:21', '<h3>Goals</h3>\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\n<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mobile site has its own bespoke layout to offer the tools relevant to the medium\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-520\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-1\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"It still showed the same content modules but in full width single file\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-521\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could also view the full article by clicking on the content item\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-522\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-3\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Contact us and Join us both triggered slide in panels from the left\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-523\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'V Robbers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:08:21', '2013-02-25 09:08:21', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('535', '1', '2013-02-25 21:09:59', '2013-02-25 09:09:59', '', 'vrobbers-featured', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'vrobbers-featured', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:09:59', '2013-02-25 09:09:59', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-featured.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('536', '1', '2013-02-25 21:08:27', '2013-02-25 09:08:27', '<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mobile site has its own bespoke layout to offer the tools relevant to the medium\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-520\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-1\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"It still showed the same content modules but in full width single file\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-521\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could also view the full article by clicking on the content item\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-522\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-3\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Contact us and Join us both triggered slide in panels from the left\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-523\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'V Robbers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-2', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:08:27', '2013-02-25 09:08:27', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('537', '1', '2013-02-25 21:10:32', '2013-02-25 09:10:32', '', 'vrobbers-1', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'vrobbers-1', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:10:32', '2013-02-25 09:10:32', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('538', '1', '2013-02-25 21:10:37', '2013-02-25 09:10:37', '', 'vrobbers-2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'vrobbers-2', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:10:37', '2013-02-25 09:10:37', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('539', '1', '2013-02-25 21:10:41', '2013-02-25 09:10:41', '', 'vrobbers-3', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'vrobbers-3', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:10:41', '2013-02-25 09:10:41', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('540', '1', '2013-02-25 21:10:44', '2013-02-25 09:10:44', '', 'vrobbers-4', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'vrobbers-4', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:10:44', '2013-02-25 09:10:44', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('541', '1', '2013-02-25 21:11:02', '2013-02-25 09:11:02', '', 'vrobbers-5', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'vrobbers-5', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:11:02', '2013-02-25 09:11:02', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('542', '1', '2013-02-25 21:11:04', '2013-02-25 09:11:04', '', 'vrobbers7', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'vrobbers7', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:11:04', '2013-02-25 09:11:04', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('543', '1', '2013-02-25 21:11:19', '2013-02-25 09:11:19', '', 'vrobbers-6', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'vrobbers-6', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:11:19', '2013-02-25 09:11:19', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('544', '1', '2013-02-25 21:11:22', '2013-02-25 09:11:22', '', 'vrobbers-8', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'vrobbers-8', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:11:22', '2013-02-25 09:11:22', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('545', '1', '2014-05-29 22:32:20', '2014-05-29 10:32:20', '<div class=\"gallery\">\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<h3>Goals</h3>\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThe front end of this project was built in Flash on top of an API I wrote in the Zend Framework.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 cash up for grabs through the game mechanic it was important to stop any cheating. Apart from that, the mechanic itself was quite sprawling with a lot of maps and suburbs to fill out. Spreading out the new users, dropping cash to the right secret locations and keeping the whole thing running while under heavy load was definitely difficult.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nThere were a few main security issues which arose during this campaign. I put a lot of effort into the robbing mechanic being as bulletproof as possible. We had no problems at all in regards to people being able to steal cash off someone when they were\'nt supposed to or defrauding the system for more money than they were supposed to get.\n\nThe main issue we has was that someone performed a denial of service attack on our infrastructure at one point in the game. They were using our API to retrieve information about the different maps as if they were a user entering a new map and getting all the locations and dollar values. The information itself was benign, but they spammed these requests to the point of it choking the server. Presumably, they wanted to rob someone and didn\'t want anyone else attacking that user and hence missing their chance to rob them. So they DDOS attacked the server for a couple minutes around the time the user became vulnerable, stopped the attack, robbed the person and then resumed the attack until they were able to put them selves on protection so they couldn\'t get robbed. This is all conjecture, we could not track down the user who was performing the attack, it came from an IP address which was not associated with any of the players. We stopped this by banning the IP which was attacking us and also implemented in some rate limiting on the number of API requests that could be performed by a single IP address within a given time frame.\n\nThe only other notable things which happened was peoples ingenuity at exploiting the rules of the game which are not technically hacks. Some users reportedly set their mouse to only move on the X or Y axis, rather than in any direction on the X,Y plane. This enabled them to clip the wires faster as they had less chance of hitting the sides of the alarm and hence steal more money. The other thing was poeople would get their friend to setup an account with no money on it and when the main account was vulnerable to attack, they would attack the user but not attempt to steal any money. This would simply tie up the account with a current robbery and since a user could only be robbed by one person at a time, this chewed up their time until they could protect their stash again. Neither of these tactics were technically against the rules, and really showed the engagement level we had achieved in the user base.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nDespite everyone\'s attempts to get as much cash as they could, our game was designed to be hard to hold onto cash. The idea was that the money would get spread out across a large number of users to make it more enjoyable for more people. At one point, one of the users made it to about $12,000, but I think the top prize claimed at the end of the game was about $2000 out of a possible $100,000. So it seems like our mechanic did what it was designed to do and spread the money around effectively. Also, despite all the bumps along the way with people trying to exploit the game and attack our servers, the game held up well and was thoroughly enjoyed by V\'s  fan base. The average time on site was something like 25 minutes per visit, so it was super engaging and a great success for the brand.\n<h3>Awards</h3>\nCannes 2013: Bronze Lion.\n\nAxis: 2014: Silver - Digital &amp; Interactive.', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-autosave', '', '', '2014-05-29 22:32:20', '2014-05-29 10:32:20', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('585', '1', '2013-02-27 12:35:37', '2013-02-27 00:35:37', '<div class=\"gallery\"><div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div><div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'V Robbers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-9', '', '', '2013-02-27 12:35:37', '2013-02-27 00:35:37', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('274', '1', '2013-01-08 17:56:20', '2013-01-08 05:56:20', 'Vestibulum vel lorem nunc, in lobortis nunc. Class aptent taciti sociosqu ad litora torquent per conubia nostra, per inceptos himenaeos. In cursus iaculis rutrum. Integer at sapien et velit porta euismod. Sed at libero ligula. Sed viverra porttitor nisl ut vulputate. Nam ac volutpat risus. Integer pretium libero a quam aliquet in auctor diam ultricies.', 'Portfolio', 'This is the excerpt for the portfolio page which will end up being the facebook meta description', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '6-revision-9', '', '', '2013-01-08 17:56:20', '2013-01-08 05:56:20', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/6-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('533', '1', '2013-02-25 21:08:27', '2013-02-25 09:08:27', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThe front end of this project was built in Flash on top of an API I wrote in the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 cash up for grabs through the game mechanic it was important to stop any cheating. Apart from that, the mechanic itself was quite sprawling with a lot of maps and suburbs to fill out. Spreading out the new users, dropping cash to the right secret locations and keeping the whole thing running while under heavy load was definitely difficult.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThere were a few main security issues which arose during this campaign. I put a lot of effort into the robbing mechanic being as bulletproof as possible. We had no problems at all in regards to people being able to steal cash off someone when they were\'nt supposed to or defrauding the system for more money than they were supposed to get.\r\n\r\nThe main issue we has was that someone performed a denial of service attack on our infrastructure at one point in the game. They were using our API to retrieve information about the different maps as if they were a user entering a new map and getting all the locations and dollar values. The information itself was benign, but they spammed these requests to the point of it choking the server. Presumably, they wanted to rob someone and didn\'t want anyone else attacking that user and hence missing their chance to rob them. So they DDOS attacked the server for a couple minutes around the time the user became vulnerable, stopped the attack, robbed the person and then resumed the attack until they were able to put them selves on protection so they couldn\'t get robbed. This is all conjecture, we could not track down the user who was performing the attack, it came from an IP address which was not associated with any of the players. We stopped this by banning the IP which was attacking us and also implemented in some rate limiting on the number of API requests that could be performed by a single IP address within a given time frame.\r\n\r\nThe only other notable things which happened was peoples ingenuity at exploiting the rules of the game which are not technically hacks. Some users reportedly set their mouse to only move on the X or Y axis, rather than in any direction on the X,Y plane. This enabled them to clip the wires faster as they had less chance of hitting the sides of the alarm and hence steal more money. The other thing was poeople would get their friend to setup an account with no money on it and when the main account was vulnerable to attack, they would attack the user but not attempt to steal any money. This would simply tie up the account with a current robbery and since a user could only be robbed by one person at a time, this chewed up their time until they could protect their stash again. Neither of these tactics were technically against the rules, and really showed the engagement level we had achieved in the user base.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nDespite everyone\'s attempts to get as much cash as they could, our game was designed to be hard to hold onto cash. The idea was that the money would get spread out across a large number of users to make it more enjoyable for more people. At one point, one of the users made it to about $12,000, but I think the top prize claimed at the end of the game was about $2000 out of a possible $100,000. So it seems like our mechanic did what it was designed to do and spread the money around effectively. Also, despite all the bumps along the way with people trying to exploit the game and attack our servers, the game held up well and was thoroughly enjoyed by V\'s  fan base. The average time on site was something like 25 minutes per visit, so it was super engaging and a great success for the brand.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nCannes 2013: Bronze Lion.\r\n\r\nAxis: 2014: Silver - Digital &amp; Interactive.', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'v-robbers', '', '', '2014-05-29 22:31:18', '2014-05-29 10:31:18', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=533', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('275', '1', '2013-01-12 19:43:44', '2013-01-12 07:43:44', 'Vestibulum vel lorem nunc, in lobortis nunc. Class aptent taciti sociosqu ad litora torquent per conubia nostra, per inceptos himenaeos. In cursus iaculis rutrum. Integer at sapien et velit porta euismod. Sed at libero ligula. Sed viverra porttitor nisl ut vulputate. Nam ac volutpat risus. Integer pretium libero a quam aliquet in auctor diam ultricies.', 'Code in Action', 'This is the excerpt for the portfolio page which will end up being the facebook meta description', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '6-revision-10', '', '', '2013-01-12 19:43:44', '2013-01-12 07:43:44', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/6-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('276', '1', '2013-01-08 17:56:09', '2013-01-08 05:56:09', 'Vestibulum vel lorem nunc, in lobortis nunc. Class aptent taciti sociosqu ad litora torquent per conubia nostra, per inceptos himenaeos. In cursus iaculis rutrum. Integer at sapien et velit porta euismod. Sed at libero ligula. Sed viverra porttitor nisl ut vulputate. Nam ac volutpat risus. Integer pretium libero a quam aliquet in auctor diam ultricies.\r\n\r\n[contact-form-7 id=\"56\" title=\"Submit a Question\"]', 'Submit a 