crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.', 'BK Brand Site', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '454-revision-10', '', '', '2013-02-27 12:29:08', '2013-02-27 00:29:08', '', '454', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/454-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('466', '1', '2013-01-16 20:16:38', '2013-01-16 08:16:38', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could take a picture using their webcam\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Webcam\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site used NEC facial recognition software to scan the users facial features\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Image Processing\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"NEC\'s results were used to pair the user with a dog from the SPCA\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Results\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could share their results on Facebook\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Share \" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.', 'BK Brand Site', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '454-revision-5', '', '', '2013-01-16 20:16:38', '2013-01-16 08:16:38', '', '454', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/454-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('467', '1', '2013-01-16 20:17:41', '2013-01-16 08:17:41', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-459\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0003_Background\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-458\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer 74\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-457\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer 75\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-456\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer 78\" src=