2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.', 'V Blue Facebook Tab', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '470-revision-5', '', '', '2013-01-16 20:58:44', '2013-01-16 08:58:44', '', '470', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/470-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('483', '1', '2013-01-12 20:26:40', '2013-01-12 08:26:40', 'Vestibulum vel lorem nunc, in lobortis nunc. Class aptent taciti sociosqu ad litora torquent per conubia nostra, per inceptos himenaeos. In cursus iaculis rutrum. Integer at sapien et velit porta euismod. Sed at libero ligula. Sed viverra porttitor nisl ut vulputate. Nam ac volutpat risus. Integer pretium libero a quam aliquet in auctor diam ultricies.', 'Code in Action', 'This is the excerpt for the portfolio page which will end up being the facebook meta description', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '6-revision-11', '', '', '2013-01-12 20:26:40', '2013-01-12 08:26:40', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/6-revision-11/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('531', '1', '2013-02-13 17:10:17', '2013-02-13 05:10:17', 'Vestibulum vel lorem nunc, in lobortis nunc. Class aptent taciti sociosqu ad litora torquent per conubia nostra, per inceptos himenaeos. In cursus iaculis rutrum. Integer at sapien et velit porta euismod. Sed at libero ligula. Sed viverra porttitor nisl ut vulputate. Nam ac volutpat risus. Integer pretium libero a quam aliquet in auctor diam ultricies.', 'Examples', 'This is the excerpt for the portfolio page which will end up being the facebook meta description', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '6-revision-13', '', '', '2013-02-13 17:10:17', '2013-02-13 05:10:17', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/6-revision-13/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('485', '1', '2013-01-28 10:51:26', '2013-01-27 22:51:26', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"#BNZgamechat was setup as a live alternative commentary for the Rugby World Cup\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-489\" alt=\"gamechat4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Our 5 alternate commentators would tweet about the All blacks games as they happened\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-488\" alt=\"gamechat3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site changed format when viewed on a mobile or tablet\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-486\" alt=\"gamechat1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Twitter users could hashtag #BNZgamechat and have their tweets show up on the side feed\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-487\" alt=\"gamechat2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nBNZ Gamechat was a sponsored alternative commentary to the Rugby World Cup as presented by local celebrities through a twitter stream users could interact with.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework. It also implements the Twitter API, JQuery and AJAX.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge of this project was to make it feel and behave just like a real twitter stream. The page also needed to reformat for mobile and tablet use as it was intended to be used as a companion to watching the game on TV.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nJavascript was used to poll the server at an interval to check if new tweets had been added. If new tweets were added, they would be AJAX\'d into the top of the list and then the post dates of all the previous tweets would also be adjusted to reflect how long ago they actually were tweeted. The same had to be done to the fan feed which was running off the hash tag #BNZGamechat. The latest tweets were indexed and kept in memcache to avoid having all the users query the database once every minute. A cron job had to be setup to pull in new tweets from the assigned users twitter streams and push them to memory for retrieval by AJAX.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThe project ran really smoothly. The twitter stream worked well and gained a high level of interaction within the New Zealand twitter community. The form factor used for mobiles and tablets was intuitive and simple with many features you expect from a mobile device, like a number showing how many new tweets were waiting for you on the other tab.', 'BNZgamechat', 'BNZ Gamechat was a sponsored alternative commentary to the Rugby World Cup as presented by local celebrities through a twitter stream users could interact with.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bnz-game-chat', '', '', '2013-02-27 15:31:01', '2013-02-27 03:31:01', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=485', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('486', '1', '2013-01-28 10:51:17', '2013-01-27 22:51:17', '', 'gamechat1', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gamechat1', '', '', '2013-01-28 10:51:17', '2013-01-27 22:51:17', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('487', '1', '2013-01-28 10:51:18', '2013-01-27 22:51:18', '', 'gamechat2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gamechat2', '', '', '2013-01-28 10:51:18', '2013-01-27 22:51:18', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('488', '1', '2013-01-28 10:51:19', '2013-01-27 22:51:19', '', 'gamechat3', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gamechat3', '', '', '2013-01-28 10:51:19', '2013-01-27 22:51:19', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('489', '1', '2013-01-28 10:51:19', '2013-01-27 22:51:19', '', 'gamechat4', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gamechat4', '', '', '2013-01-28 10:51:19', '2013-01-27 22:51:19', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('490', '1', '2013-01-28 10:51:20', '2013-01-27 22:51:20', '', 'gamechat-featured', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gamechat-featured', '', '', '2013-01-28 10:51:20', '2013-01-27 22:51:20', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat-featured.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('491', '1', '2013-01-28 10:51:09', '2013-01-27 22:51:09', '<h3>Goals</h3>\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\n\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZ game chat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '485-revision', '', '', '2013-01-28 10:51:09', '2013-01-27 22:51:09', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/485-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('492', '1', '2013-01-16 20:59:00', '2013-01-16 08:59:00', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The Facebook tab app has a like gate to unlock content for fans only\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-474\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer 2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could log into their V Republic account while still in Facebook\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer-88.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-473\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer 88\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer-88-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"If they didnt have an account they could register while still in Facebook too\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer-89.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-472\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer 89\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer-89-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They had to try and guess what flavor combinations the new V Blue was to win $10,000\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-471\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer 91\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.', 'V Blue Facebook Tab', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '470-revision-6', '', '', '2013-01-16 20:59:00', '2013-01-16 08:59:00', '', '470', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/470-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('493', '1', '2013-01-28 10:51:26', '2013-01-27 22:51:26', '<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\