wed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZ game chat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '485-revision-2', '', '', '2013-01-28 10:51:26', '2013-01-27 22:51:26', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/485-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('494', '1', '2013-01-28 10:52:21', '2013-01-27 22:52:21', '<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZ game chat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '485-revision-3', '', '', '2013-01-28 10:52:21', '2013-01-27 22:52:21', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/485-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('495', '1', '2014-05-29 21:32:03', '2014-05-29 09:32:03', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"#BNZgamechat was setup as a live alternative commentary for the Rugby World Cup\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-489\" alt=\"gamechat4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Our 5 alternate commentators would tweet about the All blacks games as they happened\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-488\" alt=\"gamechat3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site changed format when viewed on a mobile or tablet\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-486\" alt=\"gamechat1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Twitter users could hashtag #BNZgamechat and have their tweets show up on the side feed\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-487\" alt=\"gamechat2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\n<h3>Goals</h3>\nBNZ Gamechat was a sponsored alternative commentary to the Rugby World Cup as presented by local celebrities through a twitter stream users could interact with.\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework. It also implements the Twitter API, JQuery and AJAX.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nThe main challenge of this project was to make it feel and behave just like a real twitter stream. The page also needed to reformat for mobile and tablet use as it was intended to be used as a companion to watching the game on TV.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nJavascript was used to poll the server at an interval to check if new tweets had been added. If new tweets were added, they would be AJAX\'d into the top of the list and then the post dates of all the previous tweets would also be adjusted to reflect how long ago they actually were tweeted. The same had to be done to the fan feed which was running off the hash tag #BNZGamechat. The latest tweets were indexed and kept in memcache to avoid having all the users query the database once every minute. A cron job had to be setup to pull in new tweets from the assigned users twitter streams and push them to memory for retrieval by AJAX.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nThe project ran really smoothly. The twitter stream worked well and gained a high level of interaction within the New Zealand twitter community. The form factor used for mobiles and tablets was intuitive and simple with many features you expect from a mobile device, like a number showing how many new tweets were waiting for you on the other tab.', 'BNZgamechat', 'BNZ Gamechat was a sponsored alternative commentary to the Rugby World Cup as presented by local celebrities through a twitter stream users could interact with.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '485-autosave', '', '', '2014-05-29 21:32:03', '2014-05-29 09:32:03', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/485-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('583', '1', '2013-02-27 15:04:43', '2013-02-27 03:04:43', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"#BNZgamechat was setup as a live alternative commentary for the Rugby World Cup\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-489\" alt=\"gamechat4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Our 5 alternate commentators would tweet about the All blacks games as they happened\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-488\" alt=\"gamechat3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site changed format when viewed on a mobile or tablet\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-486\" alt=\"gamechat1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Twitter users could hashtag #BNZgamechat and have their tweets show up on the side feed\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-487\" alt=\"gamechat2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nBNZ Gamechat was a sponsored alternative commentary to the Rugby World Cup as presented by local celebrities through a twitter stream users could interact with.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework. It also implements the Twitter API, JQuery and AJAX.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZgamechat', 'BNZ Gamechat was a sponsored alternative commentary to the Rugby World Cup as presented by local celebrities through a twitter stream users could interact with.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '485-revision-9', '', '', '2013-02-27 15:04:43', '2013-02-27 03:04:43', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/485-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('496', '1', '2013-01-28 10:53:11', '2013-01-27 22:53:11', '<a href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-489\" alt=\"gamechat4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-488\" alt=\"gamechat3\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-486\" alt=\"gamechat1\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-487\" alt=\"gamechat2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZ game chat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '485-revision-4', '', '', '2013-01-28 10:53:11', '2013-01-27 22:53:11', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/485-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('497', '1', '2013-01-28 11:00:32', '2013-01-27 23:00:32', '<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"#BNZgamechat was setup as a live alternative commentary for the Rugby World Cup\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-489\" alt=\"gamechat4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Our 5 alternate commentators would tweet about the All blacks games as they happened\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-488\" alt=\"gamechat3\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site changed format when viewed on a mobile or tablet\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-486\" alt=\"gamechat1\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Twitter users could hashtag #BNZgamechat and have their tweets show up on the side feed\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-487\" alt=\"gamechat2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZ game chat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '485-revision-5', '', '', '2013-01-28 11:00:32', '2013-01-27 23:00:32', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/485-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('499', '1', '2013-01-28 11:00:58', '2013-01-27 23:00:58', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"#BNZgamechat was setup as a live alternative commentary for the Rugby World Cup\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-489\" alt=\"gamechat4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Our 5 alternate commentators would tweet about the All blacks games as they happened\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-488\" alt=\"gamechat3\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site changed format when viewed on a mobile or tablet\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-486\" alt=\"gamechat1\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Twitter users could hashtag #BNZgamechat and have their tweets show up on the side feed\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-487\" alt=\"gamechat2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZ game chat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '485-revision-6', '', '', '2013-01-28 11:00:58', '2013-01-27 23:00:58', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/485-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('500', '1', '2013-01-28 11:07:36', '2013-01-27 23:07:36', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The BNZ landing page consists of variable sized content which slots together\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-512\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"When the content is clicked on it expands and fills the main part of the page\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-513\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There is a utility belt down the bottom which slides up to reveal tools like calculators\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-514\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There are also the banks rates which are updated live from an xml feed\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-515\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Youtube videos from their channel were also able to be embedded into the popups\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-516\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"As were exchange rates which also ran off a live XML feed\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-517\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The page could reshuffle the content to fit different screen sizes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-518\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"It could go down to a view suitable for tablets\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-519\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was our first digital project for BNZ and part of a wider brand refresh. The landing page was designed to bring the customer information about the bank in an innovative way worthy of a forward thinking bank.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework. It heavily implements Javascript and JQuery for its animations and layout calculations.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe biggest challenge by far was to implement a dynamic grid layout for the main content area and have modules expand open from there and animate back into place. If the was screen re sized the content needed to redraw to fit while retaining its hierarchy.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThe number of content modules, each ones shape, type and content was  determined by an XML feed. From that, i wrote a script that would build a multidimensional array as if it were a grid layout with either 2, 3 or 4 columns as determined by the screen width. It would then loop through the array reserving positions as necessary and fitting the modules into the next available space. Once the grid reference of each module was determined, the content was written to the DOM and positioned with X and Y coordinates. This script could actually work with basically any 4 sided rectangular shape and any screen size but it has been restricted to a maximum 4 column view and they only use 2x2, 1x2 and 1x1 shapes currently. 2 column is the minimum you can see on a destop or tablet, then the mobile version clicked down to a full width 1 column view with a few bespoke features.\r\n<h3>Mobile Version</h3>\r\n<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mobile site has its own bespoke layout to offer the tools relevant to the medium\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-520\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"It still showed the same content modules but in full width single file\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-521\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could also view the full article by clicking on the content item\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-522\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Contact us and Join us both triggered slide in panels from the left\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-523\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\nThe mobile version implemented sideways transitions between pages as is recommended UI for mobile devices from by Google. Clicking on the contact us, join us or content modules would slide in content from the left or right respectively. The mobile version also prioritized the menu into the things most wanted by mobile users like the contact information, internet banking login and mobile app. A full site button is also included as is best practice.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis has been very well received by both the public and by BNZ. It is the most complicated UI which I have built to date and it was an intense but rewarding process getting it across the finish line.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"BNZ Landing Page\" href=\"http://www.bnz.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.bnz.co.nz\r\n\r\n</a>', 'BNZ Landing Page', 'This was our first digital project for BNZ and part of a wider brand refresh. The landing page was designed to bring the customer information about the bank in an innovative way worthy of a forward thinking bank.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bnz-landing-page', '', '', '2013-02-28 12:56:29', '2013-02-28 00:56:29', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=500', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('501', '1', '2013-01-28 11:07:32', '2013-01-27 23:07:32', '<h3>Goals</h3>\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\n\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZ Landing Page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '500-revision', '', '', '2013-01-28 11:07:32', '2013-01-27 23:07:32', '', '500', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/500-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('550', '1', '2013-02-13 17:10:59', '2013-02-13 05:10:59', 'Vestibulum vel lorem nunc, in lobortis nunc. Class aptent taciti sociosqu ad litora torquent per conubia nostra, per inceptos himenaeos. In cursus iaculis rutrum. Integer at sapien et velit porta euismod. Sed at libero ligula. Sed viverra porttitor nisl ut vulputate. Nam ac volutpat risus. Integer pretium libero a quam aliquet in auctor diam ultricies.', 'Code in Action', 'This is the excerpt for the portfolio page which will end up being the facebook meta description', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '6-revision-14', '', '', '2013-02-13 17:10:59', '2013-02-13 05:10:59', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/6-revision-14/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('551', '1', '2013-01-14 21:12:54', '2013-01-14 09:12:54', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could watch the womens stories about breast cancer and leave comments\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-408\" alt=\"saveseven-screen2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then choose friends to share the video with via facebook or email\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-410\" alt=\"saveseven-screen4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could choose 7 women to share it with from facebook through my custom friend picker\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-411\" alt=\"saveseven-screen5\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The 7 women would then be displayed with their profile pictures\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-412\" alt=\"saveseven-screen6\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.', 'Save Seven', 'Seven women every day are diagnosed with Breast Cancer in New Zealand. Our mission was to encourage people to reach out to seven women they care about and spread the message of how early detection saves lives. This a won Gold Axis for best Charity campaign of 2011 ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '413-revision-12', '', '', '2013-01-14 21:12:54', '2013-01-14 09:12:54', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/413-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('553', '1', '2013-02-25 21:33:56', '2013-02-25 09:33:56', 'Vestibulum vel lorem nunc, in lobortis nunc. Class aptent taciti sociosqu ad litora torquent per conubia nostra, per inceptos himenaeos. In cursus iaculis rutrum. Integer at sapien et velit porta euismod. Sed at libero ligula. Sed viverra porttitor nisl ut vulputate. Nam ac volutpat risus. Integer pretium libero a quam aliquet in auctor diam ultricies.', 'Examples', 'This is the excerpt for the portfolio page which will end up being the facebook meta description', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '6-revision-15', '', '', '2013-02-25 21:33:56', '2013-02-25 09:33:56', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/6-revision-15/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('556', '1', '2013-02-27 08:39:34', '2013-02-26 20:39:34', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The Facebook tab app has a like gate to unlock content for fans only\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-474\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer 2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could log into their V Republic account while still in Facebook\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer-88.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-473\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer 88\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer-88-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"If they didnt have an account they could register while still in Facebook too\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer-89.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-472\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer 89\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer-89-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They had to try and guess what flavor combinations the new V Blue was to win $10,000\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-471\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer 91\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.', 'V Blue Facebook Tab', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '470-revision-8', '', '', '2013-02-27 08:39:34', '2013-02-26 20:39:34', '', '470', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/470-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('557', '1', '2013-01-08 17:53:27', '2013-01-08 05:53:27', 'Maecenas quis mauris sapien. Donec nunc tellus, pellentesque sit amet viverra a, ultrices nec ipsum. Duis ut egestas lectus. Mauris eu facilisis massa. Donec sodales gravida dignissim. Aenean varius sem vel diam fermentum eget dictum quam porta. Class aptent taciti sociosqu ad litora torquent per conubia nostra, per inceptos himenaeos. Maecenas pellentesque dui lorem, a scelerisque mi. Nam at felis nulla.', 'Welcome home', 'This is the excerpt for the home page which will end up being the facebook meta description', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-14', '', '', '2013-01-08 17:53:27', '2013-01-08 05:53:27', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-14/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('558', '1', '2013-02-27 08:46:08', '2013-02-26 20:46:08', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips. I\'ll be writing articles on things which I\'ve found useful, hard to find solutions to, custom solutions I\'ve made, or just anything i find interesting really.\r\n\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page and I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.', 'Welcome Home', 'This is the excerpt for the home page which will end up being the facebook meta description', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-15', '', '', '2013-02-27 08:46:08', '2013-02-26 20:46:08', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-15/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('559', '1', '2013-02-27 08:46:36', '2013-02-26 20:46:36', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips. I\'ll be writing articles on things which I\'ve found useful, hard to find solutions to, custom solutions I\'ve made, or just anything i find interesting really.\r\n\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page and I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.', 'Welcome Home', 'Geekspea