l lorem nunc, in lobortis nunc. Class aptent taciti sociosqu ad litora torquent per conubia nostra, per inceptos himenaeos. In cursus iaculis rutrum. Integer at sapien et velit porta euismod. Sed at libero ligula. Sed viverra porttitor nisl ut vulputate. Nam ac volutpat risus. Integer pretium libero a quam aliquet in auctor diam ultricies.\r\n\r\n[contact-form-7 id=\"56\" title=\"Submit a Question\"]', 'Submit a Question', 'This is the excerpt for the submit a question page which will end up being the facebook meta description', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '5-revision-11', '', '', '2013-01-12 20:26:44', '2013-01-12 08:26:44', '', '5', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/5-revision-11/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('562', '1', '2013-02-27 08:53:32', '2013-02-26 20:53:32', '<p>If you can\'t find what you\'re looking for or If you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message. I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any other queries or business you can email me here: <a href=\"mailto:craig.b.macgregor@gmail.com\" title=\"email me here\">craig.b.macgregor@gmail.com</a></p>\r\n\r\n[contact-form-7 id=\"56\" title=\"Submit a Question\"]', 'Submit a Question', 'This is the excerpt for the submit a question page which will end up being the facebook meta description', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '5-revision-12', '', '', '2013-02-27 08:53:32', '2013-02-26 20:53:32', '', '5', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/5-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('563', '1', '2013-02-27 08:38:33', '2013-02-26 20:38:33', 'Here are some real world examples of projects on which I\'ve used some of the skills I\'ve outlined in the my articles.', 'Examples', 'Here are some real world examples of projects on which I\'ve used some of the skills I\'ve outlined in the my articles on geekspeak.co.nz', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '6-revision-17', '', '', '2013-02-27 08:38:33', '2013-02-26 20:38:33', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/6-revision-17/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('564', '1', '2013-02-27 09:01:12', '2013-02-26 21:01:12', 'Here are some real world examples of projects on which I\'ve used some of the skills I\'ve outlined in the articles section.', 'Examples', 'Here are some real world examples of projects on which I\'ve used some of the skills I\'ve outlined in the my articles on geekspeak.co.nz', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '6-revision-18', '', '', '2013-02-27 09:01:12', '2013-02-26 21:01:12', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/6-revision-18/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('567', '1', '2013-02-27 12:23:51', '2013-02-27 00:23:51', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"By drinking Pepsi and redeeming codes, users could win a holiday with their mates\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-438\" alt=\"bromitment-screen1\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users allowed the facebook app and filled out their details to create a profile\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-439\" alt=\"bromitment-screen2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then select 3 friends they wanted to take on the holiday through the custom friend picker\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-440\" alt=\"bromitment-screen3\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The picked friends would then be messaged on facebook to ask them to join\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-441\" alt=\"bromitment-screen4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"All the users in the group could enter codes to boost their chances of winning\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen9.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-442\" alt=\"bromitment-screen9\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen9-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"If a user hadn\'t entered a code that day, the group leader could &quot;peer pressure&quot; them\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen10.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-443\" alt=\"bromitment-screen10\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen10-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users were &quot;peer pressured&quot; into entering codes by having one of our videos posted to their profile\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen11.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-444\" alt=\"bromitment-screen11\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen11-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The more codes your users entered per day gained you bonus entries\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen12.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-445\" alt=\"bromitment-screen12\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen12-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nPepsi Max Bromitment aimed to engage users to drink more Pepsi by getting users and their Bro\'s to make a commitment to each other. Teams were formed and entered product codes gave you points into the draw to win a holiday for you and your team.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook API and AMF.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge here for me was building the API and integrating it with the flash front end and making the communication secure. The game seemed simple enough but there was a lot of hidden twists which made some of the logic quite difficult.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWith smart class architecture I was able to minimize the amount of code written. Using a lot of smaller private functions rather than repeating code helped reduce the impact of functional changes or bug fixes. As with any competition, we encrypted the communication with a token so that it was much harder for someone to send requests directly to the API.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nBromitment was well executed from a design and development perspective, however I believe the mechanic itself was too convoluted for a lot of people to engage with.  It tried to take a pyramid scheme approach which meant that to be part of someone else\'s team, i have to create my own team with 3 other people. While this was supposed to help drive involvement i think it basically confused people as to where their codes were being applied and how the scheme worked.\r\n<h3>Notes</h3>\r\nThis was the the first full API I had written solo and despite not being hugely well received as a campaign, I was extremely happy with how the code ran.', 'Bromitment', 'Pepsi Max Bromitment aimed to engage users to drink more Pepsi by getting users and their Bro\'s to make a commitment to each other. Teams were formed and entered product codes gave you points into the draw to win a holiday for you and your team.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '426-revision-14', '', '', '2013-02-27 12:23:51', '2013-02-27 00:23:51', '', '426', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/426-revision-14/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('568', '1', '2013-01-13 22:07:34', '2013-01-13 10:07:34', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could take a picture using their webcam\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Webcam\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site used NEC facial recognition software to scan the users facial features\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Image Processing\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"NEC\'s results were used to pair the user with a dog from the SPCA\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Results\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could share their results on Facebook\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Share \" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.', 'Doggelganger', 'Doggelganger used security grade facial recognition software to match your face with a dog who is up for adoption from the SPCA animal shelter. Its won a Gold at Cannes, the Grand Axis award and many more.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '372-revision-18', '', '', '2013-01-13 22:07:34', '2013-01-13 10:07:34', '', '372', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/372-revision-18/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('569', '1', '2013-02-26 20:31:23', '2013-02-26 08:31:23', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could watch the womens stories about breast cancer and leave comments\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-408\" alt=\"saveseven-screen2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then choose friends to share the video with via facebook or email\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-410\" alt=\"saveseven-screen4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could choose 7 women to share it with from facebook through my custom friend picker\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-411\" alt=\"saveseven-screen5\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The 7 women would then be displayed with their profile pictures\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-412\" alt=\"saveseven-screen6\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to reach every woman in New Zealand with the message that early detection via breast screening is the best way to save the lives of the women we care about. The main driving force behind the online campaign was for users to watch the compelling stories of 7 quite different women who have beaten breast cancer and then share them on facebook with 7 women they care about.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThe main nav of the videos was built in flash while the rest of the site was built on top of the Zend Framework. The site uses the Youtube API for video events to trigger an overlay screen over the video. It also used the facebook API, Facebook Open Graph, JQuery and a bit of fancy HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nOne of the main challenges was to build a friend picker that deviated from the standard facebook functionality. We wanted to be able to only show the users friends who are listed as female on the facebook graph. We also wanted the  video to be posted the wall of the 7 women and make sure the audience is more relevant and also to help gain traction and visibility for the campaign.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThe standard facebook friend picker was not enough, it only sends out app invites rather than wall posts and could not be customized to show different data sets. After we had app permissions granted to look at the users friends list, used FQL and the Facebook PHP API to query graph and return all the users friends listed as Female. From that data set I was able to look up those users facebook IDs on the Open Graph and get their Name, Profile Picture and used these to build the layout of the custom friend picker. Although it has a different color scheme, we tried to make it as close to the native facebook friend picker in terms of functionality. You could select up to 7 friends, then when the user clicked send the facebook app would post the video they selected on the site to all the women they had selected which could be watched straight on the facebook news feed along with a link to the site.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nSave Seven had a great core idea and a unique way of spreading its message. The friend picker ended up being such a hit that I packaged it up to be added to our code library for future projects and it has been re purposed many times since it was built. Its always great to try something you haven\'t done before, especially when it works great and is for a great cause.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nSave Seven won a Gold Axis for best Charity Campaign at the Axis Awards in 2012 and has won a few awards overseas as well.', 'Save Seven', 'Seven women every day are diagnosed with Breast Cancer in New Zealand. Our mission was to encourage people to reach out to seven women they care about and spread the message of how early detection saves lives. This a won Gold Axis for best Charity campaign of 2011 ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '413-revision-14', '', '', '2013-02-26 20:31:23', '2013-02-26 08:31:23', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/413-revision-14/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('570', '1', '2013-01-13 22:12:35', '2013-01-13 10:12:35', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Comments made on facebook would appear on live TV.\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Ulive comments page\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could vote in polls which would be discussed by the presenters\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Ulive voting page \" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could stream Ulive from within the app\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Ulive streaming page\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could invite their friends to take part in the discussions\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Ulive invite page\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a Facebook app housed on the TVNZU page which allowed facebook users to watch the live show. It was to allow the users to get involved in the discussions the presenters were having and even get their comments to appear in real time on live TV. It was also to create a sense of community within the users friends by allowing them to invite their friends to watch the show and also display a list of which of your friends were currently tuned in via the app.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built on the Zend Framework and implements the Facebook API, JQuery, AJAX, a custom scroll bar JS library and of course HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was that discussion feed needed to have the same user experience as Facebook but the feed functionality isn\'t part of the Facebook API and it needed to poll the server to add new comments without refreshing. The app also had to integrate with the users friends list and keep a track of who was online so we could display if any of your friends were watching and also have an invite mechanic. There was also the archiving of old discussions and polls as well as the feed moderation for the comments that went to air and CMS for the app.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWe had to recreate the Facebook feed\'s functionality from scratch with the added ability to flag posts for moderator review. This became a very difficult task when there\'s so much integration. Every time we AJAX\'d in a new set of posts we had to bump the same number off the bottom so the pagination was intact while keeping their indexes for the likes and times all correct. We had to update the posts times, amount of likes and comment totals and then once everything was loaded, refresh the custom scroll bar height. The scroll lock button paused new comments from auto-updating which was also quite difficult to get working seamlessly.\r\n\r\nConnecting people with their friends was an important part of the app. We kept a database record of the Facebook ID\'s of everyone who logged into the app against a timestamp and if you\'d polled our server in the last 30 seconds we considered you to be in current use of the app. We then would look at the logged in users friends list and cross section that with the people who are currently logged in and display their profile picture and a link to their profile in a grid under the X Friends Watching heading. From here you could also invite your friends to watch the show through the Ulive app and this was done with the Facebook API\'s App Invite functionality.\r\n\r\nThe CMS was relatively straight forward, once a comment was approved to go to air it would be sent via a CURL request to an API at the TVNZ studio. This would then run through their system and be put up on the screen along with the users Name, Profile pic and Age which we got from their Facebook profile.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project turned out to be a great piece of programming. The integration of so many technologies ended up seeming pretty smooth despite having to do a lot of bug fixing and tying up loose ends. Integrating a Facebook app with a live TV show was a first for me and actually a world wide first which caught the attention of a lot of people in technology sphere.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis app was featured on the Facebook developer blog and was also featured on quite a few online newspapers and blogs.\r\n<h3>Additional</h3>\r\nThe site has undergone a design overhaul since we launched it back in 2010 but its still up and running: <a title=\"Ulive facebook app\" href=\"https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive/\" target=\"_blank\">https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive/</a>', 'Ulive', 'This project encompassed a wide range of web technologies. It was the first facebook app to allow users to interact with live television and was featured on facebook\'s developer blog.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '337-revision-34', '', '', '2013-01-13 22:12:35', '2013-01-13 10:12:35', '', '337', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/337-revision-34/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('626', '1', '2013-02-27 12:27:11', '2013-02-27 00:27:11', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could take a picture using their webcam\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Webcam\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site used NEC facial recognition software to scan the users facial features\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Image Processing\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"NEC\'s results were used to pair the user with a dog from the SPCA\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Results\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could share their results on Facebook\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Share \" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.', 'Doggelganger', 'Doggelganger used security grade facial recognition software to match your face with a dog who is up for adoption from the SPCA animal shelter. Its won a Gold at Cannes, the Grand Axis award and many more.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '372-revision-19', '', '', '2013-02-27 12:27:11', '2013-02-27 00:27:11', '', '372', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/372-revision-19/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('571', '1', '2013-01-16 20:21:23', '2013-01-16 08:21:23', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The homepage has a custom slideshow gallery and all the content is manageable\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-459\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0003_Background\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The menu featured a custom accordion style menu with sub sections\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-458\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer 74\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The map can find you by GPS and show the nearest BK or you could search\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-457\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer 75\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The contact form sends email directly to their customer service team\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-456\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer 78\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.', 'BK Brand Site', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '454-revision-9', '', '', '2013-01-16 20:21:23', '2013-01-16 08:21:23', '', '454', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/454-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('572', '1', '2013-01-28 11:06:18', '2013-01-27 23:06:18', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"#BNZgamechat was setup as a live alternative commentary for the Rugby World Cup\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-489\" alt=\"gamechat4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Our 5 alternate commentators would tweet about the All blacks games as they happened\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-488\" alt=\"gamechat3\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site changed format when viewed on a mobile or tablet\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-486\" alt=\"gamechat1\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Twitter users could hashtag #BNZgamechat and have their tweets show up on the side feed\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-487\" alt=\"gamechat2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZgamechat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '485-revision-7', '', '', '2013-01-28 11:06:18', '2013-01-27 23:06:18', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/485-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('573', '1', '2013-02-13 14:28:05', '2013-02-13 02:28:05', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The BNZ landing page consists of variable sized content which slots together\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-512\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-1\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"When the content is clicked on it expands and fills the main part of the page\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-513\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There is a utility belt down the bottom which slides up to reveal tools like calculators\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-514\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-3\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There are also the banks rates which are updated live from an xml feed\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-515\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Youtube videos from their channel were also able to be embedded into the popups\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-516\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-5\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"As were exchange rates which also ran off a live XML feed\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-517\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-6\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The page could reshuffle the content to fit different screen sizes\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-518\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-7\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"It could go down to a view suitable for tablets\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-519\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-8\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mobile site has its own bespoke layout to offer the tools relevant to the medium\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-520\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-1\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"It still showed the same content modules but in full width single file\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-521\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-2\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could also view the full article by clicking on the content item\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-522\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-3\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Contact us and Join us both triggered slide in panels from the left\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-523\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-4\" src=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZ Landing Page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '500-revision-6', '', '', '2013-02-13 14:28:05', '2013-02-13 02:28:05', '', '500', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/500-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('574', '1', '2013-02-25 21:21:12', '2013-02-25 09:21:12', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jp