 class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-522\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Contact us and Join us both triggered slide in panels from the left\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-523\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZ Landing Page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '500-revision-7', '', '', '2013-02-27 12:30:30', '2013-02-27 00:30:30', '', '500', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/500-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('576', '1', '2013-02-27 12:31:03', '2013-02-27 00:31:03', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'V Robbers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-8', '', '', '2013-02-27 12:31:03', '2013-02-27 00:31:03', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('586', '1', '2013-02-27 17:14:13', '2013-02-27 05:14:13', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 for prizes up for grabs it was important to stop any cheating.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nIll post the solutions to the security challenges once the campaign ends.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project is still running but is doing very well. The game is simple, challenging and addictive.\r\n<h3></h3>', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-10', '', '', '2013-02-27 17:14:13', '2013-02-27 05:14:13', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('577', '1', '2013-02-27 12:34:21', '2013-02-27 00:34:21', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The BNZ landing page consists of variable sized content which slots together\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-512\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"When the content is clicked on it expands and fills the main part of the page\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-513\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There is a utility belt down the bottom which slides up to reveal tools like calculators\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-514\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There are also the banks rates which are updated live from an xml feed\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-515\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div><div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Youtube videos from their channel were also able to be embedded into the popups\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-516\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"As were exchange rates which also ran off a live XML feed\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-517\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The page could reshuffle the content to fit different screen sizes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-518\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"It could go down to a view suitable for tablets\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-519\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mobile site has its own bespoke layout to offer the tools relevant to the medium\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-520\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"It still showed the same content modules but in full width single file\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-521\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could also view the full article by clicking on the content item\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-522\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Contact us and Join us both triggered slide in panels from the left\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-523\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau\r\n\r\n</div>', 'BNZ Landing Page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '500-revision-8', '', '', '2013-02-27 12:34:21', '2013-02-27 00:34:21', '', '500', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/500-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('582', '1', '2013-02-27 12:29:47', '2013-02-27 00:29:47', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"#BNZgamechat was setup as a live alternative commentary for the Rugby World Cup\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-489\" alt=\"gamechat4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Our 5 alternate commentators would tweet about the All blacks games as they happened\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-488\" alt=\"gamechat3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site changed format when viewed on a mobile or tablet\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-486\" alt=\"gamechat1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Twitter users could hashtag #BNZgamechat and have their tweets show up on the side feed\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-487\" alt=\"gamechat2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/gamechat2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first lau', 'BNZgamechat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '485-revision-8', '', '', '2013-02-27 12:29:47', '2013-02-27 00:29:47', '', '485', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/485-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('580', '1', '2013-02-27 14:48:48', '2013-02-27 02:48:48', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The Facebook tab app has a like gate to unlock content for fans only\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-474\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer 2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could log into their V Republic account while still in Facebook\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer-88.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-473\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer 88\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer-88-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"If they didnt have an account they could register while still in Facebook too\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer-89.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-472\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer 89\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer-89-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They had to try and guess what flavor combinations the new V Blue was to win $10,000\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-471\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer 91\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the facebook app product launch for the new blue flavor of V Energy drink. The main goal was to raise awareness of the new product by running a competition to give away $10,000 to anyone who guessed what the flavor was.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.', 'V Blue Facebook Tab', 'This was the facebook app product launch for the new blue flavor of V Energy drink. The main goal was to raise awareness of the new product by running a competition to give away $10,000 to anyone who guessed what the flavor was. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '470-revision-10', '', '', '2013-02-27 14:48:48', '2013-02-27 02:48:48', '', '470', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/470-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('589', '1', '2013-02-27 17:42:09', '2013-02-27 05:42:09', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. \r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nMake sure you dont use a 3 character short hand like #DDD or #888 for the filter property as this wont work as expected.\r\n\r\nIts important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.\r\n\r\nIn this case the gradient goes from # 71d09b at the top to #2e8b57 at the bottom.\r\n\r\nThis is the method which I\'ve used for my menu\'s and buttons on this site for example.', 'Cross browser CSS3 gradients', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cross-browser-css3-gradients', '', '', '2013-03-05 14:08:18', '2013-03-05 02:08:18', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=589', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('590', '1', '2013-02-27 17:41:19', '2013-02-27 05:41:19', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\n\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">background-color: #71d09b;\nbackground-image: url(../images/background-gradient.jpg);\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);</p>\nIts important to emember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color going on.', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision', '', '', '2013-02-27 17:41:19', '2013-02-27 05:41:19', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('591', '1', '2013-02-27 18:06:57', '2013-02-27 06:06:57', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\n\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\n[/sourcecode]\n\nIts important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.\n\nIn this case the gradi', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-autosave', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:06:57', '2013-02-27 06:06:57', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('592', '1', '2013-02-27 17:42:09', '2013-02-27 05:42:09', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">background-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);</p>\r\nIts important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-2', '', '', '2013-02-27 17:42:09', '2013-02-27 05:42:09', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('593', '1', '2013-02-27 17:59:10', '2013-02-27 05:59:10', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-3', '', '', '2013-02-27 17:59:10', '2013-02-27 05:59:10', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('597', '1', '2013-02-27 18:03:52', '2013-02-27 06:03:52', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;\">Its important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.</span></pre>', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-7', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:03:52', '2013-02-27 06:03:52', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('594', '1', '2013-02-27 18:02:19', '2013-02-27 06:02:19', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-4', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:02:19', '2013-02-27 06:02:19', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('595', '1', '2013-02-27 18:02:46', '2013-02-27 06:02:46', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n<pre>background-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;\">Its important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.</span></pre>', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-5', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:02:46', '2013-02-27 06:02:46', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('596', '1', '2013-02-27 18:03:20', '2013-02-27 06:03:20', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode]\r\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: 13px; line-height: 19px;\">Its important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.</span></pre>', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-6', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:03:20', '2013-02-27 06:03:20', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('598', '1', '2013-02-27 18:07:26', '2013-02-27 06:07:26', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.\r\n\r\nIn this case the gradient goes from # 71d09b at the top to #2e8b57 at the bottom.', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-8', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:07:26', '2013-02-27 06:07:26', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('600', '1', '2013-02-27 18:08:16', '2013-02-27 06:08:16', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.\r\n\r\nIn this case the gradient goes from # 71d09b at the top to #2e8b57 at the bottom.', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-9', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:08:16', '2013-02-27 06:08:16', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('601', '1', '2013-02-27 08:47:23', '2013-02-26 20:47:23', '<p>This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips. I\'ll be writing articles on things which I\'ve found useful, hard to find solutions to, custom solutions I\'ve made, or just anything i find interesting really.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page and I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.</p>', 'Welcome Home', 'Geekspeak is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-18', '', '', '2013-02-27 08:47:23', '2013-02-26 20:47:23', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-18/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('603', '1', '2013-02-27 18:19:15', '2013-02-27 06:19:15', 'Javascript timers are pretty useful for any web app which requires the client machine to poll the server for updates.\r\n\r\nInitializing a javascript timer is pretty straight forward.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nsetTimeout(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},1000);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis however will only trigger once, after the 1000ms delay. If you want to trigger something multiple times, use setInterval:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nsetInterval(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},1000);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe first argument is the function to run when the timer triggers and the second is the timer interval in milliseconds.\r\n\r\nThis will set the timer running but with this method you have no way to stop the timer. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also to separate the function from the initilaization.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nvar counter = 1;\r\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction,1000);\r\n\r\nfunction timerFunction(){\r\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\r\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\r\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\r\n     }else{\r\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\r\n          counter++;\r\n     }\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer after its logged to the console 5 times.\r\n\r\nThe timer is stopped with the clearInterval command, passing in the timer object as a variable in its first argument\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nclearInterval(myTimer);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember that in situations when you\'re polling the server for content updates not to run these too often if your server is expected to be busy or you will overload your server.', 'Javascript timers', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'javascript-timers', '', '', '2014-06-17 21:30:29', '2014-06-17 09:30:29', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=603', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('604', '1', '2013-02-27 18:18:23', '2013-02-27 06:18:23', 'Javascript timers are pretty useful for any web app which requires the client machine to poll the server for updates.\n\nInitializing a javascript timer is pretty straight forward.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\nsetInterval(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},5000);\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThis will set the timer running but with this method you have no way to stop the timer. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also break out the function so its separate to the initialization.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\nvar counter = 1;\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction(),5000);\n\nfunction timerFunction(){\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\n     }else{\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\n          counter++;\n     }\n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer ', 'Javascript timers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '603-revision', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:18:23', '2013-02-27 06:18:23', '', '603', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/603-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('605', '1', '2013-02-27 18:19:15', '2013-02-27 06:19:15', 'Javascript timers are pretty useful for any web app which requires the client machine to poll the server for updates.\r\n\r\nInitializing a javascript timer is pretty straight forward.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nsetInterval(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},5000);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis will set the timer running but with this method you have no way to stop the timer. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also break out the function so its separate to the initialization.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nvar counter = 1;\r\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction(),5000);\r\n\r\nfunction timerFunction(){\r\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\r\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\r\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\r\n     }else{\r\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\r\n          counter++;\r\n     }\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer after its logged to the console 5 times.\r\n\r\nIts important to remember that in situations when you\'re polling the server for content updates not to run these too often if your server is expected to be busy or you will overload your server.', 'Javascript timers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '603-revision-2', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:19:15', '2013-02-27 06:19:15', '', '603', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/603-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('606', '1', '2013-02-27 18:19:26', '2013-0