er. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also break out the function so its separate to the initialization.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nvar counter = 1;\r\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction(),5000);\r\n\r\nfunction timerFunction(){\r\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\r\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\r\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\r\n     }else{\r\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\r\n          counter++;\r\n     }\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer after its logged to the console 5 times.\r\n\r\nIts important to remember that in situations when you\'re polling the server for content updates not to run these too often if your server is expected to be busy or you will overload your server.', 'Javascript timers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '603-revision-5', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:21:11', '2013-02-27 06:21:11', '', '603', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/603-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('610', '1', '2013-02-27 18:25:41', '2013-02-27 06:25:41', 'Javascript timers are pretty useful for any web app which requires the client machine to poll the server for updates.\r\n\r\nInitializing a javascript timer is pretty straight forward.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nsetInterval(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},5000);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe first argument is the function to run when the timer triggers and the second is the timer interval in milliseconds.\r\n\r\nThis will set the timer running but with this method you have no way to stop the timer. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also to separate the function from the initilaization.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nvar counter = 1;\r\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction(),5000);\r\n\r\nfunction timerFunction(){\r\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\r\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\r\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\r\n     }else{\r\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\r\n          counter++;\r\n     }\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer after its logged to the console 5 times.\r\n\r\nIts important to remember that in situations when you\'re polling the server for content updates not to run these too often if your server is expected to be busy or you will overload your server.', 'Javascript timers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '603-revision-6', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:25:41', '2013-02-27 06:25:41', '', '603', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/603-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('611', '1', '2013-02-27 18:27:18', '2013-02-27 06:27:18', 'Javascript timers are pretty useful for any web app which requires the client machine to poll the server for updates.\r\n\r\nInitializing a javascript timer is pretty straight forward.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nsetInterval(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},5000);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe first argument is the function to run when the timer triggers and the second is the timer interval in milliseconds.\r\n\r\nThis will set the timer running but with this method you have no way to stop the timer. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also to separate the function from the initilaization.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nvar counter = 1;\r\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction(),5000);\r\n\r\nfunction timerFunction(){\r\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\r\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\r\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\r\n     }else{\r\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\r\n          counter++;\r\n     }\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe timer is stopped with the clearInterval command, passing in the timer object as a variable in its first argument\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nclearInterval(myTimer);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer after its logged to the console 5 times.\r\n\r\nIts important to remember that in situations when you\'re polling the server for content updates not to run these too often if your server is expected to be busy or you will overload your server.', 'Javascript timers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '603-revision-7', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:27:18', '2013-02-27 06:27:18', '', '603', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/603-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('612', '1', '2013-02-27 18:09:26', '2013-02-27 06:09:26', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. Some of these are for backwards compatibility with older browsers which dont support it at all.\r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.\r\n\r\nIn this case the gradient goes from # 71d09b at the top to #2e8b57 at the bottom.\r\n\r\nThis is the method which I\'ve used for my menu\'s and buttons on this site for example.', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-10', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:09:26', '2013-02-27 06:09:26', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('613', '1', '2013-02-27 18:10:38', '2013-02-27 06:10:38', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips. I\'ll be writing articles on things which I\'ve found useful, hard to find solutions to, custom solutions I\'ve made, or just anything i find interesting really.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page and I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.', 'Welcome to Geekspeak', 'Geekspeak is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-20', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:10:38', '2013-02-27 06:10:38', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-20/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('614', '1', '2013-02-28 12:06:52', '2013-02-28 00:06:52', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips. I\'ll be writing articles on things which I\'ve found useful, hard to find solutions to, custom solutions I\'ve made, code snippets or just anything i find interesting really.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nPlease bear with me while i start to build my article base.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page and I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.', 'Welcome to Geekspeak', 'Geekspeak is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks 