bnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 for prizes up for grabs it was important to stop any cheating.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nIll post the solutions to the security challenges once the campaign ends.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project is still running but is doing very well. The game is simple, challenging and addictive.\r\n\r\nwww.v.co.nz/vrobbery', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-12', '', '', '2013-02-28 12:53:40', '2013-02-28 00:53:40', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('622', '1', '2013-02-28 12:54:08', '2013-02-28 00:54:08', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 for prizes up for grabs it was important to stop any cheating.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nIll post the solutions to the security challenges once the campaign ends.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project is still running but is doing very well. The game is simple, challenging and addictive.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"V Robbers\" href=\"www.v.co.nz/vrobbery\" target=\"_blank\">www.v.co.nz/vrobbery\r\n\r\n</a>', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-13', '', '', '2013-02-28 12:54:08', '2013-02-28 00:54:08', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-13/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('623', '1', '2013-02-28 12:54:56', '2013-02-28 00:54:56', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 for prizes up for grabs it was important to stop any cheating.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nIll post the solutions to the security challenges once the campaign ends.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project is still running but is doing very well. The game is simple, challenging and addictive.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a style=\"font-size: 13px;\" title=\"V Robbers\" href=\"www.v.co.nz/vrobbery\" target=\"_blank\">www.v.co.nz/vrobbery</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-14', '', '', '2013-02-28 12:54:56', '2013-02-28 00:54:56', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-14/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('624', '1', '2013-02-27 16:44:13', '2013-02-27 04:44:13', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The BNZ landing page consists of variable sized content which slots together\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-512\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"When the content is clicked on it expands and fills the main part of the page\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-513\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There is a utility belt down the bottom which slides up to reveal tools like calculators\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-514\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There are also the banks rates which are updated live from an xml feed\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-515\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Youtube videos from their channel were also able to be embedded into the popups\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-516\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"As were exchange rates which also ran off a live XML feed\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-517\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The page could reshuffle the content to fit different screen sizes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-518\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"It could go down to a view suitable for tablets\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-519\" alt=\"bnz-landing-desktop-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-desktop-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was our first digital project for BNZ and part of a wider brand refresh. The landing page was designed to bring the customer information about the bank in an innovative way worthy of a forward thinking bank.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework. It heavily implements Javascript and JQuery for its animations and layout calculations.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe biggest challenge by far was to implement a dynamic grid layout for the main content area and have modules expand open from there and animate back into place. If the was screen re sized the content needed to redraw to fit while retaining its hierarchy.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThe number of content modules, each ones shape, type and content was  determined by an XML feed. From that, i wrote a script that would build a multidimensional array as if it were a grid layout with either 2, 3 or 4 columns as determined by the screen width. It would then loop through the array reserving positions as necessary and fitting the modules into the next available space. Once the grid reference of each module was determined, the content was written to the DOM and positioned with X and Y coordinates. This script could actually work with basically any 4 sided rectangular shape and any screen size but it has been restricted to a maximum 4 column view and they only use 2x2, 1x2 and 1x1 shapes currently. 2 column is the minimum you can see on a destop or tablet, then the mobile version clicked down to a full width 1 column view with a few bespoke features.\r\n<h3>Mobile Version</h3>\r\n<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mobile site has its own bespoke layout to offer the tools relevant to the medium\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-520\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"It still showed the same content modules but in full width single file\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-521\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could also view the full article by clicking on the content item\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-522\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Contact us and Join us both triggered slide in panels from the left\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery2\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-523\" alt=\"bnz-landing-mobile-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bnz-landing-mobile-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\nThe mobile version implemented sideways transitions between pages as is recommended UI for mobile devices from by Google. Clicking on the contact us, join us or content modules would slide in content from the left or right respectively. The mobile version also prioritized the menu into the things most wanted by mobile users like the contact information, internet banking login and mobile app. A full site button is also included as is best practice.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis has been very well received by both the public and by BNZ. It is the most complicated UI which I have built to date and it was an intense but rewarding process getting it across the finish line.', 'BNZ Landing Page', 'This was our first digital project for BNZ and part of a wider brand refresh. The landing page was designed to bring the customer information about the bank in an innovative way worthy of a forward thinking bank.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '500-revision-10', '', '', '2013-02-27 16:44:13', '2013-02-27 04:44:13', '', '500', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/500-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1022', '1', '2014-05-28 21:08:04', '2014-05-28 09:08:04', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could watch the womens stories about breast cancer and leave comments\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-408\" alt=\"saveseven-screen2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then choose friends to share the video with via facebook or email\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-410\" alt=\"saveseven-screen4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could choose 7 women to share it with from facebook through my custom friend picker\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-411\" alt=\"saveseven-screen5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The 7 women would then be displayed with their profile pictures\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-412\" alt=\"saveseven-screen6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to reach every woman in New Zealand with the message that early detection via breast screening is the best way to save the lives of the women we care about. The main driving force behind the online campaign was for users to watch the compelling stories of 7 quite different women who have beaten breast cancer and then share them on facebook with 7 women they care about.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThe main nav of the videos was built in flash while the rest of the site was built on top of the Zend Framework. The site uses the Youtube API for video events to trigger an overlay screen over the video. It also used the facebook API, Facebook Open Graph, JQuery and a bit of fancy HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nOne of the main challenges was to build a friend picker that deviated from the standard facebook functionality. We wanted to be able to only show the users friends who are listed as female on the facebook graph. We also wanted the  video to be posted the wall of the 7 women and make sure the audience is more relevant and also to help gain traction and visibility for the campaign.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThe standard facebook friend picker was not enough, it only sends out app invites rather than wall posts and could not be customized to show different data sets. After we had app permissions granted to look at the users friends list, used FQL and the Facebook PHP API to query graph and return all the users friends listed as Female. From that data set I was able to look up those users facebook IDs on the Open Graph and get their Name, Profile Picture and used these to build the layout of the custom friend picker. Although it has a different color scheme, we tried to make it as close to the native facebook friend picker in terms of functionality. You could select up to 7 friends, then when the user clicked send the facebook app would post the video they selected on the site to all the women they had selected which could be watched straight on the facebook news feed along with a link to the site.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nSave Seven had a great core idea and a unique way of spreading its message. The friend picker ended up being such a hit that I packaged it up to be added to our code library for future projects and it has been re purposed many times since it was built. Its always great to try something you haven\'t done before, especially when it works great and is for a great cause.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nSave Seven won a Gold Axis for best Charity Campaign at the Axis Awards in 2012 and has won a few awards overseas as well.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"Save Seven\" href=\"http://www.saveseven.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.saveseven.co.nz</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Save Seven', 'Seven women every day are diagnosed with Breast Cancer in New Zealand. Our mission was to encourage people to reach out to seven women they care about and spread the message of how early detection saves lives. This a won Gold Axis for best Charity campaign of 2011 ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '413-revision-17', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:08:04', '2014-05-28 09:08:04', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/413-revision-17/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('627', '1', '2013-02-27 12:27:35', '2013-02-27 00:27:35', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could watch the womens stories about breast cancer and leave comments\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-408\" alt=\"saveseven-screen2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then choose friends to share the video with via facebook or email\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-410\" alt=\"saveseven-screen4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could choose 7 women to share it with from facebook through my custom friend picker\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-411\" alt=\"saveseven-screen5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The 7 women would then be displayed with their profile pictures\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-412\" alt=\"saveseven-screen6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to reach every woman in New Zealand with the message that early detection via breast screening is the best way to save the lives of the women we care about. The main driving force behind the online campaign was for users to watch the compelling stories of 7 quite different women who have beaten breast cancer and then share them on facebook with 7 women they care about.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThe main nav of the videos was built in flash while the rest of the site was built on top of the Zend Framework. The site uses the Youtube API for video events to trigger an overlay screen over the video. It also used the facebook API, Facebook Open Graph, JQuery and a bit of fancy HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nOne of the main challenges was to build a friend picker that deviated from the standard facebook functionality. We wanted to be able to only show the users friends who are listed as female on the facebook graph. We also wanted the  video to be posted the wall of the 7 women and make sure the audience is more relevant and also to help gain traction and visibility for the campaign.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThe standard facebook friend picker was not enough, it only sends out app invites rather than wall posts and could not be customized to show different data sets. After we had app permissions granted to look at the users friends list, used FQL and the Facebook PHP API to query graph and return all the users friends listed as Female. From that data set I was able to look up those users facebook IDs on the Open Graph and get their Name, Profile Picture and used these to build the layout of the custom friend picker. Although it has a different color scheme, we tried to make it as close to the native facebook friend picker in terms of functionality. You could select up to 7 friends, then when the user clicked send the facebook app would post the video they selected on the site to all the women they had selected which could be watched straight on the facebook news feed along with a link to the site.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nSave Seven had a great core idea and a unique way of spreading its message. The friend picker ended up being such a hit that I packaged it up to be added to our code library for future projects and it has been re purposed many times since it was built. Its always great to try something you haven\'t done before, especially when it works great and is for a great cause.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nSave Seven won a Gold Axis for best Charity Campaign at the Axis Awards in 2012 and has won a few awards overseas as well.', 'Save Seven', 'Seven women every day are diagnosed with Breast Cancer in New Zealand. Our mission was to encourage people to reach out to seven women they care about and spread the message of how early detection saves lives. This a won Gold Axis for best Charity campaign of 2011 ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '413-revision-15', '', '', '2013-02-27 12:27:35', '2013-02-27 00:27:35', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/413-revision-15/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('628', '1', '2013-02-27 14:42:46', '2013-02-27 02:42:46', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The homepage has a custom slideshow gallery and all the content is manageable\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-459\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0003_Background\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The menu featured a custom accordion style menu with sub sections\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-458\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer 74\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The map can find you by GPS and show the nearest BK or you could search\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-457\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer 75\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The contact form sends email directly to their customer service team\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-456\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer 78\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis site was intended to give BK a more comprehensive online presence and bring their site up to date with some of the new web technologies.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with a comprehensive Content Management System. It also implements the Google Maps API and JQuery.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was the integration of the Google Maps into both the front end and the CMS. The Google Map had to show the user searched store locations and prioritize them in order of proximity to the user or the searched term.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nTo load the stores into the database I wrote a script to initialize the database entries automatically from an address list. This method worked with some but not all of the addresses, particularly those newer locations or ones in shopping complexes. We ended up coding a Google Map in the CMS which the admin could click on the map to record those latitude and longitude coordinates against that store. This proved to be the most useful way of getting the coordinates exact. Then using the latitude and longitude of the stores combined with either the users coordinates or the search terms coordinates we could use the Google Maps API to find the distance between the two points and then use that to order the returned results.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThe BK Brand site is a solid piece of code which was put together both efficiently and well. Its cross compatible with all modern browsers and can even read the GPS coordinates if you\'re on a smart phone to show you your nearest stores. As far as a fast food brand site goes, this is definitely up the times.', 'BK Brand Site', 'This site was intended to give BK a more comprehensive online presence and bring their site up to date with some of the new web technologies.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '454-revision-11', '', '', '2013-02-27 14:42:46', '2013-02-27 02:42:46', '', '454', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/454-revision-11/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('629', '1', '2013-03-01 09:42:14', '2013-02-28 21:42:14', 'Facebook meta tags are what Facebookuses to determine what to preview content to display on the Facebooknews feed about a particular URL. If you dont specify this, then Facebook will simply use the first image, first text and the title tag of the page to determine these and that is often not what we want to display.\r\n\r\nThe meta tags will be used if the user types your URL directly into their wall post, or if the user posts through the Facebook sharer utility for example:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Sharer\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz</a>\r\n\r\nThe main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory, lets look at some specifics of each\r\n<h3>og:url</h3>\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically if you use shared headers across your site. Usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php\r\nfunction getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n} ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n<h3>og:title</h3>\r\nThe title must be 1 - 99 characters long. Anything longer will get truncated to 99 characters.\r\n<h3>og:description</h3>\r\nThe description must be 121 - 300 characters long. Any shorter than 121 characters and it will not display at all. Any longer and it will get truncated to 300 characters.\r\n<h3>og:image</h3>\r\nFacebook requires that the image you use for this is 200x200 pixels. Dont forget to make this link absolute, relative paths here wont work.\r\n<h3>Additional info</h3>\r\nFacebook will not read any client side scripting when looking at these meta tags. For example, javascript redirects will not be executed, the page requested will be the page inspected unless you do redirects on a server level.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to check that your facebook meta data is pulling through properly, you can check it through facebooks debugging tool:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Debugger\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug\" target=\"_blank\">https://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug</a>\r\n\r\nSimply just type in the URL you\'re trying to inspect and press the button.\r\n\r\nSince facebook cache\'s meta data, this tool is also a handy way of clearing out the cached meta data.\r\n\r\nFacebook meta tags work for sharing URL\'s on linkedin.com as well, however i believe the image dimensions are different.', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'facebook-meta-tags', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:25:46', '2013-02-28 22:25:46', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=629', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('632', '1', '2013-03-01 09:40:16', '2013-02-28 21:40:16', '[sourcecode language=\"html\"]&lt;/pre&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.google.com&quot; /&gt;\n &lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $ogTitle; ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\n &lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $ogDescription; ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\n &lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php bloginfo(\'template_url\'); ?&gt;/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-3', '', '', '2013-03-01 09:40:16', '2013-02-28 21:40:16', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('630', '1', '2013-03-01 09:39:16', '2013-02-28 21:39:16', '[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\n&amp;lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&amp;lt;?php echo &quot;http://&quot;.$_SERVER[\'SERVER_NAME\'].$_SERVER[\'REQUEST_URI\']; ?&amp;gt;&quot; /&amp;gt;\n&amp;lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;&amp;lt;?php echo $ogTitle; ?&amp;gt;&quot; /&amp;gt;\n&amp;lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;&amp;lt;?php echo $ogDescription; ?&amp;gt;&quot; /&amp;gt;\n&amp;lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;&amp;lt;?php bloginfo(\'template_url\'); ?&amp;gt;/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&amp;gt;\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision', '', '', '2013-03-01 09:39:16', '2013-02-28 21:39:16', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('631', '1', '2013-03-01 09:39:26', '2013-02-28 21:39:26', '[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n&amp;lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&amp;lt;?php echo &quot;http://&quot;.$_SERVER[\'SERVER_NAME\'].$_SERVER[\'REQUEST_URI\']; ?&amp;gt;&quot; /&amp;gt;\r\n&amp;lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;&amp;lt;?php echo $ogTitle; ?&amp;gt;&quot; /&amp;gt;\r\n&amp;lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;&amp;lt;?php echo $ogDescription; ?&amp;gt;&quot; /&amp;gt;\r\n&amp;lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;&amp;lt;?php bloginfo(\'template_url\'); ?&amp;gt;/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&amp;gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-2', '', '', '2013-03-01 09:39:26', '2013-02-28 21:39:26', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('633', '1', '2013-03-01 09:41:18', '2013-02-28 21:41:18', '[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $ogTitle; ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $ogDescription; ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php bloginfo(\'template_url\'); ?&gt;/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-4', '', '', '2013-03-01 09:41:18', '2013-02-28 21:41:18', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('634', '1', '2013-03-01 10:26:51', '2013-02-28 22:26:51', 'Facebook meta tags are what Facebookuses to determine what to preview content to display on the Facebooknews feed about a particular URL. If you dont specify this, then Facebook will simply use the first image, first text and the title tag of the page to determine these and that is often not what we want to display.\n\nThe meta tags will be used if the user types your URL directly into their wall post, or if the user posts through the Facebook sharer utility for example:\n\n<a title=\"Facebook Sharer\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz</a>\n\nThe main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\n\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\n\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory, lets look at some specifics of each\n<h3>og:url</h3>\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\n\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically if you use shared headers across your site. Usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\n\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\n&lt;?php\nfunction getURL() {\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\n     }else{\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\n     }\n     return $pageURL;\n} ?&gt;\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\n<h3>og:title</h3>\nThe title must be 1 - 99 characters long. Anything longer will get truncated to 99 characters.\n<h3>og:description</h3>\nThe description must be 121 - 300 characters long. Any shorter than 121 characters and it will not display at all. Any longer and it will get truncated to 300 characters.\n<h3>og:image</h3>\nFacebook requires that the image you use for this is 200x200 pixels. Dont forget to make this link absolute, relative paths here wont work.\n<h3>Additional info</h3>\nFacebook will not read any client side scripting when looking at these meta tags. For example, javascript redirects will not be executed, the page requested will be the page inspected unless you do redirects on a server level.\n\nIf you would like to check that your facebook meta data is pulling through properly, you can check it through facebooks debugging tool:\n\n<a title=\"Facebook Debugger\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug\" target=\"_blank\">https://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug</a>\n\nSimply just type in the URL you\'re trying to inspect and press the button.\n\nSince facebook cache\'s meta data, this tool is also a handy way of clearing out the cached meta data.\n\nFacebook meta tags work for sharing URL\'s on linkedin.com as well, however i believe the image dimensions are different.', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-autosave', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:26:51', '2013-02-28 22:26:51', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('635', '1', '2013-03-01 09:42:14', '2013-02-28 21:42:14', '[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-5', '', '', '2013-03-01 09:42:14', '2013-02-28 21:42:14', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('636', '1', '2013-03-01 09:51:30', '2013-02-28 21:51:30', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\n\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\n\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory.\n\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\n\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically, the following script', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-6', '', '', '2013-03-01 09:51:30', '2013-02-28 21:51:30', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('637', '1', '2013-03-01 09:53:30', '2013-02-28 21:53:30', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\n\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\n\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory.\n\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\n\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically, usually i just use the following PHP script which is pretty simple\n\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\n&lt;?php echo &quot;http://&quot;.$_SERVER[\'SERVER_NAME\'].$_SERVER[\'REQUEST_URI\']; ?&gt;\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-7', '', '', '2013-03-01 09:53:30', '2013-02-28 21:53:30', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('645', '1', '2013-03-01 10:02:07', '2013-02-28 22:02:07', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory.\r\n\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically, usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo &quot; /&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;!--?php &lt;br ?--&gt;function getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n}\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n?&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-15', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:02:07', '2013-02-28 22:02:07', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-15/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('638', '1', '2013-03-01 09:59:59', '2013-02-28 21:59:59', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory.\r\n\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically, usually i just use the following PHP script which is pretty simple\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo &quot;http://&quot;.$_SERVER[\'SERVER_NAME\'].$_SERVER[\'REQUEST_URI\']; ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n&lt;?php\r\nfunction getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n}\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n?&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-8', '', '', '2013-03-01 09:59:59', '2013-02-28 21:59:59', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('639', '1', '2013-03-01 10:00:24', '2013-02-28 22:00:24', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /