://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;!--?php &lt;br ?--&gt;function getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n}\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n?&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-18', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:04:13', '2013-02-28 22:04:13', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-18/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('649', '1', '2013-03-01 10:05:00', '2013-02-28 22:05:00', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory.\r\n\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically, usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;!--?php &lt;br ?--&gt;function getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n}\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n?&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-19', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:05:00', '2013-02-28 22:05:00', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-19/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('650', '1', '2013-03-01 10:05:33', '2013-02-28 22:05:33', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory.\r\n\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically, usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php &lt;br /&gt;function getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n}\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n?&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-20', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:05:33', '2013-02-28 22:05:33', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-20/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('651', '1', '2013-03-01 10:05:55', '2013-02-28 22:05:55', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory.\r\n\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically, usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php function getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n}\r\n?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-21', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:05:55', '2013-02-28 22:05:55', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-21/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('652', '1', '2013-03-01 10:06:05', '2013-02-28 22:06:05', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory.\r\n\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically, usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php \r\nfunction getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n}\r\n?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-22', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:06:05', '2013-02-28 22:06:05', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-22/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('653', '1', '2013-03-01 10:06:18', '2013-02-28 22:06:18', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory.\r\n\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically, usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php \r\nfunction getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n} ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-23', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:06:18', '2013-02-28 22:06:18', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-23/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('654', '1', '2013-03-01 10:13:35', '2013-02-28 22:13:35', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory, lets look at some specifics of each\r\n<h3>og:url</h3>\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically if you use shared headers across your site. Usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php\r\nfunction getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n} ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIf you would like to check that your facebook meta data is pulling through properly, you can check it through facebooks debugging tool\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Debugger\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug\" target=\"_blank\">https://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug</a>\r\n\r\nSimply just type in the URL you\'re trying to inspect and press the button.\r\n\r\nSince facebook cache\'s meta data, this tool is also a handy way of clearing out the cached meta data.\r\n<h3>og:title</h3>\r\nThe title must be 1 - 99 characters long. Anything longer will get truncated to 99 characters.\r\n<h3>og:description</h3>\r\nThe description must be 121 - 300 characters long. Any shorter than 121 characters and it will not display at all. Any longer and it will get truncated to 300 characters.\r\n<h3>og:image</h3>\r\nFacebook requires that the image you use for this is 200x200 pixels. Dont forget to make this link absolute, relative paths here wont work.', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-24', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:13:35', '2013-02-28 22:13:35', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-24/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('655', '1', '2013-03-01 10:18:37', '2013-02-28 22:18:37', 'The main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory, lets look at some specifics of each\r\n<h3>og:url</h3>\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically if you use shared headers across your site. Usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php\r\nfunction getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n} ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n<h3>og:title</h3>\r\nThe title must be 1 - 99 characters long. Anything longer will get truncated to 99 characters.\r\n<h3>og:description</h3>\r\nThe description must be 121 - 300 characters long. Any shorter than 121 characters and it will not display at all. Any longer and it will get truncated to 300 characters.\r\n<h3>og:image</h3>\r\nFacebook requires that the image you use for this is 200x200 pixels. Dont forget to make this link absolute, relative paths here wont work.\r\n<h3>additional</h3>\r\nFacebook will not read any client side scripting when looking at these meta tags. For example, javascript redirects will not be executed, the page requested will be the page inspected unless you do redirects on a server level.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to check that your facebook meta data is pulling through properly, you can check it through facebooks debugging tool:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Debugger\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug\" target=\"_blank\">https://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug</a>\r\n\r\nSimply just type in the URL you\'re trying to inspect and press the button.\r\n\r\nSince facebook cache\'s meta data, this tool is also a handy way of clearing out the cached meta data.', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-25', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:18:37', '2013-02-28 22:18:37', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-25/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('656', '1', '2013-03-01 10:22:05', '2013-02-28 22:22:05', 'Facebook meta tags are what facebook uses to determine what to display on the facebook news feed about a particular URL.\r\n\r\nThese will be used if the user types your URL directly into their wall post, or if the user posts through the facebook sharer utility for example:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Sharer\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz\r\n\r\n</a>\r\n\r\nThe main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory, lets look at some specifics of each\r\n<h3>og:url</h3>\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically if you use shared headers across your site. Usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php\r\nfunction getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n} ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n<h3>og:title</h3>\r\nThe title must be 1 - 99 characters long. Anything longer will get truncated to 99 characters.\r\n<h3>og:description</h3>\r\nThe description must be 121 - 300 characters long. Any shorter than 121 characters and it will not display at all. Any longer and it will get truncated to 300 characters.\r\n<h3>og:image</h3>\r\nFacebook requires that the image you use for this is 200x200 pixels. Dont forget to make this link absolute, relative paths here wont work.\r\n<h3>additional</h3>\r\nFacebook will not read any client side scripting when looking at these meta tags. For example, javascript redirects will not be executed, the page requested will be the page inspected unless you do redirects on a server level.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to check that your facebook meta data is pulling through properly, you can check it through facebooks debugging tool:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Debugger\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug\" target=\"_blank\">https://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug</a>\r\n\r\nSimply just type in the URL you\'re trying to inspect and press the button.\r\n\r\nSince facebook cache\'s meta data, this tool is also a handy way of clearing out the cached meta data.\r\n\r\nFacebook meta tags work for sharing URL\'s on linkedin.com as well, however i believe the image dimensions are different.', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-26', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:22:05', '2013-02-28 22:22:05', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-26/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('657', '1', '2013-03-01 10:23:40', '2013-02-28 22:23:40', 'Facebook meta tags are what Facebookuses to determine what to preview content to display on the Facebooknews feed about a particular URL. If you dont specify this, then Facebook will simply use the first image, first text and the title tag of the page to determine these and that is often not what we want to display.\r\n\r\nThe meta tags will be used if the user types your URL directly into their wall post, or if the user posts through the Facebook sharer utility for example:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Sharer\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz\r\n\r\n</a>\r\n\r\nThe main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory, lets look at some specifics of each\r\n<h3>og:url</h3>\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically if you use shared headers across your site. Usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php\r\nfunction getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n} ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n<h3>og:title</h3>\r\nThe title must be 1 - 99 characters long. Anything longer will get truncated to 99 characters.\r\n<h3>og:description</h3>\r\nThe description must be 121 - 300 characters long. Any shorter than 121 characters and it will not display at all. Any longer and it will get truncated to 300 characters.\r\n<h3>og:image</h3>\r\nFacebook requires that the image you use for this is 200x200 pixels. Dont forget to make this link absolute, relative paths here wont work.\r\n<h3>additional</h3>\r\nFacebook will not read any client side scripting when looking at these meta tags. For example, javascript redirects will not be executed, the page requested will be the page inspected unless you do redirects on a server level.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to check that your facebook meta data is pulling through properly, you can check it through facebooks debugging tool:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Debugger\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug\" target=\"_blank\">https://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug</a>\r\n\r\nSimply just type in the URL you\'re trying to inspect and press the button.\r\n\r\nSince facebook cache\'s meta data, this tool is also a handy way of clearing out the cached meta data.\r\n\r\nFacebook meta tags work for sharing URL\'s on linkedin.com as well, however i believe the image dimensions are different.', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-27', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:23:40', '2013-02-28 22:23:40', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-27/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('658', '1', '2013-03-01 10:25:04', '2013-02-28 22:25:04', 'Facebook meta tags are what Facebookuses to determine what to preview content to display on the Facebooknews feed about a particular URL. If you dont specify this, then Facebook will simply use the first image, first text and the title tag of the page to determine these and that is often not what we want to display.\r\n\r\nThe meta tags will be used if the user types your URL directly into their wall post, or if the user posts through the Facebook sharer utility for example:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Sharer\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz\r\n\r\n</a>\r\n\r\nThe main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory, lets look at some specifics of each\r\n<h3>og:url</h3>\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically if you use shared headers across your site. Usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php\r\nfunction getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n} ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n<h3>og:title</h3>\r\nThe title must be 1 - 99 characters long. Anything longer will get truncated to 99 characters.\r\n<h3>og:description</h3>\r\nThe description must be 121 - 300 characters long. Any shorter than 121 characters and it will not display at all. Any longer and it will get truncated to 300 characters.\r\n<h3>og:image</h3>\r\nFacebook requires that the image you use for this is 200x200 pixels. Dont forget to make this link absolute, relative paths here wont work.\r\n<h3>additional</h3>\r\nFacebook will not read any client side scripting when looking at these meta tags. For example, javascript redirects will not be executed, the page requested will be the page inspected unless you do redirects on a server level.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to check that your facebook meta data is pulling through properly, you can check it through facebooks debugging tool:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Debugger\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug\" target=\"_blank\">https://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug</a>\r\n\r\nSimply just type in the URL you\'re trying to inspect and press the button.\r\n\r\nSince facebook cache\'s meta data, this tool is also a handy way of clearing out the cached meta data.\r\n\r\nFacebook meta tags work for sharing URL\'s on linkedin.com as well, however i believe the image dimensions are different.', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-28', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:25:04', '2013-02-28 22:25:04', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-28/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('659', '1', '2013-03-01 10:25:33', '2013-02-28 22:25:33', 'Facebook meta tags are what Facebookuses to determine what to preview content to display on the Facebooknews feed about a particular URL. If you dont specify this, then Facebook will simply use the first image, first text and the title tag of the page to determine these and that is often not what we want to display.\r\n\r\nThe meta tags will be used if the user types your URL directly into their wall post, or if the user posts through the Facebook sharer utility for example:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Sharer\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=www.geekspeak.co.nz</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe main 4 meta tags that you want to use are the following\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:title&quot; content=&quot;Welcome to my website&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:description&quot; content=&quot;This is my website where i post things&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:image&quot; content=&quot;http://www.mywebsite.com/images/facebook.jpg&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nWhat they do is pretty self explanatory, lets look at some specifics of each\r\n<h3>og:url</h3>\r\nIts recommended by facebook that you include the url even though it can be inferred by the request.\r\n\r\nYou may need to build the URL dynamically if you use shared headers across your site. Usually i usually use the following PHP script which is pretty simple:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php $pageURL = \'http://\'.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;]; ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta property=&quot;og:url&quot; content=&quot;&lt;?php echo $pageURL ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis should cover most cases. If your website switches between http &amp; https protocols or uses port numbers, you may need to use a more comprehensive script to build the url\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n&lt;?php\r\nfunction getURL() {\r\n     $pageURL = ($_SERVER[&quot;HTTPS&quot;] == &quot;on&quot;) ? \'http\' : \'https\';\r\n     $pageURL .= &quot;://&quot;;\r\n     if($_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;] != &quot;80&quot;) {\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].&quot;:&quot;.$_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_PORT&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }else{\r\n          $pageURL .= $_SERVER[&quot;SERVER_NAME&quot;].$_SERVER[&quot;REQUEST_URI&quot;];\r\n     }\r\n     return $pageURL;\r\n} ?&gt;\r\n&lt;meta content=&quot;&lt;?php echo getURL(); ?&gt;&quot; /&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n<h3>og:title</h3>\r\nThe title must be 1 - 99 characters long. Anything longer will get truncated to 99 characters.\r\n<h3>og:description</h3>\r\nThe description must be 121 - 300 characters long. Any shorter than 121 characters and it will not display at all. Any longer and it will get truncated to 300 characters.\r\n<h3>og:image</h3>\r\nFacebook requires that the image you use for this is 200x200 pixels. Dont forget to make this link absolute, relative paths here wont work.\r\n<h3>Additional info</h3>\r\nFacebook will not read any client side scripting when looking at these meta tags. For example, javascript redirects will not be executed, the page requested will be the page inspected unless you do redirects on a server level.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to check that your facebook meta data is pulling through properly, you can check it through facebooks debugging tool:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Facebook Debugger\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug\" target=\"_blank\">https://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug</a>\r\n\r\nSimply just type in the URL you\'re trying to inspect and press the button.\r\n\r\nSince facebook cache\'s meta data, this tool is also a handy way of clearing out the cached meta data.\r\n\r\nFacebook meta tags work for sharing URL\'s on linkedin.com as well, however i believe the image dimensions are different.', 'Facebook meta tags', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '629-revision-29', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:25:33', '2013-02-28 22:25:33', '', '629', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/629-revision-29/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('661', '1', '2013-03-01 10:30:17', '2013-02-28 22:30:17', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips I\'ve learned along my journey. I\'ll be trying to cover a broad spectrum from the basics to the complex and everything in between.\r\n\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page and I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.', 'Welcome to Geek Speak', 'Geekspeak is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-27', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:30:17', '2013-02-28 22:30:17', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-27/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('662', '1', '2013-02-28 09:52:12', '2013-02-27 21:52:12', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. \r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.\r\n\r\nIn this case the gradient goes from # 71d09b at the top to #2e8b57 at the bottom.\r\n\r\nThis is the method which I\'ve used for my menu\'s and buttons on this site for example.', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-11', '', '', '2013-02-28 09:52:12', '2013-02-27 21:52:12', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-11/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('663', '1', '2013-03-02 13:36:01', '2013-03-02 01:36:01', 'If you\'re having problems with max-width or max-height not working properly in IE, make sure that you have the correct doctype set in the head of your document.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThese CSS proerties will only work with a Strict doctype, transitional or any other type will not work.\r\n\r\nAlso make sure that you\'re using it on a valid HTML entity.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the documentation from Microsoft.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Max Width Documentation\" href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx\" target=\"_blank\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx</a>', 'Internet Explorer and max-width', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'internet-explorer-and-max-width', '', '', '2013-03-07 09:00:58', '2013-03-06 21:00:58', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=663', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('664', '1', '2013-03-02 13:35:14', '2013-03-02 01:35:14', 'If you\'re having problems with max-width or max-height not working properly in IE, make sure that you have the correct doctype set in the head of your document.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"][/sourcecode]\n<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC \"-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict //EN\">\n[/source]\n\nIt will only work with a Strict doctype, transitional or any other type will not work.\n\nAlso make sure that you\'re using it on a valid HTML entity ', 'max-width in Internet Explorer', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '663-revision', '', '', '2013-03-02 13:35:14', '2013-03-02 01:35:14', '', '663', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/663-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('665', '1', '2013-03-02 13:36:01', '2013-03-02 01:36:01', 'If you\'re having problems with max-width or max-height not working properly in IE, make sure that you have the correct doctype set in the head of your document.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"][/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n[/source]\r\n\r\nIt will only work with a Strict doctype, transitional or any other type will not work.\r\n\r\nAlso make sure that you\'re using it on a valid HTML entity.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the documentation from Microsoft.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Max Width Documentation\" href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx\" target=\"_blank\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx\r\n\r\n</a>', 'max-width in Internet Explorer', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '663-revision-2', '', '', '2013-03-02 13:36:01', '2013-03-02 01:36:01', '', '663', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/663-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('666', '1', '2013-03-02 13:36:40', '2013-03-02 01:36:40', 'If you\'re having problems with max-width or max-height not working properly in IE, make sure that you have the correct doctype set in the head of your document.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict //EN&quot;&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIt will only work with a Strict doctype, transitional or any other type will not work.\r\n\r\nAlso make sure that you\'re using it on a valid HTML entity.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the documentation from Microsoft.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Max Width Documentation\" href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx\" target=\"_blank\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'max-width in Internet Explorer', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '663-revision-3', '', '', '2013-03-02 13:36:40', '2013-03-02 01:36:40', '', '663', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/663-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('667', '1', '2013-03-07 09:00:55', '2013-03-06 21:00:55', 'If you\'re having problems with max-width or max-height not working properly in IE, make sure that you have the correct doctype set in the head of your document.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThese CSS proerties will only work with a Strict doctype, transitional or any other type will not work.\n\nAlso make sure that you\'re using it on a valid HTML entity.\n\nHere\'s the documentation from Microsoft.\n\n<a title=\"Max Width Documentation\" href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx\" target=\"_blank\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx</a>', 'Internet Explorer and max-width', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '663-autosave', '', '', '2013-03-07 09:00:55', '2013-03-06 21:00:55', '', '663', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/663-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('668', '1', '2013-03-02 18:07:39', '2013-03-02 06:07:39', 'Often Internet Explorer requires extra CSS to get it looking nice in all of the versions. Unfortunately IE is often the default install for corporates and the older versions still need to be taken into account. I usually try and make my site look perfect in IE8 &amp; IE9 and just functional in IE7 with a message advising the users they need to upgrade for an optimal experience.\r\n\r\nConditional CSS style sheets are a good way to apply extra styles on top of what you\'ve already written to account for some of IE\'s flaws.\r\n\r\nI usually use the this script in the head of my html file to add my style sheets in\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\n&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/main.css&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if IE]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if IE 8]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie8.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if lte IE 7]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie7.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo basically, this script will apply your main styles, then in descending order styles for all of IE, then IE 8 only, then IE7 and below. With CSS, the last style which is read is the final one which is applied, so its important to put these in the correct order or else you\'ll not override the styles correctly.\r\n\r\nThe reason its good to do it in this order is that most of the things you fix for IE9 will also fix a lot of problems in IE7 &amp; IE8, so its good to have a general IE sheet in there right after you main CSS. Then we have fixes especially for IE8 which are usually pretty minimal as its quite similar to IE9. Then we put in a catch all for IE7 and below which includes the styles for the warning message advising the user to upgrade their browser.\r\n\r\nSome switches can be used in the brackets:\r\n\r\nlt = Less than eg. [if lt IE 9]\r\nlte = Less than or equal to eg. [if lte IE 7]\r\ngt = Greater than eg. [if gt IE 6]\r\ngte = Greater than or equal to eg. [if gte IE 8]\r\n! = not eg. [if !IE]', 'Conditional CSS style sheets', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'conditional-css-style-sheets', '', '', '2013-03-05 14:07:28', '2013-03-05 02:07:28', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=668', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('669', '1', '2013-03-02 17:55:16', '2013-03-02 05:55:16', 'Often Internet Explorer requires extra CSS to get it looking nice in all of the versions. Unfortunately IE is often the default install for corporates and the older versions still need to be taken into account. I usually try and make my site look perfect in IE8 &amp; IE9 and functional', 'Conditional Style Sheets', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '668-revision', '', '', '2013-03-02 17:55:16', '2013-03-02 05:55:16', '', '668', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/668-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('670', '1', '2013-03-02 17:56:16', '2013-03-02 05:56:16', 'Often Internet Explorer requires extra CSS to get it looking nice in all of the versions. Unfortunately IE is often the default install for corporates and the older versions still need to be taken into account. I usually try and make my site look perfect in IE8 &amp; IE9 and just functional in IE7 with a message advising the users they need to upgrade for an optimal experience.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Conditional Style Sheets', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '668-revision-2', '', '', '2013-03-02 17:56:16', '2013-03-02 05:56:16', '', '668', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/668-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('671', '1', '2013-03-02 18:06:55', '2013-03-02 06:06:55', 'Often Internet Explorer requires extra CSS to get it looking nice in all of the versions. Unfortunately IE is often the default install for corporates and the older versions still need to be taken into account. I usually try and make my site look perfect in IE8 &amp; IE9 and just functional in IE7 with a message advising the users they need to upgrade for an optimal experience.\r\n\r\nConditional CSS style sheets are a good way to apply extra styles on top of what you\'ve already written to account for some of IE\'s flaws.\r\n\r\nI usually use the this script in the head of my html file to add my style sheets in\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\n&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/main.css&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if IE]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if IE 8]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie8.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if lte IE 7]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie7.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo basically, this script will apply your main styles, then in descending order styles for all of IE, then IE 8 only, then IE7 and below.\r\n\r\nThe reason its good to do it in this order is that most of the things you fix for IE9 will also fix a lot of problems in IE7 &amp; IE8, so its good to have a general IE sheet in there right after you main CSS. Then we have fixes especially for IE8 which are usually pretty minimal as its quite similar to IE9. Then we put in a catch all for IE7 and below which includes the styles for the warning message advising the user to upgrade their browser.\r\n\r\nSome switches can be used in the brackets:\r\n\r\nlt = Less than eg. [if lt IE 9]\r\nlte = Less than or equal to eg. [if lte IE 7]\r\ngt = Greater than eg. [if gt IE 6]\r\ngte = Greater than or equal to eg. [if gte IE 8]\r\n! = not eg. [if !IE]', 'Conditional CSS Style Sheets', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '668-revision-3', '', '', '2013-03-