hich includes the styles for the warning message advising the user to upgrade their browser.\n\nSome switches can be used in the brackets:\n\nlt = Less than eg. [if lt IE 9]\nlte = Less than or equal to eg. [if lte IE 7]\ngt = Greater than eg. [if gt IE 6]\ngte = Greater than or equal to eg. [if gte IE 8]\n! = not eg. [if !IE]', 'Conditional CSS Style Sheets', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '668-autosave', '', '', '2013-03-02 18:10:44', '2013-03-02 06:10:44', '', '668', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/668-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('673', '1', '2013-03-02 18:07:39', '2013-03-02 06:07:39', 'Often Internet Explorer requires extra CSS to get it looking nice in all of the versions. Unfortunately IE is often the default install for corporates and the older versions still need to be taken into account. I usually try and make my site look perfect in IE8 &amp; IE9 and just functional in IE7 with a message advising the users they need to upgrade for an optimal experience.\r\n\r\nConditional CSS style sheets are a good way to apply extra styles on top of what you\'ve already written to account for some of IE\'s flaws.\r\n\r\nI usually use the this script in the head of my html file to add my style sheets in\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\n&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/main.css&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if IE]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if IE 8]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie8.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if lte IE 7]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie7.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo basically, this script will apply your main styles, then in descending order styles for all of IE, then IE 8 only, then IE7 and below.\r\n\r\nThe reason its good to do it in this order is that most of the things you fix for IE9 will also fix a lot of problems in IE7 &amp; IE8, so its good to have a general IE sheet in there right after you main CSS. Then we have fixes especially for IE8 which are usually pretty minimal as its quite similar to IE9. Then we put in a catch all for IE7 and below which includes the styles for the warning message advising the user to upgrade their browser.\r\n\r\nSome switches can be used in the brackets:\r\n\r\nlt = Less than eg. [if lt IE 9]\r\nlte = Less than or equal to eg. [if lte IE 7]\r\ngt = Greater than eg. [if gt IE 6]\r\ngte = Greater than or equal to eg. [if gte IE 8]\r\n! = not eg. [if !IE]', 'Conditional CSS Style Sheets', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '668-revision-4', '', '', '2013-03-02 18:07:39', '2013-03-02 06:07:39', '', '668', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/668-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('674', '1', '2013-03-01 10:30:46', '2013-02-28 22:30:46', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips I\'ve learned along my journey. I\'ll be trying to cover a broad spectrum from the basics to the complex and everything in between.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page and I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.', 'Welcome to Geek Speak', 'Geekspeak is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-28', '', '', '2013-03-01 10:30:46', '2013-02-28 22:30:46', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-28/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('675', '1', '2013-03-02 18:12:43', '2013-03-02 06:12:43', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips I\'ve learned along my journey. I\'ll be trying to cover a broad spectrum from the basics to the complex and everything in between.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page and I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.', 'Welcome to Geek Speak', 'Geekspeak is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-29', '', '', '2013-03-02 18:12:43', '2013-03-02 06:12:43', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-29/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('676', '1', '2013-03-02 18:12:58', '2013-03-02 06:12:58', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips I\'ve learned along my journey. I\'ll be trying to cover a broad spectrum from the basics to the complex and everything in between.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page and I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.', 'Welcome to Geek Speak', 'Geek Speak is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-30', '', '', '2013-03-02 18:12:58', '2013-03-02 06:12:58', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-30/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('795', '1', '2013-08-12 19:24:48', '2013-08-12 07:24:48', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\">\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could choose your avatar for the queue and it would put your facebook profile picture on as the head.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your queue position was determined by your social influence i.e. shares, likes, comments, re-tweets etc.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Each day new content was revealed to share on facebook and twitter\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\">\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The content consisted of different types of media\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There were even quizzes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-15', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:24:48', '2013-08-12 07:24:48', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-15/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('793', '1', '2013-08-12 19:23:22', '2013-08-12 07:23:22', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could choose your avatar for the queue and it would put your facebook profile picture on as the head.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your queue position was determined by your social influence i.e. shares, likes, comments, re-tweets etc.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Each day new content was revealed to share on facebook and twitter\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The content consisted of different types of media\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There were even quizzes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-13', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:23:22', '2013-08-12 07:23:22', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-13/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('797', '1', '2013-08-12 19:25:45', '2013-08-12 07:25:45', '<div class=\"gallery\"><div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads