nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-16', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:25:23', '2013-08-12 07:25:23', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-16/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('794', '1', '2013-08-12 19:24:06', '2013-08-12 07:24:06', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\">\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could choose your avatar for the queue and it would put your facebook profile picture on as the head.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your queue position was determined by your social influence i.e. shares, likes, comments, re-tweets etc.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Each day new content was revealed to share on facebook and twitter\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\">\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The content consisted of different types of media\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There were even quizzes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-14', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:24:06', '2013-08-12 07:24:06', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-14/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('792', '1', '2013-08-12 19:17:13', '2013-08-12 07:17:13', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>/div&gt;\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-12', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:17:13', '2013-08-12 07:17:13', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('790', '1', '2013-08-12 19:12:37', '2013-08-12 07:12:37', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-10', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:12:37', '2013-08-12 07:12:37', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('691', '1', '2013-03-02 18:10:58', '2013-03-02 06:10:58', 'Often Internet Explorer requires extra CSS to get it looking nice in all of the versions. Unfortunately IE is often the default install for corporates and the older versions still need to be taken into account. I usually try and make my site look perfect in IE8 &amp; IE9 and just functional in IE7 with a message advising the users they need to upgrade for an optimal experience.\r\n\r\nConditional CSS style sheets are a good way to apply extra styles on top of what you\'ve already written to account for some of IE\'s flaws.\r\n\r\nI usually use the this script in the head of my html file to add my style sheets in\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\n&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/main.css&quot; /&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if IE]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if IE 8]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie8.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n&lt;!--[if lte IE 7]&gt;&lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;css/ie7.css&quot; /&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo basically, this script will apply your main styles, then in descending order styles for all of IE, then IE 8 only, then IE7 and below. With CSS, the last style which is read is the final one which is applied, so its important to put these in the correct order or else you\'ll not override the styles correctly.\r\n\r\nThe reason its good to do it in this order is that most of the things you fix for IE9 will also fix a lot of problems in IE7 &amp; IE8, so its good to have a general IE sheet in there right after you main CSS. Then we have fixes especially for IE8 which are usually pretty minimal as its quite similar to IE9. Then we put in a catch all for IE7 and below which includes the styles for the warning message advising the user to upgrade their browser.\r\n\r\nSome switches can be used in the brackets:\r\n\r\nlt = Less than eg. [if lt IE 9]\r\nlte = Less than or equal to eg. [if lte IE 7]\r\ngt = Greater than eg. [if gt IE 6]\r\ngte = Greater than or equal to eg. [if gte IE 8]\r\n! = not eg. [if !IE]', 'Conditional CSS Style Sheets', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '668-revision-5', '', '', '2013-03-02 18:10:58', '2013-03-02 06:10:58', '', '668', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/668-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('692', '1', '2013-03-02 13:37:07', '2013-03-02 01:37:07', 'If you\'re having problems with max-width or max-height not working properly in IE, make sure that you have the correct doctype set in the head of your document.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict //EN&quot;&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThese CSS proerties will only work with a Strict doctype, transitional or any other type will not work.\r\n\r\nAlso make sure that you\'re using it on a valid HTML entity.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the documentation from Microsoft.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Max Width Documentation\" href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx\" target=\"_blank\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx</a>', 'max-width in Internet Explorer', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '663-revision-4', '', '', '2013-03-02 13:37:07', '2013-03-02 01:37:07', '', '663', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/663-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('693', '1', '2013-03-02 13:30:56', '2013-03-02 01:30:56', 'Due to CSS3 not being an unified browser standard yet, multiple lines are required to account for all cases. \r\n\r\nHere\'s an example of how to make your background gradients cross browser compatible:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\r\nbackground-color: #71d09b;\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#71d09b), to(#2e8b57));\r\nbackground-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nbackground-image: linear-gradient(top, #71d09b, #2e8b57);\r\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#71d09b, endColorstr=#2e8b57);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nMake sure you dont use a 3 character short hand like #DDD or #888 for the filter property as this wont work as expected.\r\n\r\nIts important to remember to set a background color so that if all else fails, at least you\'ve got the right base color there.\r\n\r\nIn this case the gradient goes from # 71d09b at the top to #2e8b57 at the bottom.\r\n\r\nThis is the method which I\'ve used for my menu\'s and buttons on this site for example.', 'Cross Browser CSS3 Gradients', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-12', '', '', '2013-03-02 13:30:56', '2013-03-02 01:30:56', '', '589', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/589-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('694', '1', '2013-03-05 14:08:05', '2013-03-05 02:08:05', 'If you\'re having problems with max-width or max-height not working properly in IE, make sure that you have the correct doctype set in the head of your document.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict //EN&quot;&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThese CSS proerties will only work with a Strict doctype, transitional or any other type will not work.\r\n\r\nAlso make sure that you\'re using it on a valid HTML entity.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the documentation from Microsoft.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Max Width Documentation\" href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx\" target=\"_blank\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx</a>', 'Internet Explorer and max-width', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '663-revision-5', '', '', '2013-03-05 14:08:05', '2013-03-05 02:08:05', '', '663', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/663-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('745', '1', '2013-02-28 12:55:09', '2013-02-28 00:55:09', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 for prizes up for grabs it was important to stop any cheating.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nIll post the solutions to the security challenges once the campaign ends.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project is still running but is doing very well. The game is simple, challenging and addictive.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a style=\"font-size: 13px;\" title=\"V Robbers\" href=\"www.v.co.nz/vrobbery\" target=\"_blank\">www.v.co.nz/vrobbery</a>', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-15', '', '', '2013-02-28 12:55:09', '2013-02-28 00:55:09', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-15/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('801', '1', '2013-08-12 19:41:53', '2013-08-12 07:41:53', 'The JS SDK for facebook launches the login screen as a popup window and not a modal frame. This means that in some browsers if the user has popups blocked, the window will never show. Safari for example doesn\'t even display a message to say it blocked a popup if you have the blocker turned on. This is a major problem, especially for mobile users whom it seems to haphazardly effect on various browsers, no matter what their popup blocker settings are.\r\n\r\nThe best way around this is to detect if the user is on moblie and use the PHP SDK for login if they are. It gives the same user journey as the popup on mobile since the browser tabs are always full screen but since its redirecting within the same window, it doesnt trigger the popup blocker.\r\n\r\nLogging in with the PHP SDK and then trying to interact with the JS SDKs FB.ui features used to be a real nightmare. Even when you had cookies enabled, the session never really seemed to share properly and I\'d always have to write custom scripts to read and write the token to the cookie manually. If you\'re having this problem, try upgrading your PHP SDK to version 3. All the bugs to do with sharing the logged in session between the client and the server seem to be resolved in this version.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re worried about it happening on desktop as well, you could implement a javascript timer which will instruct the user to turn off their popup blocker if you didn\'t get the callback from the login window within a certain time frame. Or you could present a custom popup which has a link that would log them in with the PHP SDK if you dont want the user to have to tinker with their browser settings.', 'Facebook login popup never appearing', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '798-revision-2', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:41:53', '2013-08-12 07:41:53', '', '798', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/798-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('802', '1', '2013-08-12 19:46:30', '2013-08-12 07:46:30', 'The JS SDK for facebook launches the login screen as a popup window and not a modal frame. This means that in some browsers if the user has popups blocked, the window will never show. Safari for example doesn\'t even display a message to say it blocked a popup if you have the blocker turned on. This is a major problem, especially for mobile users whom it seems to haphazardly effect on various browsers, no matter what their popup blocker settings are.\r\n\r\nThe best way around this is to detect if the user is on moblie and use the PHP SDK for login if they are. It gives the same user journey as the popup on mobile since the browser tabs are always full screen but since its redirecting within the same window, it doesnt trigger the popup blocker.\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n require_once(\'facebook.php\');\r\n\r\n  $config = array();\r\n  $config[\'appId\'] = \'YOUR_APP_ID\';\r\n  $config[\'secret\'] = \'YOUR_APP_SECRET\';\r\n  $config[\'cookie\'] = true;\r\n  $facebook = new Facebook($config);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\nLogging in with the PHP SDK and then trying to interact with the JS SDKs FB.ui features used to be a real nightmare. Even when you had cookies enabled, the session never really seemed to share properly and I\'d always have to write custom scripts to read and write the token to the cookie manually. If you\'re having this problem, try upgrading your PHP SDK to version 3. All the bugs to do with sharing the logged in session between the client and the server seem to be resolved in this version.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re worried about it happening on desktop as well, you could implement a javascript timer which will instruct the user to turn off their popup blocker if you didn\'t get the callback from the login window within a certain time frame. Or you could present a custom popup which has a link that would log them in with the PHP SDK if you dont want the user to have to tinker with their browser settings.', 'Facebook login popup never appearing', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '798-revision-3', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:46:30', '2013-08-12 07:46:30', '', '798', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/798-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('789', '1', '2013-08-12 19:11:13', '2013-08-12 07:11:13', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div><div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-9', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:11:13', '2013-08-12 07:11:13', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('791', '1', '2013-08-12 19:16:22', '2013-08-12 07:16:22', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>/div&gt;\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-11', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:16:22', '2013-08-12 07:16:22', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-11/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('788', '1', '2013-08-12 19:10:38', '2013-08-12 07:10:38', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a 