/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-5', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:00:46', '2013-08-12 07:00:46', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('784', '1', '2013-08-12 19:07:35', '2013-08-12 07:07:35', '', 'feature', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'feature', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:07:35', '2013-08-12 07:07:35', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/feature.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('785', '1', '2013-08-12 19:02:05', '2013-08-12 07:02:05', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-6', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:02:05', '2013-08-12 07:02:05', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('786', '1', '2014-06-23 08:53:22', '2014-06-22 20:53:22', '<div class=\"gallery\">\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could choose your avatar for the queue and it would put your facebook profile picture on as the head.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your queue position was determined by your social influence i.e. shares, likes, comments, re-tweets etc.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Each day new content was revealed to share on facebook and twitter\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The content consisted of different types of media\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There were even quizzes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<h3>Goals</h3>\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\n<h3>Awards</h3>\nFacebook Studio 2014: Silver\n\nAxis 2014:  Grand Prix - Out of home,  Gold - Digital and Interactive, Gold - Integrated, Silver - Social\n\nCannes 2014: Bronze Lion - Digital', 'The Smart Phoneline', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-autosave', '', '', '2014-06-23 08:53:22', '2014-06-22 20:53:22', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('773', '1', '2013-08-12 18:56:43', '2013-08-12 06:56:43', '', 'gs4_0000', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gs4_0000', '', '', '2013-08-12 18:56:43', '2013-08-12 06:56:43', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('774', '1', '2013-08-12 18:56:51', '2013-08-12 06:56:51', '', 'gs4_0001', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gs4_0001', '', '', '2013-08-12 18:56:51', '2013-08-12 06:56:51', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('759', '1', '2013-07-03 12:08:59', '2013-07-03 00:08:59', 'The first step is to initialize the SDK. The best way to do this is to follow the instructions in the official <a title=\"Getting Started with the Facebook JavaScript SDK\" href=\"https://developers.facebook.com/docs/javascript/gettingstarted/\" target=\"_blank\">documentation</a> since it changes fairly often.\r\n\r\nThen you need to run check if the user is logged in using FB.getLoginStatus\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nFB.getLoginStatus(function(response) {\r\n\r\n     if (response.status === \'connected\') {\r\n           // connected\r\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED\');\r\n      } else if (response.status === \'not_authorized\') {\r\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED, NOT AUTORIZED\');\r\n           login();\r\n      } else {\r\n           console.log(\'NOT CONNECTED\');\r\n           login();\r\n      }\r\n\r\n});\r\n\r\nfunction login(){\r\n\r\n      FB.login(function(response) {\r\n           if (response.authResponse) {\r\n                     console.log(\'LOGGED IN\');\r\n                } else {\r\n                     console.log(\'CANCELLED\');\r\n                }\r\n            },\r\n      {scope: \'publish_actions\'});\r\n\r\n}//login\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIf they\'re not logged in, ask them to login by using FB.login. I\'ve made FB.login contained in its own function to stop code repetition since its called in two situations.\r\n\r\nThe login call is where we ask for permissions, so it will get called when the user is logged in but has not given permissions as well as when the user is not logged in.\r\n\r\nThe second variable parsed to FB.login is the scope of the app. The scope defines the required permissions of the app. The scope documentation can be found <a title=\"Facebook Scope Documentation\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/docs/reference/login/#permissions\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. Multiple scope parameters can be simply a comma separated list.\r\n\r\nWe get two responses from the login function, this is so we can differentiate between the user cancelling out of the login process and actually logging in.\r\n\r\nI\'ve just put console logs through the code to show what happens when, its up to you and the needs of your app to define what you need to do when each of these circumstances occur.', 'Login with the Facebook JavaScript SDK', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'login-with-the-facebook-javascript-sdk', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:30:58', '2014-06-07 07:30:58', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=759', '0', 'post', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('757', '1', '2013-06-24 11:37:08', '2013-06-23 23:37:08', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The homepage has a custom slideshow gallery and all the content is manageable\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-459\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0003_Background\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The menu featured a custom accordion style menu with sub sections\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-458\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer 74\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The map can find you by GPS and show the nearest BK or you could search\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-457\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer 75\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The contact form sends email directly to their customer service team\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-456\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer 78\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\n<h3>Goals</h3>\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions over the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\n<h3>Live site</h3>\n<a title=\"BK Brand Site\" href=\"http://www.burgerking.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.burgerking.co.nz</a>', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-2', '', '', '2013-06-24 11:37:08', '2013-06-23 23:37:08', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('760', '1', '2013-07-03 11:45:49', '2013-07-02 23:45:49', '', 'Facebook Javascript API', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '759-revision', '', '', '2013-07-03 11:45:49', '2013-07-02 23:45:49', '', '759', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/759-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('761', '1', '2013-07-03 11:46:49', '2013-07-02 23:46:49', '[sourcecode language=\"\"][/sourcecode]&lt;script src=\"http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;[/code]', 'Facebook Javascript API', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '759-revision-2', '', '', '2013-07-03 11:46:49', '2013-07-02 23:46:49', '', '759', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/759-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('762', '1', '2013-07-03 11:46:58', '2013-07-02 23:46:58', '[sourcecode language=\"html\"][/sourcecode]&lt;script src=\"http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;[/code]', 'Facebook Javascript API', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '759-revision-3', '', '', '2013-07-03 11:46:58', '2013-07-02 23:46:58', '', '759', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/759-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('763', '1', '2013-07-03 11:47:29', '2013-07-02 23:47:29', 'Recently I ran into the situation where my overflow:visible property wasn\'t working in IE. It would cut the content off as if it were set to hide the overflow.\n\nHere\'s the CSS i was using:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\n#header {\n    background-color: #2a2a2a;\n    background-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#323232), to(#222222));\n    background-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    filter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#323232, endColorstr=#222222);\n    height: 60px;\n    overflow: visible;\n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThe header div here has a background gradient which I\'ve made compatible with IE by using the filter property. Unfortunately, using the filter property effectively kills the overflow functionality. From what I gather, the filter for all intents and purposes removes and reintroduces the element from the DOM and in this process some of its properties are overwritten or lost.\n\nThis applies to opacity filters, drop shadows, everything that uses the filter or -ms-filter property will encounter this issue. These elements will ignore the overflow property no matter what you try.\n\nMy recommendation is simply to remove it and code a different solution like using a flat color or a jpg as a background in IE.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\n#header {\n    background-color: #2a2a2a url(images/gradient.jpg) repeat-x;\n    background-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#323232), to(#222222));\n    background-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    height: 60px;\n    overflow: visible;\n}\n[/sourcecode]', 'Overflow, Filters and IE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '749-autosave', '', '', '2013-07-03 11:47:29', '2013-07-02 23:47:29', '', '749', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/749-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('764', '1', '2013-07-03 11:47:09', '2013-07-02 23:47:09', '[sourcecode language=\"html\"]&lt;script src=&quot;http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;[/sourcecode]', 'Facebook Javascript API', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '759-revision-4', '', '', '2013-07-03 11:47:09', '2013-07-02 23:47:09', '', '759', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/759-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('765', '1', '2013-07-03 12:08:59', '2013-07-03 00:08:59', 'The first step is to initialize the SDK. The best way to do this is to follow the instructions in the official <a title=\"Getting Started with the Facebook JavaScript SDK\" href=\"https://developers.facebook.com/docs/javascript/gettingstarted/\" target=\"_blank\">documentation</a> since it changes fairly often.\r\n\r\nThen you need to run check if the user is logged in using FB.getLoginStatus\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nFB.getLoginStatus(function(response) {\r\n     if (response.status === \'connected\') {\r\n           // connected\r\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED\');\r\n      } else if (response.status === \'not_authorized\') {\r\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED, NOT AUTORIZED\');\r\n           login();\r\n      } else {\r\n           console.log(\'NOT CONNECTED\');\r\n           login();\r\n      }\r\n});\r\n\r\nfunction login(){\r\n      FB.login(function(response) {\r\n           if (response.authResponse) {\r\n                     console.log(\'LOGGED IN\');\r\n                } else {\r\n                     console.log(\'CANCELLED\');\r\n                }\r\n            },\r\n      {scope: \'publish_actions\'});\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIf they\'re not logged in, ask them to login by using FB.login. I\'ve made FB.login contained in its own function to stop code repetition since its called in two situations.\r\n\r\nSince the login call is where we ask for permissions, it will get called when the user is logged in but has not given permissions as well as when the user is not logged in.\r\n\r\nThe second variable parsed to FB.login is the scope of the app. The scope defines the required permissions of the app. The scope documentation can be found <a title=\"Facebook Scope Documentation\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/docs/reference/login/#permissions\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. Multiple scope parameters can be simply a comma separated list.\r\n\r\nWe get two responses from the login function, this is so we can differentiate between the user cancelling out of the login process and actually logging in.\r\n\r\nI\'ve just put console logs through the code to show what happens when, its up to you and the needs of your app to define what you need to do when each of these circumstances occur.', 'Login with the Facebook JavaScript SDK', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '759-revision-5', '', '', '2013-07-03 12:08:59', '2013-07-03 00:08:59', '', '759', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/759-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('766', '1', '2013-07-03 12:09:45', '2013-07-03 00:09:45', 'The first step is to initialize the SDK. The best way to do this is to follow the instructions in the official <a title=\"Getting Started with the Facebook JavaScript SDK\" href=\"https://developers.facebook.com/docs/javascript/gettingstarted/\" target=\"_blank\">documentation</a> since it changes fairly often.\r\n\r\nThen you need to run check if the user is logged in using FB.getLoginStatus\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nFB.getLoginStatus(function(response) {\r\n     if (response.status === \'connected\') {\r\n           // connected\r\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED\');\r\n      } else if (response.status === \'not_authorized\') {\r\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED, NOT AUTORIZED\');\r\n           login();\r\n      } else {\r\n           console.log(\'NOT CONNECTED\');\r\n           login();\r\n      }\r\n});\r\n\r\nfunction login(){\r\n      FB.login(function(response) {\r\n           if (response.authResponse) {\r\n                     console.log(\'LOGGED IN\');\r\n                } else {\r\n                     console.log(\'CANCELLED\');\r\n                }\r\n            },\r\n      {scope: \'publish_actions\'});\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIf they\'re not logged in, ask them to login by using FB.login. I\'ve made FB.login contained in its own function to stop code repetition since its called in two situations.\r\n\r\nThe login call is where we ask for permissions, so it will get called when the user is logged in but has not given permissions as well as when the user is not logged in.\r\n\r\nThe second variable parsed to FB.login is the scope of the app. The scope defines the required permissions of the app. The scope documentation can be found <a title=\"Facebook Scope Documentation\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/docs/reference/login/#permissions\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. Multiple scope parameters can be simply a comma separated list.\r\n\r\nWe get two responses from the login function, this is so we can differentiate between the user cancelling out of the login process and actually logging in.\r\n\r\nI\'ve just put console logs through the code to show what happens when, its up to you and the needs of your app to define what you need to do when each of these circumstances occur.', 'Login with the Facebook JavaScript SDK', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '759-revision-6', '', '', '2013-07-03 12:09:45', '2013-07-03 00:09:45', '', '759', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/759-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('767', '1', '2013-07-03 12:11:21', '2013-07-03 00:11:21', 'The first step is to initialize the SDK. The best way to do this is to follow the instructions in the official <a title=\"Getting Started with the Facebook JavaScript SDK\" href=\"https://developers.facebook.com/docs/javascript/gettingstarted/\" target=\"_blank\">documentation</a> since it changes fairly often.\n\nThen you need to run check if the user is logged in using FB.getLoginStatus\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\nFB.getLoginStatus(function(response) {\n\n     if (response.status === \'connected\') {\n           // connected\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED\');\n      } else if (response.status === \'not_authorized\') {\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED, NOT AUTORIZED\');\n           login();\n      } else {\n           console.log(\'NOT CONNECTED\');\n           login();\n      }\n\n});\n\nfunction login(){\n\n      FB.login(function(response) {\n           if (response.authResponse) {\n                     console.log(\'LOGGED IN\');\n                } else {\n                     console.log(\'CANCELLED\');\n                }\n            },\n      {scope: \'publish_actions\'});\n\n}//login\n[/sourcecode]\n\nIf they\'re not logged in, ask them to login by using FB.login. I\'ve made FB.login contained in its own function to stop code repetition since its called in two situations.\n\nThe login call is where we ask for permissions, so it will get called when the user is logged in but has not given permissions as well as when the user is not logged in.\n\nThe second variable parsed to FB.login is the scope of the app. The scope defines the required permissions of the app. The scope documentation can be found <a title=\"Facebook Scope Documentation\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/docs/reference/login/#permissions\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. Multiple scope parameters can be simply a comma separated list.\n\nWe get two responses from the login function, this is so we can differentiate between the user cancelling out of the login process and actually logging in.\n\nI\'ve just put console logs through the code to show what happens when, its up to you and the needs of your app to define what you need to do when each of these circumstances occur.', 'Login with the Facebook JavaScript SDK', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '759-autosave', '', '', '2013-07-03 12:11:21', '2013-07-03 00:11:21', '', '759', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/759-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('768', '1', '2013-02-27 18:28:30', '2013-02-27 06:28:30', 'Javascript timers are pretty useful for any web app which requires the client machine to poll the server for updates.\r\n\r\nInitializing a javascript timer is pretty straight forward.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nsetInterval(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},5000);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe first argument is the function to run when the timer triggers and the second is the timer interval in milliseconds.\r\n\r\nThis will set the timer running but with this method you have no way to stop the timer. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also to separate the function from the initilaization.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nvar counter = 1;\r\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction(),5000);\r\n\r\nfunction timerFunction(){\r\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\r\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\r\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\r\n     }else{\r\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\r\n          counter++;\r\n     }\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer after its logged to the console 5 times.\r\n\r\nThe timer is stopped with the clearInterval command, passing in the timer object as a variable in its first argument\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nclearInterval(myTimer);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember that in situations when you\'re polling the server for content updates not to run these too often if your server is expected to be busy or you will overload your server.', 'Javascript timers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '603-revision-8', '', '', '2013-02-27 18:28:30', '2013-02-27 06:28:30', '', '603', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/603-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('769', '1', '2013-07-05 16:05:40', '2013-07-05 04:05:40', 'Javascript timers are pretty useful for any web app which requires the client machine to poll the server for updates.\r\n\r\nInitializing a javascript timer is pretty straight forward.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nsetInterval(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},5000);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe first argument is the function to run when the timer triggers and the second is the timer interval in milliseconds.\r\n\r\nThis will set the timer running but with this method you have no way to stop the timer. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also to separate the function from the initilaization.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nvar counter = 1;\r\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction,5000);\r\n\r\nfunction timerFunction(){\r\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\r\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\r\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\r\n     }else{\r\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\r\n          counter++;\r\n     }\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer after its logged to the console 5 times.\r\n\r\nThe timer is stopped with the clearInterval command, passing in the timer object as a variable in its first argument\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nclearInterval(myTimer);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember that in situations when you\'re polling the server for content updates not to run these too often if your server is expected to be busy or you will overload your server.', 'Javascript timers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '603-revision-9', '', '', '2013-07-05 16:05:40', '2013-07-05 04:05:40', '', '603', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/603-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('770', '1', '2013-07-05 16:06:14', '2013-07-05 04:06:14', 'Javascript timers are pretty useful for any web app which requires the client machine to poll the server for updates.\r\n\r\nInitializing a javascript timer is pretty straight forward.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nsetInterval(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},1000);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe first argument is the function to run when the timer triggers and the second is the timer interval in milliseconds.\r\n\r\nThis will set the timer running but with this method you have no way to stop the timer. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also to separate the function from the initilaization.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nvar counter = 1;\r\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction,5000);\r\n\r\nfunction timerFunction(){\r\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\r\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\r\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\r\n     }else{\r\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\r\n          counter++;\r\n     }\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer after its logged to the console 5 times.\r\n\r\nThe timer is stopped with the clearInterval command, passing in the timer object as a variable in its first argument\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nclearInterval(myTimer);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember that in situations when you\'re polling the server for content updates not to run these too often if your server is expected to be busy or you will overload your server.', 'Javascript timers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '603-revision-10', '', '', '2013-07-05 16:06:14', '2013-07-05 04:06:14', '', '603', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/603-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('771', '1', '2013-07-05 16:06:20', '2013-07-05 04:06:20', 'Javascript timers are pretty useful for any web app which requires the client machine to poll the server for updates.\r\n\r\nInitializing a javascript timer is pretty straight forward.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nsetInterval(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},1000);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe first argument is the function to run when the timer triggers and the second is the timer interval in milliseconds.\r\n\r\nThis will set the timer running but with this method you have no way to stop the timer. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also to separate the function from the initilaization.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nvar counter = 1;\r\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction,5000);\r\n\r\nfunction timerFunction(){\r\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\r\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\r\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\r\n     }else{\r\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\r\n          counter++;\r\n     }\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer after its logged to the console 5 times.\r\n\r\nThe timer is stopped with the clearInterval command, passing in the timer object as a variable in its first argument\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nclearInterval(myTimer);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember that in situations when you\'re polling the server for content updates not to run these too often if your server is expected to be busy or you will overload your server.', 'Javascript timers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '603-revision-11', '', '', '2013-07-05 16:06:20', '2013-07-05 04:06:20', '', '603', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/603-revision-11/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('781', '1', '2013-08-12 19:00:30', '2013-08-12 07:00:30', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\n\n<a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\n\n<a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\n\n<a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\n\n<a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\n\n<a class=\"fancybox\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\n\n</div>\n<h3>Goals</h3>\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-3', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:00:30', '2013-08-12 07:00:30', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('709', '1', '2013-03-07 08:53:47', '2013-03-06 20:53:47', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important subtleties to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set, IE will run in \'Quirks Mode\' which stops \'margin:auto\' working in Internet Explorer. Also, when setting your doctype make sure you dont have any HTML comments above your doctype declaration or IE will fall back to quirks mode.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin:auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you should get a div which is centered both vertically and horizontally no matter what the screen size is.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that it will only work in IE8 and above. I\'m working on an IE7 fix and will update this article when I\'ve come up with an acceptable solution.\r\n\r\nThe other thing is that also have to specify a height and width which means it not great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>\r\n\r\nThis solution was built on a suggestion offered by Daniel Whyte, check out his <a title=\"Daniel Whyte\'s Website\" href=\"http://www.danielwhyte.com\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>.', 'Vertically centering using margin:auto', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'vertically-centering-using-margin-auto', '', '', '2013-03-11 08:53:01', '2013-03-10 20:53:01', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=709', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('712', '1', '2013-05-22 11:00:25', '2013-05-21 23:00:25', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n    &lt;head&gt;\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\n            div#container {\n                margin: auto;\n                position: absolute;\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\n                border-radius: 5px;\n                background-color: #EEE;\n                top: 0;\n                right: 0;\n                bottom: 0;\n                left: 0;\n                height: 315px;\n                width: 600px;\n            }\n            div#inner {\n                margin: 20px;\n            }\n        &lt;/style&gt;\n    &lt;/head&gt;\n    &lt;body&gt;\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\n            &lt;/div&gt;\n        &lt;/div&gt;\n    &lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThere are a few important subtleties to note here.\n\nIf your doctype is not set, IE will run in \'Quirks Mode\' which stops \'margin:auto\' working in Internet Explorer. Also, when setting your doctype make sure you dont have any HTML comments above your doctype declaration or IE will fall back to quirks mode.\n\nWhen using \'margin:auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\n\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\n\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you should get a div which is centered both vertically and horizontally no matter what the screen size is.\n\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that it will only work in IE8 and above. I\'m working on an IE7 fix and will update this article when I\'ve come up with an acceptable solution.\n\nThe other thing is that also have to specify a height and width which means it not great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\n\nHere\'s the code in action:\n\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>\n\nThis solution was built on a suggestion offered by Daniel Whyte, check out his <a title=\"Daniel Whyte\'s Website\" href=\"http://www.danielwhyte.com\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>.', 'Vertically centering using margin:auto', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-autosave', '', '', '2013-05-22 11:00:25', '2013-05-21 23:00:25', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('710', '1', '2013-03-07 08:29:50', '2013-03-06 20:29:50', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\n\nWhen using an auto margin, make sure you\'ve specified a width and the div is not floating and uses the default position of static.\n\nTo get things to vertically center is a bit trickier and takes a bit of lateral thinking.\n\nHTML\n\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n    &lt;head&gt;\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }\n            div#container {\n                margin: auto;\n                position: absolute;\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\n                border-radius: 5px;\n                background-color: #EEE;\n                top: 0;\n                right: 0;\n                bottom: 0;\n                left: 0;\n                height: 315px;\n                width: 600px;\n            }\n            div#inner {\n                margin: 20px;\n            }\n        &lt;/style&gt;\n    &lt;/head&gt;\n    &lt;body&gt;\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\n            &lt;/div&gt;\n        &lt;/div&gt;\n    &lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\nCSS\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\nhtml, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\n\ndiv#h-center {\n    width: 600px;\n    height: 0;\n    margin: 0 auto;\n    position: static;\n}\n\ndiv#v-full {\n    height: 100%;\n    position: absolute;\n}\n\ndiv#pusher {\n    height: 50%;\n}\n\ndiv#overlay {\n    position: fixed;\n    width: 600px;\n    height: 315px;\n    background-color: #EEE;\n    margin-top: -157px;\n    border-radius: 5px;\n    border: 1px solid #CCC;\n    background-repeat: no-repeat;\n    background-position: center center;\n}\n\ndiv#inner {\n    margin: 20px;\n}\n[/sourcecode]\nThe h-center div is the same width as we want the overlay to be with a 0 height and its margin set to \'0 auto\' to center it on the page. This is so that none of our content is pushed down by the overlay but you cant use \'0 auto\' on something which is positioned absolutely or fixed, which is why we need to use this as our first container.\n\nThe v-full div has 100% height has its position set to absolute. Remember, we\'re already centered on the page since we\'re inside the h-center div. Even though the v-full one is absolutely positioned, its starting point is where it would naturally sit on the page unless we use \'top\' or \'left\' attributes to position it. We need this div so that we\'re inside a div with 100% height which we can then use to determine the vertical center.\n\nThen we have the pusher div which is set to 50% height. Percentages always work in regard to the container we\'re inside. Since this is inside the v-full div which is at 100% page height, it ends up being 50% the height of the entire page. This div is set to the default position of static, so it pushes the starting point of our next div down the page.\n\nLastly comes our overlay. This is again position fixed like our dimmer, but just as the v-full div, it sits where it naturally would in the page which is at the bottom of our pusher div. All we need to do now, is move the overlay\'s top margin up by half the height of itself and it will be in the center of the page.\n\nHopefully that makes sense.\n\nRemember to put the HTML right after your opening body tag.\n\nThis method should overlay straight on top of whatever content you have on the page, so all you need to add is some javascript to have it display block when necessary.\n\nIf you\'re having problems visualizing how it fits together, try giving each of the div\'s different, bright colored backgrounds to make them differentiate.\n\nAdditional\n\nAs Daniel Whyte has pointed out (as with all programming) there are other ways to do this.\n\nHis method uses the following code:\n\nHTML\n\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\n&lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;&lt;!-- content --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\nCSS\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\n    html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }\n    div#container {\n        margin: auto;\n        position: absolute;\n        border: 1px solid #CCC;\n        border-radius: 5px;\n        background-color: #EEE;\n        top: 10%;\n        right: 10%;\n        bottom: 10%;\n        left: 10%;\n        height: 315px;\n        width: 600px;\n    }\n[/sourcecode]\nDont forget to set the margin to auto or this won\'t center properly.\n\nThis method has its merits, its simpler and you wouldn\'t have to change the top padding if you wanted to change the height of the container div.\n\nHowever, it only really works on a screen that is much larger than the box you\'re centering. The horizontal centering breaks down if your content is too wide or you resize your screen below a certain point. It also doesn\'t seem to work in Internet Explorer 7, 8 and 9.\n\nI\'ve found that by using Daniel\'s example and changing the positioning attributes to zero, it stops the horizontal centering from breaking down when you resize the window smaller.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\n    html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }\n    div#container {\n        margin: auto;\n        position: absolute;\n        border: 1px solid #CCC;\n        border-radius: 5px;\n        background-color: #EEE;\n        top: 0;\n        right: 0;\n        bottom: 0;\n        left: 0;\n        height: 315px;\n        width: 600px;\n    }\n[/sourcecode]\nHowever, it still doesn\'t seem to work in any of the Internet Explorers.\n\nConclusion\n\nWhile my medthod is a bit more comlpex and would require a few extra css properties to be adjusted via javascript if you were loading in dynamic content, its cross browser compatibility makes it my pick.\n\nHere\'s an example of each:\n\nMy technique:\nhttp://www.geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/pusher.html\n\nDaniel\'s technique:\nhttp://www.geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\n\nDaniel\'s technique with my modification:\n\nhttp://www.geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto-zero.html\n\nHave a play resizing the windows and trying it in different browsers and see what you think.', 'Centering content', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision', '', '', '2013-03-07 08:29:50', '2013-03-06 20:29:50', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('711', '1', '2013-03-07 08:33:50', '2013-03-06 20:33:50', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\n\nWhen using an auto margin, make sure you\'ve specified a width and the div is not floating and uses the default position of static.\n\nTo get things to vertically center is a bit trickier and takes a bit of lateral thinking.\n\nHTML\n\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n    &lt;head&gt;\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\n    &lt;/head&gt;\n    &lt;body&gt;\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\n            &lt;/div&gt;\n        &lt;/div&gt;\n    &lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\nCSS\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\nhtml, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }\ndiv#container {\n    margin: auto;\n    position: absolute;\n    border: 1px solid #CCC;\n    border-radius: 5px;\n    background-color: #EEE;\n    top: 0;\n    right: 0;\n    bottom: 0;\n    left: 0;\n    height: 315px;\n    width: 600px;\n}\ndiv#inner {\n    margin: 20px;\n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThe important things to note here are \nAdditional\n\nAs Daniel Whyte has pointed out (as with all programming) there are other ways to do this.\n\nHis method uses the following code:\n\nHTML\n\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\n&lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;&lt;!-- content --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n[/sourcecode]\nCSS\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\n    html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }\n    div#container {\n        margin: auto;\n        position: absolute;\n        border: 1px solid #CCC;\n        border-radius: 5px;\n        background-color: #EEE;\n        top: 10%;\n        right: 10%;\n        bottom: 10%;\n        left: 10%;\n        height: 315px;\n        width: 600px;\n    }\n[/sourcecode]\nDont forget to set the margin to auto or this won\'t center properly.\n\nThis method has its merits, its simpler and you wouldn\'t have to change the top padding if you wanted to change the height of the container div.\n\nHowever, it only really works on a screen that is much larger than the box you\'re centering. The horizontal centering breaks down if your content is too wide or you resize your screen below a certain point. It also doesn\'t seem to work in Internet Explorer 7, 8 and 9.\n\nI\'ve found that by using Daniel\'s example and changing the positioning attributes to zero, it stops the horizontal centering from breaking down when you resize the window smaller.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\n    html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }\n    div#container {\n        margin: auto;\n        position: absolute;\n        border: 1px solid #CCC;\n        border-radius: 5px;\n        background-color: #EEE;\n        top: 0;\n        right: 0;\n        bottom: 0;\n        left: 0;\n        height: 315px;\n        width: 600px;\n    }\n[/sourcecode]\nHowever, it still doesn\'t seem to work in any of the Internet Explorers.\n\nConclusion\n\nWhile my medthod is a bit more comlpex and would require a few extra css properties to be adjusted via javascript if you were loading in dynamic content, its cross browser compatibility makes it my pick.\n\nHere\'s an example of each:\n\nMy technique:\nhttp://www.geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/pusher.html\n\nDaniel\'s technique:\nhttp://www.geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\n\nDaniel\'s technique with my modification:\n\nhttp://www.geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto-zero.html\n\nHave a play resizing the windows and trying it in different browsers and see what you think.', 'Centering content', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-2', '', '', '2013-03-07 08:33:50', '2013-03-06 20:33:50', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('713', '1', '2013-03-07 08:53:47', '2013-03-06 20:53:47', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\nHTML\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to note here. \r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set to strict, then using \'margin: auto\' will not work in Internet Explorer.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin: auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides. \r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you will get a div which is perfectly centered no matter what the screen size is or what browser the user is on.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that you have to specify a height and width. This makes it not so great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\nhttp://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto-test.html', 'Centering content', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-3', '', '', '2013-03-07 08:53:47', '2013-03-06 20:53:47', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('715', '1', '2013-03-07 08:55:37', '2013-03-06 20:55:37', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\nHTML\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set to strict, then using \'margin: auto\' will not work in Internet Explorer.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin: auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you will get a div which is perfectly centered no matter what the screen size is or what browser the user is on.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that you have to specify a height and width. This makes it not so great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Centering content', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-4', '', '', '2013-03-07 08:55:37', '2013-03-06 20:55:37', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('716', '1', '2013-03-05 16:02:28', '2013-03-05 04:02:28', 'If you\'re having problems with max-width or max-height not working properly in IE, make sure that you have the correct doctype set in the head of your document.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict //EN&quot;&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThese CSS proerties will only work with a Strict doctype, transitional or any other type will not work.\r\n\r\nAlso make sure that you\'re using it on a valid HTML entity.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the documentation from Microsoft.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Max Width Documentation\" href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx\" target=\"_blank\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx</a>', 'Internet Explorer and max-width', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '663-revision-6', '', '', '2013-03-05 16:02:28', '2013-03-05 04:02:28', '', '663', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/663-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('717', '1', '2013-03-07 08:58:50', '2013-03-06 20:58:50', 'If you\'re having problems with max-width or max-height not working properly in IE, make sure that you have the correct doctype set in the head of your document.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThese CSS proerties will only work with a Strict doctype, transitional or any other type will not work.\r\n\r\nAlso make sure that you\'re using it on a valid HTML entity.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the documentation from Microsoft.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Max Width Documentation\" href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx\" target=\"_blank\">http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-nz/library/ie/ms530811(v=vs.85).aspx</a>', 'Internet Explorer and max-width', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '663-revision-7', '', '', '2013-03-07 08:58:50', '2013-03-06 20:58:50', '', '663', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/663-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('718', '1', '2013-03-07 08:58:47', '2013-03-06 20:58:47', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\nHTML\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set to strict, then using \'margin: auto\' will not work in Internet Explorer.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin: auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you will get a div which is perfectly centered no matter what the screen size is or what browser the user is on.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that you have to specify a height and width. This makes it not so great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Centering content', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-5', '', '', '2013-03-07 08:58:47', '2013-03-06 20:58:47', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('798', '1', '2013-08-12 19:41:53', '2013-08-12 07:41:53', 'The JS SDK for facebook launches the login screen as a popup window and not a modal frame. This means that in some browsers if the user has popups blocked, the window will never show. Safari for example doesn\'t even display a message to say it blocked a popup if you have the blocker turned on. This is a major problem, especially for mobile users whom it seems to haphazardly effect on various browsers, no matter what their popup blocker settings are.\r\n\r\nThe best way around this is to detect if the user is on moblie and use the PHP SDK for login if they are. It gives the same user journey as the popup on mobile since the browser tabs are always full screen but since its redirecting within the same window, it doesnt trigger the popup blocker.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n require_once(\'facebook.php\');\r\n\r\n  $config = array();\r\n  $config[\'appId\'] = \'YOUR_APP_ID\';\r\n  $config[\'secret\'] = \'YOUR_APP_SECRET\';\r\n  $config[\'cookie\'] = true;\r\n\r\n  $facebook = new Facebook($config);\r\n\r\n  $me = null;\r\n\r\n  try {\r\n    $me = $facebook-&gt;api(\'/me\');\r\n  } catch (FacebookApiException $e) {\r\n    error_log($e);\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  if($me){\r\n    //do whatever you need to do with the PHP SDK\r\n  }else{\r\n    $params = array(\r\n      \'scope\' =&gt; \'read_stream, friends_likes\',\r\n      \'redirect_uri\' =&gt; \'https://www.myapp.com/post_login_page\'\r\n    );\r\n    $loginURL = $facebook-&gt;getLoginUrl($params);\r\n    //redirect them to the above login URL or make it the href on an a tag.\r\n  }\r\n\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nLogging in with the PHP SDK and then trying to interact with the JS SDKs FB.ui features used to be a real nightmare. Even when you had cookies enabled, the session never really seemed to share properly and I\'d always have to write custom scripts to read and write the token to the cookie manually. If you\'re having this problem, try upgrading your PHP SDK to version 3. All the bugs to do with sharing the logged in session between the client and the server seem to be resolved in this version.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re worried about it happening on desktop as well, you could implement a javascript timer which will instruct the user to turn off their popup blocker if you didn\'t get the callback from the login window within a certain time frame. Or you could present a custom popup which has a link that would log them in with the PHP SDK if you dont want the user to have to tinker with their browser settings.', 'Facebook login popup never appearing', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'facebook-login-popup-never-appearing', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:31:01', '2014-06-07 07:31:01', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=798', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('799', '1', '2013-08-12 19:41:45', '2013-08-12 07:41:45', 'The JS SDK for facebook launches the login screen as a popup window and not a modal frame. This means that in some browsers if the user has popups blocked, the window will never show. Safari for example doesn\'t even display a message to say it blocked a popup if you have the blocker turned on. This is a major problem, especially for mobile users whom it seems to haphazardly effect on various browsers, no matter what their popup blocker settings are.\n\nThe best way around this is to detect if the user is on moblie and use the PHP SDK for login if they are. It gives the same user journey as the popup on mobile since the browser tabs are always full screen but since its redirecting within the same window, it doesnt trigger the popup blocker.\n\nLogging in with the PHP SDK and then trying to interact with the JS SDKs FB.ui features used to be a real nightmare. Even when you had cookies enabled, the session never really seemed to share properly and I\'d always have to write custom scripts to read and write the token to the cookie manually. If you\'re having this problem, try upgrading your PHP SDK to version 3. All the bugs to do with sharing the logged in session between the client and the server seem to be resolved in this version.\n\nIf you\'re worried about it happening on desktop as well, you could always implement some kind of timer to instruct the user to turn off their popup blocker if you didnt get the callback from the login window within a certain time frame. Or you could present a custom popup with a link which would log them in with the PHP SDK if you dont want \n\n', 'Facebook login popup never appearing', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '798-revision', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:41:45', '2013-08-12 07:41:45', '', '798', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/798-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('800', '1', '2014-06-07 19:16:19', '2014-06-07 07:16:19', 'The JS SDK for facebook launches the login screen as a popup window and not a modal frame. This means that in some browsers if the user has popups blocked, the window will never show. Safari for example doesn\'t even display a message to say it blocked a popup if you have the blocker turned on. This is a major problem, especially for mobile users whom it seems to haphazardly effect on various browsers, no matter what their popup blocker settings are.\n\nThe best way around this is to detect if the user is on moblie and use the PHP SDK for login if they are. It gives the same user journey as the popup on mobile since the browser tabs are always full screen but since its redirecting within the same window, it doesnt trigger the popup blocker.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\n require_once(\'facebook.php\');\n\n  $config = array();\n  $config[\'appId\'] = \'YOUR_APP_ID\';\n  $config[\'secret\'] = \'YOUR_APP_SECRET\';\n  $config[\'cookie\'] = true;\n\n  $facebook = new Facebook($config);\n\n  $me = null;\n\n  try {\n    $me = $facebook-&gt;api(\'/me\');\n  } catch (FacebookApiException $e) {\n    error_log($e);\n  }\n\n  if($me){\n    //do whatever you need to do with the PHP SDK\n  }else{\n    $params = array(\n      \'scope\' =&gt; \'read_stream, friends_likes\',\n      \'redirect_uri\' =&gt; \'https://www.myapp.com/post_login_page\'\n    );\n    $loginURL = $facebook-&gt;getLoginUrl($params);\n    //redirect them to the above login URL or make it the href on an a tag.\n  }\n\n[/sourcecode]\n\nLogging in with the PHP SDK and then trying to interact with the JS SDKs FB.ui features used to be a real nightmare. Even when you had cookies enabled, the session never really seemed to share properly and I\'d always have to write custom scripts to read and write the token to the cookie manually. If you\'re having this problem, try upgrading your PHP SDK to version 3. All the bugs to do with sharing the logged in session between the client and the server seem to be resolved in this version.\n\nIf you\'re worried about it happening on desktop as well, you could implement a javascript timer which will instruct the user to turn off their popup blocker if you didn\'t get the callback from the login window within a certain time frame. Or you could present a custom popup which has a link that would log them in with the PHP SDK if you dont want the user to have to tinker with their browser settings.', 'Facebook login popup never appearing', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '798-autosave', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:16:19', '2014-06-07 07:16:19', '', '798', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/798-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('720', '1', '2013-03-07 09:01:04', '2013-03-06 21:01:04', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\nHTML\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set to strict, then using \'margin: auto\' will not work in Internet Explorer.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin: auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you will get a div which is perfectly centered no matter what the screen size is or what browser the user is on.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that you have to specify a height and width. This makes it not so great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Centering content', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-6', '', '', '2013-03-07 09:01:04', '2013-03-06 21:01:04', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('721', '1', '2013-03-07 09:36:00', '2013-03-06 21:36:00', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\nHTML\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set to strict, then using \'margin: auto\' will not work in Internet Explorer. Make sure not have any HTML comments above your doctype declaration or IE will be forced into quirks mode which will stop this from working. Quirks mode will also be used if no doctype is set.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin: auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you will get a div which is perfectly centered no matter what the screen size is or what browser the user is on.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that you have to specify a height and width. This makes it not so great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Centering content', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-7', '', '', '2013-03-07 09:36:00', '2013-03-06 21:36:00', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('730', '1', '2013-03-07 09:42:41', '2013-03-06 21:42:41', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\nHTML\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set to strict, then using \'margin:auto\' will not work in Internet Explorer. \r\n\r\nIf no doctype is set, IE will run in \'Quirks Mode\' which also stops it from working. When setting your doctype make sure you dont have any HTML comments above your doctype declaration or IE will fall back to quirks mode.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin:auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you will get a div which is perfectly centered no matter what the screen size is or what browser the user is on.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that you have to specify a height and width. This makes it not so great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Centering content using margin:auto', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-16', '', '', '2013-03-07 09:42:41', '2013-03-06 21:42:41', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-16/', '0', 'rev