ake sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you will get a div which is perfectly centered no matter what the screen size is or what browser the user is on.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that you have to specify a height and width. This makes it not so great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Centering content', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-8', '', '', '2013-03-07 09:36:10', '2013-03-06 21:36:10', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('723', '1', '2013-03-07 09:39:04', '2013-03-06 21:39:04', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\nHTML\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n           