ackground-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set to strict, then using \'margin: auto\' will not work in Internet Explorer. If no doctype is set, IE will run in \'Quirks Mode\' which also stops it from working. When setting your doctype make sure you dont have any HTML comments above your doctype declaration or IE will be forced into quirks mode regardless.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin: auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you will get a div which is perfectly centered no matter what the screen size is or what browser the user is on.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that you have to specify a height and width. This makes it not so great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Centering content with margin: auto', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-11', '', '', '2013-03-07 09:39:44', '2013-03-06 21:39:44', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/artic