 you should get a div which is centered both vertically and horizontally no matter what the screen size is or what browser the user is on.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that you have to specify a height and width. This makes it not so great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Vertically centering using margin:auto', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-21', '', '', '2013-03-07 10:13:20', '2013-03-06 22:13:20', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-21/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('736', '1', '2013-03-07 10:13:40', '2013-03-06 22:13:40', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set, IE will run in \'Quirks Mode\' which stops \'margin:auto\' working in Internet Explorer. Also, when setting your doctype make sure you dont have any HTML comments above your doctype declaration or IE will fall back to quirks mode.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin:auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you should get a div which is centered both vertically and horizontally no matter what the screen size is or what browser the user is on.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that you have to specify a height and width. This makes it not so great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Vertically centering using margin:auto', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-22', '', '', '2013-03-07 10:13:40', '2013-03-06 22:13:40', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-22/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('737', '1', '2013-03-07 10:18:59', '2013-03-06 22:18:59', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set, IE will run in \'Quirks Mode\' which stops \'margin:auto\' working in Internet Explorer. Also, when setting your doctype make sure you dont have any HTML comments above your doctype declaration or IE will fall back to quirks mode.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin:auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you should get a div which is centered both vertically and horizontally no matter what the screen size is.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that it will only work in IE8 and above. You also have to specify a height and width which makes it not great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Vertically centering using margin:auto', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-23', '', '', '2013-03-07 10:18:59', '2013-03-06 22:18:59', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-23/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('738', '1', '2013-03-07 10:19:11', '2013-03-06 22:19:11', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important things to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set, IE will run in \'Quirks Mode\' which stops \'margin:auto\' working in Internet Explorer. Also, when setting your doctype make sure you dont have any HTML comments above your doctype declaration or IE will fall back to quirks mode.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin:auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you should get a div which is centered both vertically and horizontally no matter what the screen size is.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that it will only work in IE8 and above. You also have to specify a height and width which makes it not great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Vertically centering using margin:auto', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-24', '', '', '2013-03-07 10:19:11', '2013-03-06 22:19:11', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-24/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('739', '1', '2013-03-07 13:38:44', '2013-03-07 01:38:44', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important subtleties to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set, IE will run in \'Quirks Mode\' which stops \'margin:auto\' working in Internet Explorer. Also, when setting your doctype make sure you dont have any HTML comments above your doctype declaration or IE will fall back to quirks mode.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin:auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you should get a div which is centered both vertically and horizontally no matter what the screen size is.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that it will only work in IE8 and above. You also have to specify a height and width which makes it not great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Vertically centering using margin:auto', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-25', '', '', '2013-03-07 13:38:44', '2013-03-07 01:38:44', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-25/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('804', '1', '2013-03-02 18:17:42', '2013-03-02 06:17:42', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips I\'ve learned along my journey. I\'ll be trying to cover a broad spectrum from the basics to the complex and everything in between.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page and I\'ll either point you to some resources or write it up for all to see.', 'Welcome to Geek Speak', 'Geek Speak is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-31', '', '', '2013-03-02 18:17:42', '2013-03-02 06:17:42', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-31/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('803', '1', '2013-08-12 19:50:09', '2013-08-12 07:50:09', 'The JS SDK for facebook launches the login screen as a popup window and not a modal frame. This means that in some browsers if the user has popups blocked, the window will never show. Safari for example doesn\'t even display a message to say it blocked a popup if you have the blocker turned on. This is a major problem, especially for mobile users whom it seems to haphazardly effect on various browsers, no matter what their popup blocker settings are.\r\n\r\nThe best way around this is to detect if the user is on moblie and use the PHP SDK for login if they are. It gives the same user journey as the popup on mobile since the browser tabs are always full screen but since its redirecting within the same window, it doesnt trigger the popup blocker.\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n require_once(\'facebook.php\');\r\n\r\n  $config = array();\r\n  $config[\'appId\'] = \'YOUR_APP_ID\';\r\n  $config[\'secret\'] = \'YOUR_APP_SECRET\';\r\n  $config[\'cookie\'] = true;\r\n\r\n  $facebook = new Facebook($config);\r\n\r\n  $me = null;\r\n\r\n  try {\r\n    $uid = $facebook-&gt;getUser();\r\n    $me = $facebook-&gt;api(\'/me\');\r\n  } catch (FacebookApiException $e) {\r\n    error_log($e);\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  if($me){\r\n    //do whatever you need to do with the PHP SDK\r\n  }else{\r\n    $params = array(\r\n      \'scope\' =&gt; \'read_stream, friends_likes\',\r\n      \'redirect_uri\' =&gt; \'https://www.myapp.com/post_login_page\'\r\n    );\r\n    $loginURL = $facebook-&gt;getLoginUrl($params);\r\n    //redirect them to the above login URL or make it the href on an a tag.\r\n  }\r\n\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\nLogging in with the PHP SDK and then trying to interact with the JS SDKs FB.ui features used to be a real nightmare. Even when you had cookies enabled, the session never really seemed to share properly and I\'d always have to write custom scripts to read and write the token to the cookie manually. If you\'re having this problem, try upgrading your PHP SDK to version 3. All the bugs to do with sharing the logged in session between the client and the server seem to be resolved in this version.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re worried about it happening on desktop as well, you could implement a javascript timer which will instruct the user to turn off their popup blocker if you didn\'t get the callback from the login window within a certain time frame. Or you could present a custom popup which has a link that would log them in with the PHP SDK if you dont want the user to have to tinker with their browser settings.', 'Facebook login popup never appearing', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '798-revision-4', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:50:09', '2013-08-12 07:50:09', '', '798', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/798-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('805', '1', '2013-08-13 17:13:44', '2013-08-13 05:13:44', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips I\'ve learned along my journey. I\'ll be trying to cover a broad spectrum from the basics to the complex and everything in between.\r\n\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page.\r\n\r\nOr, head on over to the <a title=\"Examples\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/examples/\">examples</a> section to check out some of my work.', 'Welcome to Geek Speak', 'Geek Speak is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-32', '', '', '2013-08-13 17:13:44', '2013-08-13 05:13:44', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-32/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('806', '1', '2013-08-13 17:14:03', '2013-08-13 05:14:03', 'This is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips I\'ve learned along my journey. I\'ll be trying to cover a broad spectrum from the basics to the complex and everything in between.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nIf you have any specific problems that you\'d like me to cover in an article, feel free to drop me a message on the contact page.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nOr, head on over to the <a title=\"Examples\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/examples/\">examples</a> section to check out some of my work.', 'Welcome to Geek Speak', 'Geek Speak is a site dedicated to writing better code through sharing tricks and tips.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '240-revision-33', '', '', '2013-08-13 17:14:03', '2013-08-13 05:14:03', '', '240', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/240-revision-33/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1004', '1', '2014-05-28 22:22:30', '2014-05-28 10:22:30', '', 'Archive', '', 'private', 'open', 'open', '', 'archive', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:29:45', '2014-05-28 10:29:45', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=1004', '100', 'page', '', '0'), ('752', '1', '2013-05-22 11:01:42', '2013-05-21 23:01:42', 'Recently I ran into the situation where my overflow:visible property wasn\'t working in IE. It would cut the content off as if it were set to hide the overflow.\n\nHere\'s the CSS i was using:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]&lt;/pre&gt;\n#header {\nbackground-color: #2a2a2a;\n background-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#323232), to(#222222));\n background-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n background-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n background-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n background-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n background-image: linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\nfilter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#323232, endColorstr=#222222);\n height: 60px;\n overflow: visible;\n}\n\n[/sourcecode]', 'Overflow, Filters and IE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '749-revision-3', '', '', '2013-05-22 11:01:42', '2013-05-21 23:01:42', '', '749', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/749-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('750', '1', '2013-05-22 11:00:42', '2013-05-21 23:00:42', 'Recently I ran into the situation where my overflow:visible property wasn\'t working in IE. It would cut the content off as if it were set to hide the overflow.\n\nHere\'s the CSS i was using:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]&lt;/pre&gt;\n#header {\n background-color: #2a2a2a;\n background-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#323232), to(#222222));\n background-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n background-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n background-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n background-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n background-image: linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n -ms-filter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#323232, endColorstr=#222222);\n height: 60px;\n overflow: visible;\n}\n\n[/sourcecode]', 'Overflow, Filters and IE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '749-revision', '', '', '2013-05-22 11:00:42', '2013-05-21 23:00:42', '', '749', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/749-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('751', '1', '2013-05-22 11:01:03', '2013-05-21 23:01:03', 'Recently I ran into the situation where my overflow:visible property wasn\'t working in IE. It would cut the content off as if it were set to hide the overflow.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the CSS i was using:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]&lt;/pre&gt;\r\n#header {\r\n background-color: #2a2a2a;\r\n background-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#323232), to(#222222));\r\n background-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\r\n background-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\r\n background-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\r\n background-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\r\n background-image: linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\r\n -ms-filter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#323232, endColorstr=#222222);\r\n height: 60px;\r\n overflow: visible;\r\n}\r\n\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Overflow, Filters and IE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '749-revision-2', '', '', '2013-05-22 11:01:03', '2013-05-21 23:01:03', '', '749', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/749-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('753', '1', '2013-05-22 11:11:36', '2013-05-21 23:11:36', 'Recently I ran into the situation where my overflow:visible property wasn\'t working in IE. It would cut the content off as if it were set to hide the overflow.\n\nHere\'s the CSS i was using:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\n#header {\n    background-color: #2a2a2a;\n    background-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#323232), to(#222222));\n    background-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    filter: progid:DXImageTransform.Microsoft.gradient(startColorstr=#323232, endColorstr=#222222);\n    height: 60px;\n    overflow: visible;\n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThe header div here has a background gradient which I\'ve made compatible with IE by using the filter property. Unfortunately, using the filter property effectively kills the overflow functionality. From what I gather, the filter for all intents and purposes removes and reintroduces the element from the DOM and in this process some of its properties are overwritten or lost.\n\nThis applies to opacity filters, drop shadows, everything that uses the filter or -ms-filter property will encounter this issue. These elements will ignore the overflow property no matter what you try.\n\nMy recommendation is simply to remove it and code a different solution like using a flat color or a jpg as a background in IE.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"css\"]\n#header {\n    background-color: #2a2a2a url(images/gradient.jpg) repeat-x;\n    background-image: -webkit-gradient(linear, left top, left bottom, from(#323232), to(#222222));\n    background-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -ms-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    background-image: linear-gradient(top, #323232, #222222);\n    height: 60px;\n    overflow: visible;\n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\n&nbsp;', 'Overflow, Filters and IE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '749-revision-4', '', '', '2013-05-22 11:11:36', '2013-05-21 23:11:36', '', '749', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/749-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('755', '1', '2013-08-12 19:02:05', '2013-08-12 07:02:05', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could choose your avatar for the queue and it would put your facebook profile picture on as the head.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your queue position was determined by your social influence i.e. shares, likes, comments, re-tweets etc.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Each day new content was revealed to share on facebook and twitter\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The content consisted of different types of media\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There were even quizzes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nFacebook Studio 2014: Silver\r\n\r\nCannes 2014: Bronze Lion - Digital\r\n\r\nAxis 2014:  Grand Prix - Out of home,  Gold - Digital and Interactive, Gold - Integrated, Silver - Social\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'The Smart Phoneline', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'get-in-line-galaxy-s4-launch', '', '', '2014-06-23 08:53:28', '2014-06-22 20:53:28', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=755', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('776', '1', '2013-08-12 18:57:05', '2013-08-12 06:57:05', '', 'gs4_0003', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gs4_0003', '', '', '2013-08-12 18:57:05', '2013-08-12 06:57:05', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('777', '1', '2013-08-12 18:57:12', '2013-08-12 06:57:12', '', 'gs4_0004', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gs4_0004', '', '', '2013-08-12 18:57:12', '2013-08-12 06:57:12', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('778', '1', '2013-08-12 18:57:19', '2013-08-12 06:57:19', '', 'gs4_005', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gs4_005', '', '', '2013-08-12 18:57:19', '2013-08-12 06:57:19', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('779', '1', '2013-08-12 18:57:26', '2013-08-12 06:57:26', '', 'gs4_0006', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gs4_0006', '', '', '2013-08-12 18:57:26', '2013-08-12 06:57:26', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('780', '1', '2013-08-12 18:57:34', '2013-08-12 06:57:34', '', 'test fancybox caption', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gs4_0007', '', '', '2013-08-12 18:57:34', '2013-08-12 06:57:34', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('775', '1', '2013-08-12 18:56:58', '2013-08-12 06:56:58', '', 'gs4_0002', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'gs4_0002', '', '', '2013-08-12 18:56:58', '2013-08-12 06:56:58', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('756', '1', '2013-06-24 11:16:59', '2013-06-23 23:16:59', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The homepage has a custom slideshow gallery and all the content is manageable\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-459\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0003_Background\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The menu featured a custom accordion style menu with sub sections\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-458\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer 74\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The map can find you by GPS and show the nearest BK or you could search\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-457\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer 75\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The contact form sends email directly to their customer service team\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-456\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer 78\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\n<h3>Goals</h3>\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people eventually joining the queue and it dynamically updating.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nTo load the stores into the database I wrote a script to initialize the database entries automatically from an address list. This method worked with some but not all of the addresses, particularly those newer locations or ones in shopping complexes. We ended up coding a Google Map in the CMS which the admin could click on the map to record those latitude and longitude coordinates against that store. This proved to be the most useful way of getting the coordinates exact. Then using the latitude and longitude of the stores combined with either the users coordinates or the search terms coordinates we could use the Google Maps API to find the distance between the two points and then use that to order the returned results.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nThe BK Brand site is a solid piece of code which was put together both efficiently and well. Its cross compatible with all modern browsers and can even read the GPS coordinates if you\'re on a smart phone to show you your nearest stores. As far as a fast food brand site goes, this is definitely up the times.\n<h3>Live site</h3>\n<a title=\"BK Brand Site\" href=\"http://www.burgerking.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.burgerking.co.nz</a>', 'Get in line - Galaxy S4 Launch', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision', '', '', '2013-06-24 11:16:59', '2013-06-23 23:16:59', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('743', '1', '2013-03-07 13:40:03', '2013-03-07 01:40:03', 'Sometimes you\'ll want to vertically and horizontally center something on the page. Whether its an image you\'ve popped up or a login box, this can be a confusing thing to get right. There are a couple little tricks you need to know for it to work properly.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"html\"]\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/strict.dtd&quot;&gt;\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n    &lt;head&gt;\r\n        &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;\r\n        &lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;\r\n        &lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;\r\n            html, body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\r\n            div#container {\r\n                margin: auto;\r\n                position: absolute;\r\n                border: 1px solid #CCC;\r\n                border-radius: 5px;\r\n                background-color: #EEE;\r\n                top: 0;\r\n                right: 0;\r\n                bottom: 0;\r\n                left: 0;\r\n                height: 315px;\r\n                width: 600px;\r\n            }\r\n            div#inner {\r\n                margin: 20px;\r\n            }\r\n        &lt;/style&gt;\r\n    &lt;/head&gt;\r\n    &lt;body&gt;\r\n        &lt;div id=&quot;container&quot;&gt;\r\n            &lt;div id=&quot;inner&quot;&gt;\r\n                &lt;!-- content --&gt;\r\n            &lt;/div&gt;\r\n        &lt;/div&gt;\r\n    &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThere are a few important subtleties to note here.\r\n\r\nIf your doctype is not set, IE will run in \'Quirks Mode\' which stops \'margin:auto\' working in Internet Explorer. Also, when setting your doctype make sure you dont have any HTML comments above your doctype declaration or IE will fall back to quirks mode.\r\n\r\nWhen using \'margin:auto\', make sure you\'ve specified a width and height for the container or again it will not work.\r\n\r\nYou will need to set the position of the container to absolute and position it to 0 on all sides.\r\n\r\nIf you follow all 3 of these steps, then you should get a div which is centered both vertically and horizontally no matter what the screen size is.\r\n\r\nThe biggest downside to this technique is that it will only work in IE8 and above. I\'m working on an IE7 fix and will update this article when I\'ve come up with an acceptable solution. \r\n\r\nThe other thing is that also have to specify a height and width which means it not great for dynamic content but awesome for things which are a fixed size.\r\n\r\nHere\'s the code in action:\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Margin auto\" href=\"http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html\" target=\"_blank\">http://geekspeak.co.nz/code/v-h-centering/margin-auto.html</a>', 'Vertically centering using margin:auto', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '709-revision-26', '', '', '2013-03-07 13:40:03', '2013-03-07 01:40:03', '', '709', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/709-revision-26/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('848', '1', '2014-04-16 14:30:17', '2014-04-16 02:30:17', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-5', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:30:17', '2014-04-16 02:30:17', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('847', '1', '2014-04-16 14:29:52', '2014-04-16 02:29:52', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\nvar canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\nvar canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\ndrawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\n function drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-4', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:29:52', '2014-04-16 02:29:52', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('842', '1', '2014-04-16 14:52:49', '2014-04-16 02:52:49', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\r\n\r\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to implement a state change on the element requires the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework.\r\n\r\nKinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could fit my needs. However, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which weren\'t so obvious to me when I started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. If you follow the <a title=\"Image Object example\" href=\"http://www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-kineticjs-image-tutorial/\" target=\"_blank\">Kinetic JS Image object example</a>, the image gets added to the stage on the callback of its load function. This is fine if you\'re only loading one image, but if you want to draw a shape after the image which overlays the image, you\'ll have a problem.\r\n\r\nThe image will always sit on top of the shape because it will always take longer for the image to load than the shape drawing code takes to execute. Unless you pre-load your images, they will always end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in your script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that got me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'canvas-with-kinetic-js', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:30:45', '2014-06-07 07:30:45', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=842', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('844', '1', '2014-04-16 14:29:22', '2014-04-16 02:29:22', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\n\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\n\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"][/sourcecode]</pre>\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\n\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\n\nvar canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\nvar canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\ndrawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\n\n}\n\nresizeCanvas();\n\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\n\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\n\n}', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:29:22', '2014-04-16 02:29:22', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('845', '1', '2014-04-16 14:29:28', '2014-04-16 02:29:28', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]&lt;/pre&gt;\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\nvar canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\nvar canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\ndrawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\n function drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n&lt;pre&gt;[/sourcecode]', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-2', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:29:28', '2014-04-16 02:29:28', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('846', '1', '2014-04-16 14:29:43', '2014-04-16 02:29:43', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]&lt;\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\nvar canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\nvar canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\ndrawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\n function drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-3', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:29:43', '2014-04-16 02:29:43', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('823', '1', '2014-02-26 13:15:41', '2014-02-26 01:15:41', 'Holiday replay enabled people to connect with Facebook and write a story about how they lost cash while on holiday. We would then take their story and match the words up with keywords in our database which were mapped to images and video content that would be compiled along with any facebook photos found of that holiday, into a video sequence with the music track they selected.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"915,922,921,920,919,918,917,916\"]\r\n\r\nThey were able to review the images pulled from facebook for their story and remove any unwanted ones. They could then upload new ones from their facebook gallery or directly from their computer before submitting it to our gallery.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"928,927,926,924\"]\r\n\r\nTheir submitted stories ended up in a searchable gallery where they could be voted on. They could be shared on Facebook and even played within the time line until facebook removed SWF support from timeline posts.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" columns=\"4\" ids=\"930,935,941,942\"]\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nHoliday replay was to be a mobile first web experience that brought an engaging rich media experience to tablet and mobile devices.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built using HTML5, SCSS, Javascript, JQuery and Canvas running on top of the Zend Framework. The API for the data service was built using the Zend Framework. It used the Javascript Facebook API and some quite complex FQL queries to get the right information about users. It used the Google Places Autocomplete field, Google Maps Geo-Coding service and the Google Maps Static Map service. It used HTML5 video and audio. It uploaded user content to the Rackspace Cloud via their API and this was later switched to upload to the Amazon Cloud for performance reasons. As you can see, there is a huge amount of technology combining into this one site and it all operated seamlessly together.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nHoliday Replay was a unique project with a lot of technical aspects to work through. I was the lead developer on this project, and as well as developing the API, my role included guiding the other two developers and ensuring their work pieced together into the final product. Getting all of these technologies to work together was a major challenge in it self. The major challenge for me was to figure out how to turn the users 50 word story into an actual sequence of images, videos, animations, custom fonts, graphics, colors and then serve it to the canvas in a meaningful way so that it could be used to control the animations the user sees to give them a unique experience.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWe had a huge amount of manually compiled stock imagery which was linked to locations and key words. For example if you used the word \"taxi\" and your story was geo tagged as in New York, the background image of that frame would be the iconic yellow taxi of New York. However if it were geo tagged as being in London, you would get an image of their also iconic black taxi cabs.\r\n\r\nIf we couldn\'t match the word, we\'d pull media that was related to the geo tagged location. If we\'d used all the default images for that location, we\'d fall back to a pool of generic imagery. This was my main solution, to have 5 or 6 levels of redundancy so that we were never left with the frame not having an asset to show.\r\n\r\nI would also look up the story location in your facebook albums and splice in some of your facebook images at appropriate intervals to make the experience that much more personal.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis campaign has had a good response and it has held together well over the 3 month course of the campaign. Thousands of people have submitted stories all across Australia. I will update with some more meaningful stats once the post campaign analysis has been done.', 'Holiday Replay', 'Holiday Replay was a unique project with a lot of technical aspects to work through. I was the lead developer on this project, I built the API behind it and guided the other two developers, ensuring their work pieced together into the final product.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'holiday-replay', '', '', '2014-05-29 22:09:15', '2014-05-29 10:09:15', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=823', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('824', '1', '2014-02-26 13:14:50', '2014-02-26 01:14:50', '', 'Holiday Replay', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '823-revision', '', '', '2014-02-26 13:14:50', '2014-02-26 01:14:50', '', '823', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/823-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('916', '1', '2014-05-28 20:08:47', '2014-05-28 08:08:47', '', 'The intro and outro were predetermined sequences', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0002s_0015_layer-146', '', '', '2014-05-28 20:08:47', '2014-05-28 08:08:47', '', '823', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/portfolio-_0002s_0015_Layer-146.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('917', '1', '2014-05-28 20:08:57', '2014-05-28 08:08:57', '', 'Keyword is matched to a video clip of a bicycle', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0002s_0016_layer-145', '', '', '