play', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '823-revision-16', '', '', '2014-02-26 15:15:07', '2014-02-26 03:15:07', '', '823', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/823-revision-16/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('849', '1', '2014-04-16 14:30:20', '2014-04-16 02:30:20', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-6', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:30:20', '2014-04-16 02:30:20', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('850', '1', '2014-04-16 14:38:54', '2014-04-16 02:38:54', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas on page load\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe other thing to note is that images are added to the asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function to run before your initialization of the canvas.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"][/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\nvar imageSources = {\r\nimage1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\nimage2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n}\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\nvar images = {};\r\nvar loadedImages = 0;\r\nvar numImages = 0;\r\n// get num of sources\r\nfor(var src in sources) {\r\nnumImages++;\r\n}\r\nfor(var src in sources) {\r\nimages[src] = new Image();\r\nimages[src].onload = function() {\r\nif(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\ncallback(images);\r\n}\r\n};\r\nimages[src].src = sources[src];\r\n}\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n});', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-7', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:38:54', '2014-04-16 02:38:54', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('851', '1', '2014-04-16 14:39:12', '2014-04-16 02:39:12', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas on page load\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe other thing to note is that images are added to the asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function to run before your initialization of the canvas.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\n function loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n var images = {};\r\n var loadedImages = 0;\r\n var numImages = 0;\r\n // get num of sources\r\n for(var src in sources) {\r\n numImages++;\r\n }\r\n for(var src in sources) {\r\n images[src] = new Image();\r\n images[src].onload = function() {\r\n if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n callback(images);\r\n }\r\n };\r\n images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n }\r\n }\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\n loadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n resizeCanvas();\r\n });\r\n\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-8', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:39:12', '2014-04-16 02:39:12', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('852', '1', '2014-04-16 14:40:39', '2014-04-16 02:40:39', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas on page load\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe other thing to note is that images are added to the asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function to run before your initialization of the canvas.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-9', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:40:39', '2014-04-16 02:40:39', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('853', '1', '2014-04-16 14:48:10', '2014-04-16 02:48:10', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe other thing to note is that images are added to the asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function to run before your initialization of the canvas.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was drawing objects within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges seemed fine, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (function(){\r\n var tempImage = new Image();\r\n image.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n x: 100,\r\n y: 100,\r\n image: image,\r\n\r\n });\r\n&lt;pre&gt;    })();\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-10', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:48:10', '2014-04-16 02:48:10', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('854', '1', '2014-04-16 14:50:12', '2014-04-16 02:50:12', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\n\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\n\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\n//event handler for window resize\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\n\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\n\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\n\n}\n\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\nresizeCanvas();\n\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\n\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\n\n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThe other thing to note is that images are added to the asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas.\n\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function to run before your initialization of the canvas.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\n\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\n var imageSources = {\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\n }\n\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\n    var images = {};\n    var loadedImages = 0;\n    var numImages = 0;\n    // get num of sources\n    for(var src in sources) {\n        numImages++;\n    }\n    for(var src in sources) {\n        images[src] = new Image();\n        images[src].onload = function() {\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\n                callback(images);\n            }\n        };\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\n    }\n}\n\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\n    resizeCanvas();\n});\n[/sourcecode]\n\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\n\nThe last thing that threw me was drawing objects within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage.\n\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges seemed fine, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\n    function(){\n        var tempImage = new Image();\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\n            x: 100,\n            y: 100,\n            image: tempImage,\n            width: 100,\n            height: 100,\n            id: \'image\'+i\n        });\n        kineticImage\n\n})();\n\n}\n[/sourcecode]', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-11', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:50:12', '2014-04-16 02:50:12', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-11/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('855', '1', '2014-04-16 14:51:09', '2014-04-16 02:51:09', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe other thing to note is that images are added to the asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function to run before your initialization of the canvas.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was drawing objects within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges seemed fine to not be wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-12', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:51:09', '2014-04-16 02:51:09', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('856', '1', '2014-04-16 14:52:11', '2014-04-16 02:52:11', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\n\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\n\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\n//event handler for window resize\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\n\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\n\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\n\n}\n\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\nresizeCanvas();\n\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\n\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\n\n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThe other thing to note is that images are added to the asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas.\n\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function to run before your initialization of the canvas.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\n\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\n var imageSources = {\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\n }\n\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\n    var images = {};\n    var loadedImages = 0;\n    var numImages = 0;\n    // get num of sources\n    for(var src in sources) {\n        numImages++;\n    }\n    for(var src in sources) {\n        images[src] = new Image();\n        images[src].onload = function() {\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\n                callback(images);\n            }\n        };\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\n    }\n}\n\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\n    resizeCanvas();\n});\n[/sourcecode]\n\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\n\nThe last thing that threw me was drawing objects within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage.\n\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges seemed fine to not be wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\n    function(){\n        var tempImage = new Image();\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\n            x: 100,\n            y: 100,\n            image: tempImage,\n            width: 100,\n            height: 100,\n            id: \'image\'+i\n        });\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\n        stage.add(layer);\n    })();\n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-13', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:52:11', '2014-04-16 02:52:11', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-13/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('857', '1', '2015-04-04 13:31:54', '2015-04-04 01:31:54', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\n\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to implement a state change on the element requires the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework.\n\nKinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could fit my needs. However, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which weren\'t so obvious to me when I started out.\n\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\n//event handler for window resize\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\n\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\n\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\n\n}\n\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\nresizeCanvas();\n\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\n\n//draw your canvas elements here\n\n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. If you follow the <a title=\"Image Object example\" href=\"http://www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-kineticjs-image-tutorial/\" target=\"_blank\">Kinetic JS Image object example</a>, the image gets added to the stage on the callback of its load function. This is fine if you\'re only loading one image, but if you want to draw a shape after the image which overlays the image, you\'ll have a problem.\n\nThe image will always sit on top of the shape because it will always take longer for the image to load than the shape drawing code takes to execute. Unless you pre-load your images, they will always end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in your script they are.\n\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\n\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\n var imageSources = {\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\n }\n\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\n    var images = {};\n    var loadedImages = 0;\n    var numImages = 0;\n    // get num of sources\n    for(var src in sources) {\n        numImages++;\n    }\n    for(var src in sources) {\n        images[src] = new Image();\n        images[src].onload = function() {\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\n                callback(images);\n            }\n        };\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\n    }\n}\n\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\n    resizeCanvas();\n});\n[/sourcecode]\n\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\n\nThe last thing that got me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\n\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\n    function(){\n        var tempImage = new Image();\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\n            x: 100,\n            y: 100,\n            image: tempImage,\n            width: 100,\n            height: 100,\n            id: \'image\'+i\n        });\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\n        stage.add(layer);\n    })();\n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\n\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\n\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-autosave', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:31:54', '2015-04-04 01:31:54', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('858', '1', '2014-04-16 14:52:49', '2014-04-16 02:52:49', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when first starting out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want your canvas to redraw when the window is resized:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elemnts here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe other thing to note is that images are added to the asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function to run before your initialization of the canvas.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was drawing objects within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges seemed fine to not be wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.', 'Canvas with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-14', '', '', '2014-04-16 14:52:49', '2014-04-16 02:52:49', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-14/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('859', '1', '2014-04-16 14:56:56', '2014-04-16 02:56:56', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be redrawn. For these reasons alone, I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nH