00,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with canvas using Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-21', '', '', '2014-04-16 15:07:47', '2014-04-16 03:07:47', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-21/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('866', '1', '2014-04-16 15:08:01', '2014-04-16 03:08:01', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. The reasons alone stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from natively coding in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when I first started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window