 they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was drawing objects within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges seemed fine to not be wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-31', '', '', '2014-04-16 16:03:51', '2014-04-16 04:03:51', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-3