INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('876', '1', '2014-04-16 16:04:39', '2014-04-16 04:04:39', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. These reasons alone stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when I first started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function to run before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was drawing objects within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges seemed fine to not be wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-32', '', '', '2014-04-16 16:04:39', '2014-04-16 04:04:39', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-32/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('877', '1', '2013-08-12 19:28:38', '2013-08-12 07:28:38', '<div class=\"gallery\"><div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could choose your avatar for the queue and it would put your facebook profile picture on as the head.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your queue position was determined by your social influence i.e. shares, likes, comments, re-tweets etc.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Each day new content was revealed to share on facebook and twitter\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div><div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The content consisted of different types of media\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There were even quizzes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.', 'Get in line: Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-18', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:28:38', '2013-08-12 07:28:38', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-18/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('878', '1', '2014-04-16 16:05:01', '2014-04-16 04:05:01', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. These reasons alone stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when I first started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was drawing objects within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges seemed fine to not be wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-33', '', '', '2014-04-16 16:05:01', '2014-04-16 04:05:01', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-33/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('879', '1', '2014-04-16 18:59:38', '2014-04-16 06:59:38', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. These reasons alone stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when I first started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was drawing objects within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or even have it return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.</pre>\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-34', '', '', '2014-04-16 18:59:38', '2014-04-16 06:59:38', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-34/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('880', '1', '2014-04-16 19:00:12', '2014-04-16 07:00:12', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. These reasons alone stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when I first started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or even have it return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-35', '', '', '2014-04-16 19:00:12', '2014-04-16 07:00:12', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-35/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('881', '1', '2014-04-16 19:01:04', '2014-04-16 07:01:04', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects and any state changes of elements require the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. These reasons alone stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when I first started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-36', '', '', '2014-04-16 19:01:04', '2014-04-16 07:01:04', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-36/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('882', '1', '2014-04-16 19:06:13', '2014-04-16 07:06:13', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape. Then once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to add any state change of elements require the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when I first started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-37', '', '', '2014-04-16 19:06:13', '2014-04-16 07:06:13', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-37/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('883', '1', '2014-04-16 19:06:24', '2014-04-16 07:06:24', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\r\n\r\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to add any state change of elements require the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when I first started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-38', '', '', '2014-04-16 19:06:24', '2014-04-16 07:06:24', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-38/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('885', '1', '2014-04-16 19:08:09', '2014-04-16 07:08:09', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\r\n\r\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to implement a state change on the element requires the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework.\r\n\r\nKinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could fit the bill. However, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when I first started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-40', '', '', '2014-04-16 19:08:09', '2014-04-16 07:08:09', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-40/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('884', '1', '2014-04-16 19:07:24', '2014-04-16 07:07:24', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\r\n\r\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to implement a state change on the element requires the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework. Kinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could do what I required.\r\n\r\nHowever, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which threw me when I first started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-39', '', '', '2014-04-16 19:07:24', '2014-04-16 07:07:24', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-39/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('886', '1', '2014-04-16 19:08:37', '2014-04-16 07:08:37', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\r\n\r\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to implement a state change on the element requires the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework.\r\n\r\nKinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could fit the bill. However, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which weren\'t so obvious to me when I started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. They get added to the stage on the callback of their load function. Meaning that unless you preload your images, they will all end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that threw me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-41', '', '', '2014-04-16 19:08:37', '2014-04-16 07:08:37', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-41/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('887', '1', '2014-04-16 19:11:24', '2014-04-16 07:11:24', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\r\n\r\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to implement a state change on the element requires the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework.\r\n\r\nKinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could fit the bill. However, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which weren\'t so obvious to me when I started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. If you follow the Kinetic JS Image object example, each image gets added to the stage on the callback of its load function. Due to the fact that the following code will execute faster than the image takes to load means that unless you pre-load your images, they will always end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that got me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-42', '', '', '2014-04-16 19:11:24', '2014-04-16 07:11:24', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-42/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('888', '1', '2014-04-16 19:17:31', '2014-04-16 07:17:31', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\r\n\r\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to implement a state change on the element requires the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework.\r\n\r\nKinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could fit the bill. However, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which weren\'t so obvious to me when I started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. If you follow the Kinetic JS Image object example, each image gets added to the stage on the callback of its load function. This is fine if you\'re only loading one image, but if you want to draw a shape after the image which overlays the image, you\'ll have a problem. The image will always sit on top of the shape because it will always take longer for the image to load than the shape drawing code takes to execute. Unless you pre-load your images, they will always end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that got me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-43', '', '', '2014-04-16 19:17:31', '2014-04-16 07:17:31', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-43/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('889', '1', '2014-04-16 19:17:51', '2014-04-16 07:17:51', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\r\n\r\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to implement a state change on the element requires the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework.\r\n\r\nKinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could fit the bill. However, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which weren\'t so obvious to me when I started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. If you follow the Kinetic JS Image object example, each image gets added to the stage on the callback of its load function. This is fine if you\'re only loading one image, but if you want to draw a shape after the image which overlays the image, you\'ll have a problem.\r\n\r\nThe image will always sit on top of the shape because it will always take longer for the image to load than the shape drawing code takes to execute. Unless you pre-load your images, they will always end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in yours script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that got me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-44', '', '', '2014-04-16 19:17:51', '2014-04-16 07:17:51', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-44/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('890', '1', '2014-04-16 19:18:32'