as a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nAxis - Grand Prix - Out of home\r\n\r\nAxis - Gold - Digital and Interactive\r\n\r\nAxis - Gold - Integrated\r\n\r\nAxis - Silver - Social', 'Get in line: Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-21', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:00:18', '2014-05-28 09:00:18', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-21/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('954', '1', '2013-03-21 13:04:33', '2013-03-21 01:04:33', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 for prizes up for grabs it was important to stop any cheating.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nIll post the solutions to the security challenges once the campaign ends.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project is still running but is doing very well. The game is simple, challenging and addictive.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a style=\"font-size: 13px;\" title=\"V Robbers\" href=\"http://www.v.co.nz/vrobbery\" target=\"_blank\">www.v.co.nz/vrobbery</a>', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-16', '', '', '2013-03-21 13:04:33', '2013-03-21 01:04:33', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-16/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('955', '1', '2014-05-28 21:02:18', '2014-05-28 09:02:18', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could choose your avatar for the queue and it would put your facebook profile picture on as the head.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your queue position was determined by your social influence i.e. shares, likes, comments, re-tweets etc.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Each day new content was revealed to share on facebook and twitter\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The content consisted of different types of media\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There were even quizzes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nAxis - Grand Prix - Out of home\r\n\r\nAxis - Gold - Digital and Interactive\r\n\r\nAxis - Gold - Integrated\r\n\r\nAxis - Silver - Social', 'Get in line: Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-22', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:02:18', '2014-05-28 09:02:18', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-22/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('956', '1', '2013-02-28 12:59:59', '2013-02-28 00:59:59', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could watch the womens stories about breast cancer and leave comments\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-408\" alt=\"saveseven-screen2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then choose friends to share the video with via facebook or email\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-410\" alt=\"saveseven-screen4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could choose 7 women to share it with from facebook through my custom friend picker\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-411\" alt=\"saveseven-screen5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The 7 women would then be displayed with their profile pictures\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-412\" alt=\"saveseven-screen6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/saveseven-screen6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to reach every woman in New Zealand with the message that early detection via breast screening is the best way to save the lives of the women we care about. The main driving force behind the online campaign was for users to watch the compelling stories of 7 quite different women who have beaten breast cancer and then share them on facebook with 7 women they care about.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThe main nav of the videos was built in flash while the rest of the site was built on top of the Zend Framework. The site uses the Youtube API for video events to trigger an overlay screen over the video. It also used the facebook API, Facebook Open Graph, JQuery and a bit of fancy HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nOne of the main challenges was to build a friend picker that deviated from the standard facebook functionality. We wanted to be able to only show the users friends who are listed as female on the facebook graph. We also wanted the  video to be posted the wall of the 7 women and make sure the audience is more relevant and also to help gain traction and visibility for the campaign.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThe standard facebook friend picker was not enough, it only sends out app invites rather than wall posts and could not be customized to show different data sets. After we had app permissions granted to look at the users friends list, used FQL and the Facebook PHP API to query graph and return all the users friends listed as Female. From that data set I was able to look up those users facebook IDs on the Open Graph and get their Name, Profile Picture and used these to build the layout of the custom friend picker. Although it has a different color scheme, we tried to make it as close to the native facebook friend picker in terms of functionality. You could select up to 7 friends, then when the user clicked send the facebook app would post the video they selected on the site to all the women they had selected which could be watched straight on the facebook news feed along with a link to the site.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nSave Seven had a great core idea and a unique way of spreading its message. The friend picker ended up being such a hit that I packaged it up to be added to our code library for future projects and it has been re purposed many times since it was built. Its always great to try something you haven\'t done before, especially when it works great and is for a great cause.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nSave Seven won a Gold Axis for best Charity Campaign at the Axis Awards in 2012 and has won a few awards overseas as well.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"Save Seven\" href=\"http://www.saveseven.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.saveseven.co.nz\r\n\r\n</a>', 'Save Seven', 'Seven women every day are diagnosed with Breast Cancer in New Zealand. Our mission was to encourage people to reach out to seven women they care about and spread the message of how early detection saves lives. This a won Gold Axis for best Charity campaign of 2011 ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '413-revision-16', '', '', '2013-02-28 12:59:59', '2013-02-28 00:59:59', '', '413', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/413-revision-16/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1023', '1', '2014-05-29 08:19:57', '2014-05-28 20:19:57', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could choose your avatar for the queue and it would put your facebook profile picture on as the head.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your queue position was determined by your social influence i.e. shares, likes, comments, re-tweets etc.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Each day new content was revealed to share on facebook and twitter\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The content consisted of different types of media\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There were even quizzes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nAxis - Grand Prix - Out of home\r\n\r\nAxis - Gold - Digital and Interactive\r\n\r\nAxis - Gold - Integrated\r\n\r\nAxis - Silver - Social', 'The Smart Phoneline', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-24', '', '', '2014-05-29 08:19:57', '2014-05-28 20:19:57', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-24/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('957', '1', '2014-05-28 21:19:19', '2014-05-28 09:19:19', '[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"958,967,965,964,962,961,960,959\"]\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nWe wanted to use facial recognition software to map how you reacted as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations with the goal of deciphering how customers really felt about money.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThe site housing the scan was built using HTML, CSS , Javascript and JQuery on top of the Zend Framework. The Emotion Scanner itself was built in Flash and connected to a facial recognition API provided by a third party. I also built and API for the flash to submit the users results to the database and run an analysis algorithm on the data.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nWorking with the developers of the facial recognition software who lived on the other side of the world was challenging. The time difference proved to be a real nuisance and slowed down bug fixing to a crawl. I actually joined this project half way through to help out with some of the front end build and to do the data analysis, but it quickly became apparent that the job was slipping through the fingers of the people who where supposed to be in charge.\r\n\r\nFrom a technical perspective the main challenge for me here was the data analysis, how to extract meaningful information from the raw data sent back to us from the facial recognition API and how to display that back to the user is a format that made sense to them.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEven though I was supposed to be only helping on a minor level, I ended up stepping in and taking the reigns of the job to help it across the finish line. I was able to get everyone to re-group, re-assess and re-enter the job with clear goals and objectives rather than being reactive which was causing a lot of double ups and re-doing of work.\r\n\r\nWith the data, I was able to process it, with some guidance by research done by our planners, into a readable digestable form. We were able to show the customer the graphs of their raw data over time as well as ranking the 7 subjects matters from most to least happy and giving that insight to the customer.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis campaign performed well and the client was happy with how it was received by their customers and clients.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nAxis 2014: Gold - Digital &amp; Interactive.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'EmotionScan', 'Emotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations with the goal of deciphering how customers really felt about money.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'emotionscan', '', '', '2014-05-29 21:54:24', '2014-05-29 09:54:24', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=957', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('958', '1', '2014-05-28 21:09:07', '2014-05-28 09:09:07', '', 'Home page with tutorial video', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0009_layer-164', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:09:07', '2014-05-28 09:09:07', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0001s_0009_Layer-164.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('959', '1', '2014-05-28 21:09:12', '2014-05-28 09:09:12', '', 'Allowing you to share the results with your friends', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0000_layer-175', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:09:12', '2014-05-28 09:09:12', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0001s_0000_Layer-175.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('960', '1', '2014-05-28 21:09:18', '2014-05-28 09:09:18', '', 'Giving you scores for various sections', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0001_layer-174', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:09:18', '2014-05-28 09:09:18', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0001s_0001_Layer-174.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('961', '1', '2014-05-28 21:09:25', '2014-05-28 09:09:25', '', 'Plotting your data over time', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0002_layer-173', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:09:25', '2014-05-28 09:09:25', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0001s_0002_Layer-173.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('962', '1', '2014-05-28 21:09:31', '2014-05-28 09:09:31', '', 'Processing the data points', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0003_layer-172', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:09:31', '2014-05-28 09:09:31', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0001s_0003_Layer-172.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('963', '1', '2014-05-28 21:09:38', '2014-05-28 09:09:38', '', '', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0004_layer-171', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:09:38', '2014-05-28 09:09:38', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0001s_0004_Layer-171.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('964', '1', '2014-05-28 21:09:43', '2014-05-28 09:09:43', '', 'Scanning your face while it plays emotive video and audio about financial situations', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0005_layer-170', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:09:43', '2014-05-28 09:09:43', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0001s_0005_Layer-170.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('965', '1', '2014-05-28 21:09:48', '2014-05-28 09:09:48', '', 'Locking onto your face', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0006_layer-176', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:09:48', '2014-05-28 09:09:48', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0001s_0006_Layer-176.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('966', '1', '2014-05-28 21:09:51', '2014-05-28 09:09:51', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0007_Layer 168', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0007_layer-168', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:09:51', '2014-05-28 09:09:51', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0001s_0007_Layer-168.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('967', '1', '2014-05-28 21:09:55', '2014-05-28 09:09:55', '', 'Selecting options', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0001s_0008_layer-167', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:09:55', '2014-05-28 09:09:55', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0001s_0008_Layer-167.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('968', '1', '2014-05-28 21:18:38', '2014-05-28 09:18:38', '[gallery ids=\"959,960,961,962,964,965,967,958\"]\n\nEmotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations.\n\nWe then took the data points and plotted them against time. From that, we extrapolated how you felt about different types of financial topics depending on what emotions we could read off your face.\n\nI was involved in building the API which saved the data which we received from the facial recognition API and running it through an algorithm to turn it into meaningful, digestible results.\n\nThe main challenges arose from the facial recognition API not being particularly sturdy and we had to spend a lot of time working with its developer to get t', 'EmotionScan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '957-revision', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:18:38', '2014-05-28 09:18:38', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/957-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('969', '1', '2014-05-29 21:54:06', '2014-05-29 09:54:06', '[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"958,967,965,964,962,961,960,959\"]\n<h3>Goals</h3>\nWe wanted to use facial recognition software to map how you reacted as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations with the goal of deciphering how customers really felt about money.\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThe site housing the scan was built using HTML, CSS , Javascript and JQuery on top of the Zend Framework. The Emotion Scanner itself was built in Flash and connected to a facial recognition API provided by a third party. I also built and API for the flash to submit the users results to the database and run an analysis algorithm on the data.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nWorking with the developers of the facial recognition software who lived on the other side of the world was challenging. The time difference proved to be a real nuisance and slowed down bug fixing to a crawl. I actually joined this project half way through to help out with some of the front end build and to do the data analysis, but it quickly became apparent that the job was slipping through the fingers of the people who where supposed to be in charge.\n\nFrom a technical perspective the main challenge for me here was the data analysis, how to extract meaningful information from the raw data sent back to us from the facial recognition API and how to display that back to the user is a format that made sense to them.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nEven though I was supposed to be only helping on a minor level, I ended up stepping in and taking the reigns of the job to help it across the finish line. I was able to get everyone to re-group, re-assess and re-enter the job with clear goals and objectives rather than being reactive which was causing a lot of double ups and re-doing of work.\n\nWith the data, I was able to process it, with some guidance by research done by our planners, into a readable digestable form. We were able to show the customer the graphs of their raw data over time as well as ranking the 7 subjects matters they were most and least happy about.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nThis campaign performed well and the client was happy with how it was received by their customers and clients.\n<h3>Awards</h3>\nAxis 2014: Gold - Digital &amp; Interactive.\n\n&nbsp;', 'EmotionScan', 'Emotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations with the goal of deciphering how customers really felt about money.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '957-autosave', '', '', '2014-05-29 21:54:06', '2014-05-29 09:54:06', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/957-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('970', '1', '2014-05-28 21:20:56', '2014-05-28 09:20:56', '', 'emotion-scan-featured', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'emotion-scan-featured', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:20:56', '2014-05-28 09:20:56', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/emotion-scan-featured.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('971', '1', '2014-05-28 21:19:19', '2014-05-28 09:19:19', '[gallery ids=\"959,960,961,962,964,965,967,958\"]\r\n\r\nEmotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations.\r\n\r\nWe then took the data points and plotted them against time. From that, we extrapolated how you felt about different types of financial topics depending on what emotions we could read off your face.\r\n\r\nI was involved in building the API which saved the data which we received from the facial recognition API and running it through an algorithm to turn it into meaningful, digestible results.\r\n\r\nThe main challenges arose from the facial recognition API not being particularly sturdy and we had to spend a lot of time working with its developer to get it working properly.\r\n\r\nThis campaign performed well and the client was happy with how it was received by their customers and clients.', 'EmotionScan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '957-revision-2', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:19:19', '2014-05-28 09:19:19', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/957-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('972', '1', '2014-05-28 21:42:28', '2014-05-28 09:42:28', '', 'emotion-scan-featured', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'emotion-scan-featured-2', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:42:28', '2014-05-28 09:42:28', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/emotion-scan-featured1.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('973', '1', '2014-05-28 21:41:15', '2014-05-28 09:41:15', '[gallery ids=\"959,960,961,962,964,965,967,958\"]\r\n\r\nEmotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations.\r\n\r\nWe then took the data points and plotted them against time. From that, we extrapolated how you felt about different types of financial topics depending on what emotions we could read off your face.\r\n\r\nI was involved in building the API which saved the data which we received from the facial recognition API and running it through an algorithm to turn it into meaningful, digestible results.\r\n\r\nThe main challenges arose from the facial recognition API not being particularly sturdy and we had to spend a lot of time working with its developer to get it working properly.\r\n\r\nThis campaign performed well and the client was happy with how it was received by their customers and clients.', 'EmotionScan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '957-revision-3', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:41:15', '2014-05-28 09:41:15', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/957-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('974', '1', '2014-05-28 21:43:43', '2014-05-28 09:43:43', '', 'emotion-scan-featured', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'emotion-scan-featured-3', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:43:43', '2014-05-28 09:43:43', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/emotion-scan-featured2.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('975', '1', '2014-05-28 21:43:05', '2014-05-28 09:43:05', '[gallery ids=\"959,960,961,962,964,965,967,958\"]\r\n\r\nEmotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations.\r\n\r\nWe then took the data points and plotted them against time. From that, we extrapolated how you felt about different types of financial topics depending on what emotions we could read off your face.\r\n\r\nI was involved in building the API which saved the data which we received from the facial recognition API and running it through an algorithm to turn it into meaningful, digestible results.\r\n\r\nThe main challenges arose from the facial recognition API not being particularly sturdy and we had to spend a lot of time working with its developer to get it working properly.\r\n\r\nThis campaign performed well and the client was happy with how it was received by their customers and clients.', 'EmotionScan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '957-revision-4', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:43:05'