tible results.\r\n\r\nThe main challenges arose from the facial recognition API not being particularly sturdy and we had to spend a lot of time working with its developer to get it working properly.\r\n\r\nThis campaign performed well and the client was happy with how it was received by their customers and clients.', 'EmotionScan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '957-revision-6', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:45:25', '2014-05-28 09:45:25', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/957-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('978', '1', '2014-05-28 21:46:06', '2014-05-28 09:46:06', '[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"958,967,965,964,962,961,960,959\"]\r\n\r\nEmotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations.\r\n\r\nWe then took the data points and plotted them against time. From that, we extrapolated how you felt about different types of financial topics depending on what emotions we could read off your face.\r\n\r\nI was involved in building the API which saved the data which we received from the facial recognition API and running it through an algorithm to turn it into meaningful, digestible results.\r\n\r\nThe main challenges arose from the facial recognition API not being particularly sturdy and we had to spend a lot of time working with its developer to get it working properly.\r\n\r\nThis campaign performed well and the client was happy with how it was received by their customers and clients.', 'EmotionScan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '957-revision-7', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:46:06', '2014-05-28 09:46:06', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/957-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('979', '1', '2014-05-28 22:03:57', '2014-05-28 10:03:57', '[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"987,986,985,984,983,982,981,980\"]\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis site intended to show people the kind of trouble the everyday freedoms they take for granted would get them into if they lived in a country which was not as free as New Zealand\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis site was built using HTML, CSS, Javascript and JQuery on top of the Zend Framework. It also used the Facebook JavaScript API and FQL to access users details. It used some advanced server optimization techniques like storing data in memcache and a custom built queuing system to help handle the large server loads it was hit with.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nAccessing every sing le bit of information on someone has on their facebook profile including posts, comments, photos, events, likes, relationship status\'s, right back to the day their account opened was a serious challenge. Running all of the required FQL queries would take quite a long time since we could only batch process i think 20 queries at once. The other big challenge was actually defining what constituted a crime in which countries, a lot of these data relationships had to be manually figured out and entered into a database for us to run our comparisons on.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nI had to write a custom queuing system which processed a queue of users every few minutes when a cron job fired. Also, rather than writing their data to the database immediately, we stored their information into memcache to speed up the response time of the server.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nTrial by timeline was a confronting piece of software. It was a huge success and the server ended up under heavy load as the campaign began to go viral. We had to do a fair bit of maintenance and optimization on the fly as this project ramped up to keep it running smoothly. It has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nFacebook Studio 2014: Blue award\r\n\r\nCannes 2013: Gold Lion, Bronze Lion\r\n\r\nD &amp; AD 2014: Yellow Pencil', 'Trial By Timeline', 'This campaign was a huge success and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'trial-by-timeline', '', '', '2014-05-29 22:08:09', '2014-05-29 10:08:09', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=979', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('980', '1', '2014-05-28 21:48:07', '2014-05-28 09:48:07', '', 'it would then display an interactive map of the countries you were convicted in', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0000s_0000_layer-188', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:48:07', '2014-05-28 09:48:07', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0000s_0000_Layer-188.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('981', '1', '2014-05-28 21:48:10', '2014-05-28 09:48:10', '', 'and quite serious', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0000s_0001_layer-187', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:48:10', '2014-05-28 09:48:10', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0000s_0001_Layer-187.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('982', '1', '2014-05-28 21:48:16', '2014-05-28 09:48:16', '', 'these were animated', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0000s_0002_layer-186', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:48:16', '2014-05-28 09:48:16', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0000s_0002_Layer-186.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('983', '1', '2014-05-28 21:48:22', '2014-05-28 09:48:22', '', 'It would show what type of sentence you would receive', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0000s_0003_layer-185', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:48:22', '2014-05-28 09:48:22', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0000s_0003_Layer-185.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('984', '1', '2014-05-28 21:48:31', '2014-05-28 09:48:31', '', 'It would list the countries which convictions were found', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0000s_0004_layer-182', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:48:31', '2014-05-28 09:48:31', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0000s_0004_Layer-182.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('985', '1', '2014-05-28 21:48:34', '2014-05-28 09:48:34', '', 'Every post, photo, event and all other data points were scanned', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0000s_0005_layer-179', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:48:34', '2014-05-28 09:48:34', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0000s_0005_Layer-179.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('986', '1', '2014-05-28 21:48:37', '2014-05-28 09:48:37', '', 'Clicking sentence would connect to facebook', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0000s_0006_layer-180', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:48:37', '2014-05-28 09:48:37', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0000s_0006_Layer-180.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('987', '1', '2014-05-28 21:48:41', '2014-05-28 09:48:41', '', 'Home page', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'portfolio-_0000s_0007_layer-177', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:48:41', '2014-05-28 09:48:41', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/portfolio-_0000s_0007_Layer-177.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('988', '1', '2014-05-28 22:03:33', '2014-05-28 10:03:33', '[gallery ids=\"987,986,985,984,983,982,981,980\"]\n\nTrial by timeline was a confronting piece of software. We got the user to login with facebook, we then looked at every data point we could. We searched posts, comments, photos, events, likes, relationship status anything we could get our hands on for any shred of information. There was a huge amount of manual data association done to give us the critera for what constitutes a crime. The users data was scanned all the way back to when they first signed up with facebook.\n\nThis provided some technical challenges in the form of needing to build a queueing system as the FQL queries would take a long time to execute. We also stored the data in memcache to improve load time rather than continually writing to the database.\n\nThis campaign was a huge success and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as\n\nFacebook Studio 2014: Blue award\n\nCannes 2013: Gold Lion, Bronze Lion\n\nD &amp; AD 2014: Yellow Pencil\n\n&nbsp;', 'Trial By Timeline', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '979-revision', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:03:33', '2014-05-28 10:03:33', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/979-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('989', '1', '2014-05-29 22:07:33', '2014-05-29 10:07:33', '[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"987,986,985,984,983,982,981,980\"]\n<h3>Goals</h3>\nThis site intended to show people the kind of trouble the everyday freedoms they take for granted would get them into if they lived in a country which was not as free as New Zealand\n<h3>Technology</h3>\nThis site was built using HTML, CSS, Javascript and JQuery on top of the Zend Framework. It also used the Facebook JavaScript API and FQL to access users details. It used some advanced server optimization techniques like storing data in memcache and a custom built queuing system to help handle the large server loads it was hit with.\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\nAccessing every sing le bit of information on someone has on their facebook profile including posts, comments, photos, events, likes, relationship status\'s, right back to the day their account opened was a serious challenge. Running all of the required FQL queries would take quite a long time since we could only batch process i think 20 queries at once. The other big challenge was actually defining what constituted a crime in which countries, a lot of these data relationships had to be manually figured out and entered into a database for us to run our comparisons on.\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\nI had to write a custom queuing system which processed a queue of users every few minutes when a cron job fired. Also, rather than writing their data to the database immediately, we stored their information into memcache to speed up the response time of the server.\n<h3>Results</h3>\nTrial by timeline was a confronting piece of software. It was a huge success and the server ended up under heavy load as the campaign began to go viral. We had to do a lot of maintainence  and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.\n<h3>Awards</h3>\nFacebook Studio 2014: Blue award\n\nCannes 2013: Gold Lion, Bronze Lion\n\nD &amp; AD 2014: Yellow Pencil', 'Trial By Timeline', 'This campaign was a huge success and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '979-autosave', '', '', '2014-05-29 22:07:33', '2014-05-29 10:07:33', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/979-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('990', '1', '2014-05-28 22:05:23', '2014-05-28 10:05:23', '', 'trial-featured', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'trial-featured', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:05:23', '2014-05-28 10:05:23', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/trial-featured.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('991', '1', '2014-05-28 22:03:57', '2014-05-28 10:03:57', '[gallery ids=\"987,986,985,984,983,982,981,980\"]\r\n\r\nTrial by timeline was a confronting piece of software. We got the user to login with facebook, we then looked at every data point we could. We searched posts, comments, photos, events, likes, relationship status anything we could get our hands on for any shred of information. There was a huge amount of manual data association done to give us the critera for what constitutes a crime. The users data was scanned all the way back to when they first signed up with facebook.\r\n\r\nThis provided some technical challenges in the form of needing to build a queueing system as the FQL queries would take a long time to execute. We also stored the data in memcache to improve load time rather than continually writing to the database.\r\n\r\nThis campaign was a huge success and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.\r\n\r\nFacebook Studio 2014: Blue award\r\n\r\nCannes 2013: Gold Lion, Bronze Lion\r\n\r\nD &amp; AD 2014: Yellow Pencil\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Trial By Timeline', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '979-revision-2', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:03:57', '2014-05-28 10:03:57', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/979-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('992', '1', '2014-05-28 22:05:29', '2014-05-28 10:05:29', '[gallery ids=\"987,986,985,984,983,982,981,980\"]\r\n\r\nTrial by timeline was a confronting piece of software. We got the user to login with facebook, we then looked at every data point we could. We searched posts, comments, photos, events, likes, relationship status anything we could get our hands on for any shred of information. There was a huge amount of manual data association done to give us the critera for what constitutes a crime. The users data was scanned all the way back to when they first signed up with facebook.\r\n\r\nThis provided some technical challenges in the form of needing to build a queueing system as the FQL queries would take a long time to execute. We also stored the data in memcache to improve load time rather than continually writing to the database.\r\n\r\nThis campaign was a huge success and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.\r\n\r\nFacebook Studio 2014: Blue award\r\n\r\nCannes 2013: Gold Lion, Bronze Lion\r\n\r\nD &amp; AD 2014: Yellow Pencil', 'Trial By Timeline', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '979-revision-3', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:05:29', '2014-05-28 10:05:29', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/979-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('993', '1', '2014-05-28 22:07:04', '2014-05-28 10:07:04', '[gallery ids=\"987,986,985,984,983,982,981,980\"]\r\n\r\nTrial by timeline was a confronting piece of software. We got the user to login with facebook, we then looked at every data point we could. We searched posts, comments, photos, events, likes, relationship status anything we could get our hands on for any shred of information. There was a huge amount of manual data association done to give us the critera for what constitutes a crime. The users data was scanned all the way back to when they first signed up with facebook.\r\n\r\nThis provided some technical challenges in the form of needing to build a queueing system as the FQL queries would take a long time to execute. We also stored the data in memcache to improve load time rather than continually writing to the database.\r\n\r\nThis campaign was a huge success and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.\r\n\r\nFacebook Studio 2014: Blue award\r\n\r\nCannes 2013: Gold Lion, Bronze Lion\r\n\r\nD &amp; AD 2014: Yellow Pencil', 'Trial By Timeline', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '979-revision-4', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:07:04', '2014-05-28 10:07:04', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/979-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('994', '1', '2014-05-28 21:46:49', '2014-05-28 09:46:49', '[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"958,967,965,964,962,961,960,959\"]\r\n\r\nEmotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations.\r\n\r\nWe then took the data points and plotted them against time. From that, we extrapolated how you felt about different types of financial topics depending on what emotions we could read off your face.\r\n\r\nI was involved in building the API which saved the data which we received from the facial recognition API and running it through an algorithm to turn it into meaningful, digestible results.\r\n\r\nThe main challenges arose from the facial recognition API not being particularly sturdy and we had to spend a lot of time working with its developer to get it working properly.\r\n\r\nThis campaign performed well and the client was happy with how it was received by their customers and clients.', 'EmotionScan', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '957-revision-8', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:46:49', '2014-05-28 09:46:49', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/957-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1033', '1', '2014-06-07 18:06:07', '2014-06-07 06:06:07', 'Raspberry Pi\'s are fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'an-introduction-to-raspberry-pi', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:57:38', '2015-04-04 01:57:38', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=1033', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('1159', '1', '2015-04-04 13:58:52', '2015-04-04 01:58:52', 'Writing server scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet using PHP? Here’s a quickstart guide which should be able to get you up and running in no time.\n\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\n\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\n\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\n\nStart the daemon:\n\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\n~$ ./bitcoind\n[/sourcecode]\n\nCreate a new address\n\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\n[/sourcecode]\n\ncheck the balance of the wallet\n\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\n[/sourcecode]\n\netc...\n\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\n\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\n//include the easybitcoin source\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\n\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\n\n//start making RCP calls\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\n[/sourcecode]\n\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\n\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\n\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-autosave', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:58:52', '2015-04-04 01:58:52', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('996', '1', '2013-02-28 12:58:36', '2013-02-28 00:58:36', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Comments made on facebook would appear on live TV.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Ulive comments page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could vote in polls which would be discussed by the presenters\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Ulive voting page \" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could stream Ulive from within the app\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Ulive streaming page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could invite their friends to take part in the discussions\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Ulive invite page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a Facebook app housed on the TVNZU page which allowed facebook users to watch the live show. It was to allow the users to get involved in the discussions the presenters were having and even get their comments to appear in real time on live TV. It was also to create a sense of community within the users friends by allowing them to invite their friends to watch the show and also display a list of which of your friends were currently tuned in via the app.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built on the Zend Framework and implements the Facebook API, JQuery, AJAX, a custom scroll bar JS library and of course HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was that discussion feed needed to have the same user experience as Facebook but the feed functionality isn\'t part of the Facebook API and it needed to poll the server to add new comments without refreshing. The app also had to integrate with the users friends list and keep a track of who was online so we could display if any of your friends were watching and also have an invite mechanic. There was also the archiving of old discussions and polls as well as the feed moderation for the comments that went to air and CMS for the app.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWe had to recreate the Facebook feed\'s functionality from scratch with the added ability to flag posts for moderator review. This became a very difficult task when there\'s so much integration. Every time we AJAX\'d in a new set of posts we had to bump the same number off the bottom so the pagination was intact while keeping their indexes for the likes and times all correct. We had to update the posts times, amount of likes and comment totals and then once everything was loaded, refresh the custom scroll bar height. The scroll lock button paused new comments from auto-updating which was also quite difficult to get working seamlessly.\r\n\r\nConnecting people with their friends was an important part of the app. We kept a database record of the Facebook ID\'s of everyone who logged into the app against a timestamp and if you\'d polled our server in the last 30 seconds we considered you to be in current use of the app. We then would look at the logged in users friends list and cross section that with the people who are currently logged in and display their profile picture and a link to their profile in a grid under the X Friends Watching heading. From here you could also invite your friends to watch the show through the Ulive app and this was done with the Facebook API\'s App Invite functionality.\r\n\r\nThe CMS was relatively straight forward, once a comment was approved to go to air it would be sent via a CURL request to an API at the TVNZ studio. This would then run through their system and be put up on the screen along with the users Name, Profile pic and Age which we got from their Facebook profile.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project turned out to be a great piece of programming. The integration of so many technologies ended up seeming pretty smooth despite having to do a lot of bug fixing and tying up loose ends. Integrating a Facebook app with a live TV show was a first for me and actually a world wide first which caught the attention of a lot of people in technology sphere.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis app was featured on the Facebook developer blog and was also featured on quite a few online newspapers and blogs.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"U Live\" href=\"https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive\" target=\"_blank\">https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive\r\n\r\n</a>', 'Ulive', 'This project encompassed a wide range of web technologies. It was the first facebook app to allow users to interact with live television and was featured on facebook\'s developer blog.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '337-revision-36', '', '', '2013-02-28 12:58:36', '2013-02-28 00:58:36', '', '337', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/337-revision-36/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('997', '1', '2013-02-27 12:26:39', '2013-02-27 00:26:39', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"By drinking Pepsi and redeeming codes, users could win a holiday with their mates\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-438\" alt=\"bromitment-screen1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users allowed the facebook app and filled out their details to create a profile\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-439\" alt=\"bromitment-screen2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then select 3 friends they wanted to take on the holiday through the custom friend picker\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-440\" alt=\"bromitment-screen3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The picked friends would then be messaged on facebook to ask them to join\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-441\" alt=\"bromitment-screen4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"All the users in the group could enter codes to boost their chances of winning\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen9.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-442\" alt=\"bromitment-screen9\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen9-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"If a user hadn\'t entered a code that day, the group leader could &quot;peer pressure&quot; them\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen10.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-443\" alt=\"bromitment-screen10\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen10-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users were &quot;peer pressured&quot; into entering codes by having one of our videos posted to their profile\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen11.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-444\" alt=\"bromitment-screen11\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen11-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The more codes your users entered per day gained you bonus entries\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen12.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-445\" alt=\"bromitment-screen12\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen12-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nPepsi Max Bromitment aimed to engage users to drink more Pepsi by getting users and their Bro\'s to make a commitment to each other. Teams were formed and entered product codes gave you points into the draw to win a holiday for you and your team.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook API and AMF.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge here for me was building the API and integrating it with the flash front end and making the communication secure. The game seemed simple enough but there was a lot of hidden twists which made some of the logic quite difficult.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWith smart class architecture I was able to minimize the amount of code written. Using a lot of smaller private functions rather than repeating code helped reduce the impact of functional changes or bug fixes. As with any competition, we encrypted the communication with a token so that it was much harder for someone to send requests directly to the API.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nBromitment was well executed from a design and development perspective, however I believe the mechanic itself was too convoluted for a lot of people to engage with.  It tried to take a pyramid scheme approach which meant that to be part of someone else\'s team, i have to create my own team with 3 other people. While this was supposed to help drive involvement i think it basically confused people as to where their codes were being applied and how the scheme worked.\r\n<h3>Notes</h3>\r\nThis was the the first full API I had written solo and despite not being hugely well received as a campaign, I was extremely happy with how the code ran.', 'Bromitment', 'Pepsi Max Bromitment aimed to engage users to drink more Pepsi by getting users and their Bro\'s to make a commitment to each other. Teams were formed and entered product codes gave you points into the draw to win a holiday for you and your team.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '426-revision-15', '', '', '2013-02-27 12:26:39', '2013-02-27 00:26:39', '', '426', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/426-revision-15/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('998', '1', '2014-05-28 22:10:46', '2014-05-28 10:10:46', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"By drinking Pepsi and redeeming codes, users could win a holiday with their mates\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-438\" alt=\"bromitment-screen1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users allowed the facebook app and filled out their details to create a profile\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-439\" alt=\"bromitment-screen2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then select 3 friends they wanted to take on the holiday through the custom friend picker\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-440\" alt=\"bromitment-screen3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The picked friends would then be messaged on facebook to ask them to join\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-441\" alt=\"bromitment-screen4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"All the users in the group could enter codes to boost their chances of winning\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen9.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-442\" alt=\"bromitment-screen9\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen9-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"If a user hadn\'t entered a code that day, the group leader could &quot;peer pressure&quot; them\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen10.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-443\" alt=\"bromitment-screen10\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen10-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users were &quot;peer pressured&quot; into entering codes by having one of our videos posted to their profile\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen11.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-444\" alt=\"bromitment-screen11\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen11-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The more codes your users entered per day gained you bonus entries\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen12.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-445\" alt=\"bromitment-screen12\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen12-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nPepsi Max Bromitment aimed to engage users to drink more Pepsi by getting users and their Bro\'s to make a commitment to each other. Teams were formed and entered product codes gave you points into the draw to win a holiday for you and your team.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook API and AMF.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge here for me was building the API and integrating it with the flash front end and making the communication secure. The game seemed simple enough but there was a lot of hidden twists which made some of the logic quite difficult.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWith smart class architecture I was able to minimize the amount of code written. Using a lot of smaller private functions rather than repeating code helped reduce the impact of functional changes or bug fixes. As with any competition, we encrypted the communication with a token so that it was much harder for someone to send requests directly to the API.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nBromitment was well executed from a design and development perspective, however I believe the mechanic itself was too convoluted for a lot of people to engage with.  It tried to take a pyramid scheme approach which meant that to be part of someone else\'s team, i have to create my own team with 3 other people. While this was supposed to help drive involvement i think it basically confused people as to where their codes were being applied and how the scheme worked.\r\n<h3>Notes</h3>\r\nThis was the the first full API I had written solo and despite not being hugely well received as a campaign, I was extremely happy with how the code ran.', 'Bromitment', 'Pepsi Max Bromitment aimed to engage users to drink more Pepsi by getting users and their Bro\'s to make a commitment to each other. Teams were formed and entered product codes gave you points into the draw to win a holiday for you and your team.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '426-revision-16', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:10:46', '2014-05-28 10:10:46', '', '426', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/426-revision-16/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('999', '1', '2013-02-28 12:59:17', '2013-02-28 00:59:17', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could take a picture using their webcam\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Webcam\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site used NEC facial recognition software to scan the users facial features\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Image Processing\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"NEC\'s results were used to pair the user with a dog from the SPCA\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Results\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could share their results on Facebook\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Share \" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"Doggelganger\" href=\"http://www.doggelganger.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.doggelganger.co.nz\r\n\r\n</a>', 'Doggelganger', 'Doggelganger used security grade facial recognition software to match your face with a dog who is up for adoption from the SPCA animal shelter. Its won a Gold at Cannes, the Grand Axis award and many more.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '372-revision-20', '', '', '2013-02-28 12:59:17', '2013-02-28 00:59:17', '', '372', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/372-revision-20/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1000', '1', '2014-05-28 22:10:10', '2014-05-28 10:10:10', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Comments made on facebook would appear on live TV.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Ulive comments page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could vote in polls which would be discussed by the presenters\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Ulive voting page \" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could stream Ulive from within the app\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Ulive streaming page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could invite their friends to take part in the discussions\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Ulive invite page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a Facebook app housed on the TVNZU page which allowed facebook users to watch the live show. It was to allow the users to get involved in the discussions the presenters were having and even get their comments to appear in real time on live TV. It was also to create a sense of community within the users friends by allowing them to invite their friends to watch the show and also display a list of which of your friends were currently tuned in via the app.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built on the Zend Framework and implements the Facebook API, JQuery, AJAX, a custom scroll bar JS library and of course HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was that discussion feed needed to have the same user experience as Facebook but the feed functionality isn\'t part of the Facebook API and it needed to poll the server to add new comments without refreshing. The app also had to integrate with the users friends list and keep a track of who was online so we could display if any of your friends were watching and also have an invite mechanic. There was also the archiving of old discussions and polls as well as the feed moderation for the comments that went to air and CMS for the app.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWe had to recreate the Facebook feed\'s functionality from scratch with the added ability to flag posts for moderator review. This became a very difficult task when there\'s so much integration. Every time we AJAX\'d in a new set of posts we had to bump the same number off the bottom so the pagination was intact while keeping their indexes for the likes and times all correct. We had to update the posts times, amount of likes and comment totals and then once everything was loaded, refresh the custom scroll bar height. The scroll lock button paused new comments from auto-updating which was also quite difficult to get working seamlessly.\r\n\r\nConnecting people with their friends was an important part of the app. We kept a database record of the Facebook ID\'s of everyone who logged into the app against a timestamp and if you\'d polled our server in the last 30 seconds we considered you to be in current use of the app. We then would look at the logged in users friends list and cross section that with the people who are currently logged in and display their profile picture and a link to their profile in a grid under the X Friends Watching heading. From here you could also invite your friends to watch the show through the Ulive app and this was done with the Facebook API\'s App Invite functionality.\r\n\r\nThe CMS was relatively straight forward, once a comment was approved to go to air it would be sent via a CURL request to an API at the TVNZ studio. This would then run through their system and be put up on the screen along with the users Name, Profile pic and Age which we got from their Facebook profile.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project turned out to be a great piece of programming. The integration of so many technologies ended up seeming pretty smooth despite having to do a lot of bug fixing and tying up loose ends. Integrating a Facebook app with a live TV show was a first for me and actually a world wide first which caught the attention of a lot of people in technology sphere.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis app was featured on the Facebook developer blog and was also featured on quite a few online newspapers and blogs.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"U Live\" href=\"https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive\" target=\"_blank\">https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Ulive', 'This project encompassed a wide range of web technologies. It was the first facebook app to allow users to interact with live television and was featured on facebook\'s developer blog.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '337-revision-37', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:10:10', '2014-05-28 10:10:10', '', '337', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/337-revision-37/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1001', '1', '2013-02-27 14:58:22', '2013-02-27 02:58:22', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The Facebook tab app has a like gate to unlock content for fans only\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-474\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer 2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could log into their V Republic account while still in Facebook\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer-88.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-473\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer 88\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer-88-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"If they didnt have an account they could register while still in Facebook too\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer-89.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-472\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer 89\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer-89-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They had to try and guess what flavor combinations the new V Blue was to win $10,000\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-471\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer 91\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the facebook app product launch for the new blue flavor of V Energy drink. The main goal was to raise awareness of the new product by running a competition to give away $10,000 to anyone who guessed the flavor correctly.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook API and and is a Facebook App served inside a tab.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe competition needed to be restricted to people who like the V Energy Facebook page with what is known as a \"Like Gate\". The rest of the build was fairly simple as its simple just a form in a light box essentially. The form did however have to plug in to a Frucor\'s CRM database which was also worth noting.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nUsing the facebook API we were able to find out if the user likes the V Energy Page. If they like it, then we show the login screen, otherwise we show the lock screen. Once the user clicks the like button at the top of the tab, the page is forced to refresh by facebook which would reveal the login screen. The V CRM and the Database for the competition resided on different servers, so there was a bit of setup involved on the hosting side of things to allow database connections from different servers.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThe competition went really well with lots of user engagement. The facebook app was also considered such an easy and good format that it has been re skinned and re purposed multiple times since to run more competitions with.', 'V Blue Facebook Tab', 'This was the facebook app product launch for the new blue flavor of V Energy drink. The main goal was to raise awareness of the new product by running a competition to give away $10,000 to anyone who guessed what the flavor was. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '470-revision-12', '', '', '2013-02-27 14:58:22', '2013-02-27 02:58:22', '', '470', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/470-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1002', '1', '2013-02-28 13:00:48', '2013-02-28 01:00:48', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The homepage has a custom slideshow gallery and all the content is manageable\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-459\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0003_Background\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0003_Background-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The menu featured a custom accordion style menu with sub sections\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-458\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer 74\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0002_screens_0006s_0012_Layer-74-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The map can find you by GPS and show the nearest BK or you could search\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-457\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer 75\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0001_screens_0006s_0011_Layer-75-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The contact form sends email directly to their customer service team\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-456\" alt=\"bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer 78\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bk-brandsite_0000_screens_0006s_0008_Layer-78-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis site was intended to give BK a more comprehensive online presence and bring their site up to date with some of the new web technologies.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with a comprehensive Content Management System. It also implements the Google Maps API and JQuery.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was the integration of the Google Maps into both the front end and the CMS. The Google Map had to show the user searched store locations and prioritize them in order of proximity to the user or the searched term.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nTo load the stores into the database I wrote a script to initialize the database entries automatically from an address list. This method worked with some but not all of the addresses, particularly those newer locations or ones in shopping complexes. We ended up coding a Google Map in the CMS which the admin could click on the map to record those latitude and longitude coordinates against that store. This proved to be the most useful way of getting the coordinates exact. Then using the latitude and longitude of the stores combined with either the users coordinates or the search terms coordinates we could use the Google Maps API to find the distance between the two points and then use that to order the returned results.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThe BK Brand site is a solid piece of code which was put together both efficiently and well. Its cross compatible with all modern browsers and can even read the GPS coordinates if you\'re on a smart phone to show you your nearest stores. As far as a fast food brand site goes, this is definitely up the times.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"BK Brand Site\" href=\"http://www.burgerking.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.burgerking.co.nz\r\n\r\n</a>', 'BK Brand Site', 'This site was intended to give BK a more comprehensive online presence and bring their site up to date with some of the new web technologies.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '454-revision-12', '', '', '2013-02-28 13:00:48', '2013-02-28 01:00:48', '', '454', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/454-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1008', '1', '2014-05-28 22:13:16', '2014-05-28 10:13:16', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Comments made on facebook would appear on live TV.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Ulive comments page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could vote in polls which would be discussed by the presenters\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Ulive voting page \" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Facebook users could stream Ulive from within the app\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Ulive streaming page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could invite their friends to take part in the discussions\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Ulive invite page\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a Facebook app housed on the TVNZU page which allowed facebook users to watch the live show. It was to allow the users to get involved in the discussions the presenters were having and even get their comments to appear in real time on live TV. It was also to create a sense of community within the users friends by allowing them to invite their friends to watch the show and also display a list of which of your friends were currently tuned in via the app.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built on the Zend Framework and implements the Facebook API, JQuery, AJAX, a custom scroll bar JS library and of course HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was that discussion feed needed to have the same user experience as Facebook but the feed functionality isn\'t part of the Facebook API and it needed to poll the server to add new comments without refreshing. The app also had to integrate with the users friends list and keep a track of who was online so we could display if any of your friends were watching and also have an invite mechanic. There was also the archiving of old discussions and polls as well as the feed moderation for the comments that went to air and CMS for the app.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWe had to recreate the Facebook feed\'s functionality from scratch with the added ability to flag posts for moderator review. This became a very difficult task when there\'s so much integration. Every time we AJAX\'d in a new set of posts we had to bump the same number off the bottom so the pagination was intact while keeping their indexes for the likes and times all correct. We had to update the posts times, amount of likes and comment totals and then once everything was loaded, refresh the custom scroll bar height. The scroll lock button paused new comments from auto-updating which was also quite difficult to get working seamlessly.\r\n\r\nConnecting people with their friends was an important part of the app. We kept a database record of the Facebook ID\'s of everyone who logged into the app against a timestamp and if you\'d polled our server in the last 30 seconds we considered you to be in current use of the app. We then would look at the logged in users friends list and cross section that with the people who are currently logged in and display their profile picture and a link to their profile in a grid under the X Friends Watching heading. From here you could also invite your friends to watch the show through the Ulive app and this was done with the Facebook API\'s App Invite functionality.\r\n\r\nThe CMS was relatively straight forward, once a comment was approved to go to air it would be sent via a CURL request to an API at the TVNZ studio. This would then run through their system and be put up on the screen along with the users Name, Profile pic and Age which we got from their Facebook profile.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project turned out to be a great piece of programming. The integration of so many technologies ended up seeming pretty smooth despite having to do a lot of bug fixing and tying up loose ends. Integrating a Facebook app with a live TV show was a first for me and actually a world wide first which caught the attention of a lot of people in technology sphere.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis app was featured on the Facebook developer blog and was also featured on quite a few online newspapers and blogs.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"U Live\" href=\"https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive\" target=\"_blank\">https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive</a>', 'Ulive', 'This project encompassed a wide range of web technologies. It was the first facebook app to allow users to interact with live television and was featured on facebook\'s developer blog.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '337-revision-38', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:13:16', '2014-05-28 10:13:16', '', '337', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/337-revision-38/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1003', '1', '2014-05-28 22:11:52', '2014-05-28 10:11:52', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could take a picture using their webcam\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Webcam\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site used NEC facial recognition software to scan the users facial features\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Image Processing\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"NEC\'s results were used to pair the user with a dog from the SPCA\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Results\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could share their results on Facebook\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Share \" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"Doggelganger\" href=\"http://www.doggelganger.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.doggelganger.co.nz</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Doggelganger', 'Doggelganger used security grade facial recognition software to match your face with a dog who is up for adoption from the SPCA animal shelter. Its won a Gold at Cannes, the Grand Axis award and many more.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '372-revision-21', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:11:52', '2014-05-28 10:11:52', '', '372', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/372-revision-21/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1005', '1', '2014-05-28 22:22:28', '2014-05-28 10:22:28', '', 'Archive', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1004-revision', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:22:28', '2014-05-28 10:22:28', '', '1004', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1004-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1006', '1', '2014-05-28 22:22:30', '2014-05-28 10:22:30', '', 'Archive', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1004-revision-2', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:22:30', '2014-05-28 10:22:30', '', '1004', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1004-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1007', '1', '2014-05-28 22:14:43', 