>\r\nThis site was intended to give BK a more comprehensive online presence and bring their site up to date with some of the new web technologies.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with a comprehensive Content Management System. It also implements the Google Maps API and JQuery.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was the integration of the Google Maps into both the front end and the CMS. The Google Map had to show the user searched store locations and prioritize them in order of proximity to the user or the searched term.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nTo load the stores into the database I wrote a script to initialize the database entries automatically from an address list. This method worked with some but not all of the addresses, particularly those newer locations or ones in shopping complexes. We ended up coding a Google Map in the CMS which the admin could click on the map to record those latitude and longitude coordinates against that store. This proved to be the most useful way of getting the coordinates exact. Then using the latitude and longitude of the stores combined with either the users coordinates or the search terms coordinates we could use the Google Maps API to find the distance between the two points and then use that to order the returned results.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThe BK Brand site is a solid piece of code which was put together both efficiently and well. Its cross compatible with all modern browsers and can even read the GPS coordinates if you\'re on a smart phone to show you your nearest stores. As far as a fast food brand site goes, this is definitely up the times.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"BK Brand Site\" href=\"http://www.burgerking.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.burgerking.co.nz</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'BK Brand Site', 'This site was intended to give BK a more comprehensive online presence and bring their site up to date with some of the new web technologies.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '454-revision-13', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:14:43', '2014-05-28 10:14:43', '', '454', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/454-revision-13/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1009', '1', '2014-05-28 22:14:16', '2014-05-28 10:14:16', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The Facebook tab app has a like gate to unlock content for fans only\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-474\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer 2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0003_Layer-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could log into their V Republic account while still in Facebook\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer-88.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-473\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer 88\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0002_screens_0005s_0004_Layer-88-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"If they didnt have an account they could register while still in Facebook too\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer-89.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-472\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer 89\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0001_screens_0005s_0003_Layer-89-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They had to try and guess what flavor combinations the new V Blue was to win $10,000\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-471\" alt=\"v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer 91\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/v-blue-facebook_0000_screens_0005s_0001_Layer-91-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the facebook app product launch for the new blue flavor of V Energy drink. The main goal was to raise awareness of the new product by running a competition to give away $10,000 to anyone who guessed the flavor correctly.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook API and and is a Facebook App served inside a tab.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe competition needed to be restricted to people who like the V Energy Facebook page with what is known as a \"Like Gate\". The rest of the build was fairly simple as its simple just a form in a light box essentially. The form did however have to plug in to a Frucor\'s CRM database which was also worth noting.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nUsing the facebook API we were able to find out if the user likes the V Energy Page. If they like it, then we show the login screen, otherwise we show the lock screen. Once the user clicks the like button at the top of the tab, the page is forced to refresh by facebook which would reveal the login screen. The V CRM and the Database for the competition resided on different servers, so there was a bit of setup involved on the hosting side of things to allow database connections from different servers.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThe competition went really well with lots of user engagement. The facebook app was also considered such an easy and good format that it has been re skinned and re purposed multiple times since to run more competitions with.', 'V Blue Facebook Tab', 'This was the facebook app product launch for the new blue flavor of V Energy drink. The main goal was to raise awareness of the new product by running a competition to give away $10,000 to anyone who guessed what the flavor was. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '470-revision-13', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:14:16', '2014-05-28 10:14:16', '', '470', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/470-revision-13/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1010', '1', '2014-05-28 22:11:14', '2014-05-28 10:11:14', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"By drinking Pepsi and redeeming codes, users could win a holiday with their mates\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-438\" alt=\"bromitment-screen1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users allowed the facebook app and filled out their details to create a profile\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-439\" alt=\"bromitment-screen2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"They could then select 3 friends they wanted to take on the holiday through the custom friend picker\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-440\" alt=\"bromitment-screen3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The picked friends would then be messaged on facebook to ask them to join\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-441\" alt=\"bromitment-screen4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"All the users in the group could enter codes to boost their chances of winning\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen9.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-442\" alt=\"bromitment-screen9\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen9-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"If a user hadn\'t entered a code that day, the group leader could &quot;peer pressure&quot; them\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen10.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-443\" alt=\"bromitment-screen10\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen10-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users were &quot;peer pressured&quot; into entering codes by having one of our videos posted to their profile\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen11.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-444\" alt=\"bromitment-screen11\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen11-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The more codes your users entered per day gained you bonus entries\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen12.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-445\" alt=\"bromitment-screen12\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/bromitment-screen12-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nPepsi Max Bromitment aimed to engage users to drink more Pepsi by getting users and their Bro\'s to make a commitment to each other. Teams were formed and entered product codes gave you points into the draw to win a holiday for you and your team.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook API and AMF.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge here for me was building the API and integrating it with the flash front end and making the communication secure. The game seemed simple enough but there was a lot of hidden twists which made some of the logic quite difficult.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWith smart class architecture I was able to minimize the amount of code written. Using a lot of smaller private functions rather than repeating code helped reduce the impact of functional changes or bug fixes. As with any competition, we encrypted the communication with a token so that it was much harder for someone to send requests directly to the API.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nBromitment was well executed from a design and development perspective, however I believe the mechanic itself was too convoluted for a lot of people to engage with.  It tried to take a pyramid scheme approach which meant that to be part of someone else\'s team, i have to create my own team with 3 other people. While this was supposed to help drive involvement i think it basically confused people as to where their codes were being applied and how the scheme worked.\r\n<h3>Notes</h3>\r\nThis was the the first full API I had written solo and despite not being hugely well received as a campaign, I was extremely happy with how the code ran.', 'Bromitment', 'Pepsi Max Bromitment aimed to engage users to drink more Pepsi by getting users and their Bro\'s to make a commitment to each other. Teams were formed and entered product codes gave you points into the draw to win a holiday for you and your team.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '426-revision-17', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:11:14', '2014-05-28 10:11:14', '', '426', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/426-revision-17/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1011', '1', '2014-05-28 22:23:24', '2014-05-28 10:23:24', '', 'Archive', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1004-revision-3', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:23:24', '2014-05-28 10:23:24', '', '1004', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1004-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1012', '1', '2014-05-28 22:24:38', '2014-05-28 10:24:38', '', 'Archive', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1004-revision-4', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:24:38', '2014-05-28 10:24:38', '', '1004', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1004-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1013', '1', '2014-05-28 22:25:23', '2014-05-28 10:25:23', '', 'zArchive', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1004-revision-5', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:25:23', '2014-05-28 10:25:23', '', '1004', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1004-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1014', '1', '2014-05-28 22:25:39', '2014-05-28 10:25:39', '', 'zArchive', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1004-revision-6', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:25:39', '2014-05-28 10:25:39', '', '1004', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1004-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1015', '1', '2014-05-28 22:25:43', '2014-05-28 10:25:43', '', 'Archive', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1004-revision-7', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:25:43', '2014-05-28 10:25:43', '', '1004', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1004-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1016', '1', '2014-05-28 22:08:16', '2014-05-28 10:08:16', '[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"958,967,965,964,962,961,960,959\"]\r\n\r\nEmotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations.\r\n\r\nWe then took the data points and plotted them against time. From that, we extrapolated how you felt about different types of financial topics depending on what emotions we could read off your face.\r\n\r\nI was involved in building the API which saved the data which we received from the facial recognition API and running it through an algorithm to turn it into meaningful, digestible results.\r\n\r\nThe main challenges arose from the facial recognition API not being particularly sturdy and we had to spend a lot of time working with its developer to get it working properly.\r\n\r\nThis campaign performed well and the client was happy with how it was received by their customers and clients.', 'EmotionScan', 'Emotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '957-revision-9', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:08:16', '2014-05-28 10:08:16', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/957-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1017', '1', '2014-05-28 21:04:44', '2014-05-28 09:04:44', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could choose your avatar for the queue and it would put your facebook profile picture on as the head.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your queue position was determined by your social influence i.e. shares, likes, comments, re-tweets etc.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Each day new content was revealed to share on facebook and twitter\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The content consisted of different types of media\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There were even quizzes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nAxis - Grand Prix - Out of home\r\n\r\nAxis - Gold - Digital and Interactive\r\n\r\nAxis - Gold - Integrated\r\n\r\nAxis - Silver - Social', 'Get in line: Galaxy S4 Launch', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-23', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:04:44', '2014-05-28 09:04:44', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-23/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1018', '1', '2014-05-28 22:07:14', '2014-05-28 10:07:14', '[gallery ids=\"987,986,985,984,983,982,981,980\"]\r\n\r\nTrial by timeline was a confronting piece of software. We got the user to login with facebook, we then looked at every data point we could. We searched posts, comments, photos, events, likes, relationship status anything we could get our hands on for any shred of information. There was a huge amount of manual data association done to give us the critera for what constitutes a crime. The users data was scanned all the way back to when they first signed up with facebook.\r\n\r\nThis provided some technical challenges in the form of needing to build a queueing system as the FQL queries would take a long time to execute. We also stored the data in memcache to improve load time rather than continually writing to the database.\r\n\r\nThis campaign was a huge success and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.\r\n\r\nFacebook Studio 2014: Blue award\r\n\r\nCannes 2013: Gold Lion, Bronze Lion\r\n\r\nD &amp; AD 2014: Yellow Pencil', 'Trial By Timeline', 'This campaign was a huge success and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '979-revision-5', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:07:14', '2014-05-28 10:07:14', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/979-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1019', '1', '2014-05-28 20:58:29', '2014-05-28 08:58:29', 'Holiday replay enabled people to connect with Facebook and write a story about how they lost cash while on holiday. We would then take their story and match the words up with keywords in our database which were mapped to images and video content that would be compiled along with any facebook photos found of that holiday, into a video sequence with the music track they selected.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"915,922,921,920,919,918,917,916\"]\r\n\r\nThey were able to review the images pulled from facebook for their story and remove any unwanted ones. They could then upload new ones from their facebook gallery or directly from their computer before submitting it to our gallery.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"928,927,926,924\"]\r\n\r\nTheir submitted stories ended up in a searchable gallery where they could be voted on. They could be shared on Facebook and even played within the time line until facebook removed SWF support from timeline posts.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" columns=\"4\" ids=\"930,935,941,942\"]\r\n\r\nHoliday Replay was a unique project with a lot of technical aspects to work through. I was the lead developer on this project, guiding the other two developers and ensuring their work pieced together into the final product. I developed the back end of this application which consisted of all the API calls to get and save data along with a complex algorithm to figure out the users frame sequence.\r\n\r\nWe had a huge amount of manually compiled stock imagery which was linked to locations and key words. For example if you used the word \"taxi\" and your story was geo tagged as in New York, the background image of that frame would be the iconic yellow taxi of New York. However if it were geo tagged as being in London, you would get an image of their also iconic black taxi cabs.\r\n\r\nIf we couldn\'t match the word, we\'d pull media that was related to the geo tagged location. We\'d also look up any albums you had from that location and splice in some of your facebook images at appropriate intervals.\r\n\r\nEach frame was also assigned a custom font for the text, animation and static graphic to border the text.\r\n\r\nOne of the other developers took care of the front end of the site, while the third took care of compiling and animating the video sequence.\r\n\r\nBehind the scenes, this job was huge. It involved a custom API, uploading users files to the cloud, facebook FQL queries, the Google Places API, Geo Coding, Canvas, HTML5, SCSS, jQuery &amp; Flash. The whole experience was mobile optimized to full functionality. You could submit, edit and watch the compiled video\'s all from your mobile phone or tablet.\r\n\r\nThe campaign performed well and has just come to a close. I\'ll update this post with some stats once they\'re available.', 'Holiday Replay', 'Holiday Replay was a unique project with a lot of technical aspects to work through. I was the lead developer on this project, I built the API behind it and guided the other two developers, ensuring their work pieced together into the final product.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '823-revision-39', '', '', '2014-05-28 20:58:29', '2014-05-28 08:58:29', '', '823', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/823-revision-39/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1020', '1', '2014-05-28 23:00:36', '2014-05-28 11:00:36', '[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"958,967,965,964,962,961,960,959\"]\r\n\r\nEmotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations.\r\n\r\nWe then took the data points and plotted them against time. From that, we extrapolated how you felt about different types of financial topics depending on what emotions we could read off your face.\r\n\r\nI was involved in building the API which saved the data which we received from the facial recognition API and running it through an algorithm to turn it into meaningful, digestible results.\r\n\r\nThe main challenges arose from the facial recognition API not being particularly sturdy and we had to spend a lot of time working with its developer to get it working properly.\r\n\r\nThis campaign performed well and the client was happy with how it was received by their customers and clients.', 'EmotionScan', 'Emotion Scan is an interesting site. We used facial recognition software to map your face as you listen to an emotive narrative about financial situations with the goal of deciphering how customers really felt about money.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '957-revision-10', '', '', '2014-05-28 23:00:36', '2014-05-28 11:00:36', '', '957', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/957-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1021', '1', '2014-05-28 22:21:08', '2014-05-28 10:21:08', '<div class=\"gallery\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could take a picture using their webcam\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-338 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Webcam\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The site used NEC facial recognition software to scan the users facial features\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-339 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Image Processing\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"NEC\'s results were used to pair the user with a dog from the SPCA\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-340 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Results\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could share their results on Facebook\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"size-thumbnail wp-image-341 \" alt=\"Doggelganger Share \" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/doggelganger-screen4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a website which users could upload their photo to and get their face matched to a dog which is up for adoption at the SPCA. The premise being that owners often look like their pets.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the CMS and API built on the Zend Framework. It also implements the Facebook and NEC APIs.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nA lot of the heavy lifting was left up to NEC. Their security grade facial recognition software which was accessed via an API handled the facial scanning and matching functionality. The main challenges for us was to capture the images, save them to the database and provide a URL for each result that could be shared on facebook with all the relevant meta data. The real challenge however arose after the build finished. The project went viral and was receiving over 100,000 hits per day. Streamlining the server side code and using better data access techniques to stop the database crashing under such a heavy load was quite technical.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nImages were first captured by the flash and sent to the server as a base64 image string. The PHP then used the GD library to merge the users image, the dogs image and the doggelganger logo onto a yellow background and resize it to become the image which would be shared by Facebook. We would also resize and save the user and dog images individually along with the NEC match statistics to be displayed on the share page.\r\n\r\nWhen the project went viral we had to implement a number of things to stop the server from crashing. We moved the flash file itself to an Amazon cloud servers so our web server didn\'t have to send it out every time it was requested. We found that the main bottleneck was around reading and writing to the database so we tried to limit the number of database calls to a minimum. We kept as many recent records as we could in memcache so that when the user shared their match, it could hopefully just get pulled from memory instead of the database. The other thing we did was archive matches more than 5 days old so that when we were doing a database look up the table wasn\'t millions of rows long. All of these things combined with a queuing system allowed the server to tick over quite nicely despite the huge volume of traffic.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project was both simple and well executed. The core idea was great, it was easy to use, it was fun and the main goal of adopting dogs from the SPCA animal shelters exceeded expectation.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis site has won numerous awards including the Grand Axis, Gold Cannes, Spikes, Caples and many others. It was also featured on Campbell Live when it first launched.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a title=\"Doggelganger\" href=\"http://www.doggelganger.co.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.doggelganger.co.nz</a>', 'Doggelganger', 'Doggelganger used security grade facial recognition software to match your face with a dog who is up for adoption from the SPCA animal shelter. Its won a Gold at Cannes, the Grand Axis award and many more.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '372-revision-22', '', '', '2014-05-28 22:21:08', '2014-05-28 10:21:08', '', '372', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/372-revision-22/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('1024', '1', '2014-05-28 21:03:33', '2014-05-28 09:03:33', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 for prizes up for grabs it was important to stop any cheating.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nIll post the solutions to the security challenges once the campaign ends.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project is still running but is doing very well. The game is simple, challenging and addictive.\r\n<h3>Live site</h3>\r\n<a style=\"font-size: 13px;\" title=\"V Robbers\" href=\"http://www.v.co.nz/vrobbery\" target=\"_blank\">www.v.co.nz/vrobbery</a>', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-17', '', '', '2014-05-28 21:03:33', '2014-05-28 09:03:33', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-17/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1025', '1', '2014-05-29 09:30:52', '2014-05-28 21:30:52', '[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"987,986,985,984,983,982,981,980\"]\r\n\r\nTrial by timeline was a confronting piece of software. We got the user to login with facebook, we then looked at every data point we could. We searched posts, comments, photos, events, likes, relationship status anything we could get our hands on for any shred of information. There was a huge amount of manual data association done to give us the critera for what constitutes a crime. The users data was scanned all the way back to when they first signed up with facebook.\r\n\r\nThis provided some technical challenges in the form of needing to build a queueing system as the FQL queries would take a long time to execute. We also stored the data in memcache to improve load time rather than continually writing to the database.\r\n\r\nThis campaign was a huge success and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.\r\n\r\nFacebook Studio 2014: Blue award\r\n\r\nCannes 2013: Gold Lion, Bronze Lion\r\n\r\nD &amp; AD 2014: Yellow Pencil', 'Trial By Timeline', 'This campaign was a huge success and has picked up some high profile awards as well as being named the best Facebook app of 2014 as chosen by Facebook Studio.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '979-revision-6', '', '', '2014-05-29 09:30:52', '2014-05-28 21:30:52', '', '979', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/979-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1026', '1', '2014-05-29 21:42:57', '2014-05-29 09:42:57', 'Holiday replay enabled people to connect with Facebook and write a story about how they lost cash while on holiday. We would then take their story and match the words up with keywords in our database which were mapped to images and video content that would be compiled along with any facebook photos found of that holiday, into a video sequence with the music track they selected.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"915,922,921,920,919,918,917,916\"]\r\n\r\nThey were able to review the images pulled from facebook for their story and remove any unwanted ones. They could then upload new ones from their facebook gallery or directly from their computer before submitting it to our gallery.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"928,927,926,924\"]\r\n\r\nTheir submitted stories ended up in a searchable gallery where they could be voted on. They could be shared on Facebook and even played within the time line until facebook removed SWF support from timeline posts.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" columns=\"4\" ids=\"930,935,941,942\"]\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nHoliday replay was to be a mobile first web experience that brought an engaging rich media experience to tablet and mobile devices.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built using HTML5, SCSS, Javascript, JQuery and Canvas running on top of the Zend Framework. The API for the data service was built using the Zend Framework. It used the Javascript Facebook API and some quite complex FQL queries to get the right information about users. It used the Google Places Autocomplete field, Google Maps Geo-Coding service and the Google Maps Static Map service. It used HTML5 video and audio. It uploaded user content to the Rackspace Cloud via their API and this was later switched to upload to the Amazon Cloud for performance reasons. As you can see, there is a huge amount of technology combining into this one site and it all operated seamlessly together.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nHoliday Replay was a unique project with a lot of technical aspects to work through. I was the lead developer on this project, and as well as developing the API, my role included guiding the other two developers and ensuring their work pieced together into the final product. Getting all of these technologies to work together was a major challenge in it self. The major challenge for me was to figure out how to turn the users 50 word story into an actual sequence of images, videos, animations, custom fonts, graphics, colors and then serve it to the canvas in a meaningful way so that it could be used to control the animations the user sees to give them a unique experience.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWe had a huge amount of manually compiled stock imagery which was linked to locations and key words. For example if you used the word \"taxi\" and your story was geo tagged as in New York, the background image of that frame would be the iconic yellow taxi of New York. However if it were geo tagged as being in London, you would get an image of their also iconic black taxi cabs.\r\n\r\nIf we couldn\'t match the word, we\'d pull media that was related to the geo tagged location. If we\'d used all the default images for that location, we\'d fall back to a pool of generic imagery. This was my main solution, to have 5 or 6 levels of redundancy so that we were never left with the frame not having an asset to show.\r\n\r\nI would also look up the story location in your facebook albums and splice in some of your facebook images at appropriate intervals to make the experience that much more personal.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis campaign has had a good response and it has held together well over the 3 month course of the campaign. Thousands of people have submitted stories all across Australia. I will update with some more meaningful stats once the post campaign analysis has been done.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBehind the scenes, this job was huge. It involved a custom API, uploading users files to the cloud, facebook FQL queries, the Google Places API, Geo Coding, Canvas, HTML5, SCSS, jQuery &amp; Flash. The whole experience was mobile optimized to full functionality. You could submit, edit and watch the compiled video\'s all from your mobile phone or tablet.\r\n\r\nThe campaign performed well and has just come to a close. I\'ll update this post with some stats once they\'re available.', 'Holiday Replay', 'Holiday Replay was a unique project with a lot of technical aspects to work through. I was the lead developer on this project, I built the API behind it and guided the other two developers, ensuring their work pieced together into the final product.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '823-revision-40', '', '', '2014-05-29 21:42:57', '2014-05-29 09:42:57', '', '823', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/823-revision-40/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1027', '1', '2014-05-29 22:08:50', '2014-05-29 10:08:50', 'Holiday replay enabled people to connect with Facebook and write a story about how they lost cash while on holiday. We would then take their story and match the words up with keywords in our database which were mapped to images and video content that would be compiled along with any facebook photos found of that holiday, into a video sequence with the music track they selected.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"915,922,921,920,919,918,917,916\"]\r\n\r\nThey were able to review the images pulled from facebook for their story and remove any unwanted ones. They could then upload new ones from their facebook gallery or directly from their computer before submitting it to our gallery.\r\n\r\n[gallery columns=\"4\" link=\"file\" ids=\"928,927,926,924\"]\r\n\r\nTheir submitted stories ended up in a searchable gallery where they could be voted on. They could be shared on Facebook and even played within the time line until facebook removed SWF support from timeline posts.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" columns=\"4\" ids=\"930,935,941,942\"]\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nHoliday replay was to be a mobile first web experience that brought an engaging rich media experience to tablet and mobile devices.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built using HTML5, SCSS, Javascript, JQuery and Canvas running on top of the Zend Framework. The API for the data service was built using the Zend Framework. It used the Javascript Facebook API and some quite complex FQL queries to get the right information about users. It used the Google Places Autocomplete field, Google Maps Geo-Coding service and the Google Maps Static Map service. It used HTML5 video and audio. It uploaded user content to the Rackspace Cloud via their API and this was later switched to upload to the Amazon Cloud for performance reasons. As you can see, there is a huge amount of technology combining into this one site and it all operated seamlessly together.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nHoliday Replay was a unique project with a lot of technical aspects to work through. I was the lead developer on this project, and as well as developing the API, my role included guiding the other two developers and ensuring their work pieced together into the final product. Getting all of these technologies to work together was a major challenge in it self. The major challenge for me was to figure out how to turn the users 50 word story into an actual sequence of images, videos, animations, custom fonts, graphics, colors and then serve it to the canvas in a meaningful way so that it could be used to control the animations the user sees to give them a unique experience.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWe had a huge amount of manually compiled stock imagery which was linked to locations and key words. For example if you used the word \"taxi\" and your story was geo tagged as in New York, the background image of that frame would be the iconic yellow taxi of New York. However if it were geo tagged as being in London, you would get an image of their also iconic black taxi cabs.\r\n\r\nIf we couldn\'t match the word, we\'d pull media that was related to the geo tagged location. If we\'d used all the default images for that location, we\'d fall back to a pool of generic imagery. This was my main solution, to have 5 or 6 levels of redundancy so that we were never left with the frame not having an asset to show.\r\n\r\nI would also look up the story location in your facebook albums and splice in some of your facebook images at appropriate intervals to make the experience that much more personal.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis campaign has had a good response and it has held together well over the 3 month course of the campaign. Thousands of people have submitted stories all across Australia. I will update with some more meaningful stats once the post campaign analysis has been done.\r\n\r\nBehind the scenes, this job was huge. It involved a custom API, uploading users files to the cloud, facebook FQL queries, the Google Places API, Geo Coding, Canvas, HTML5, SCSS, jQuery &amp; Flash. The whole experience was mobile optimized to full functionality. You could submit, edit and watch the compiled video\'s all from your mobile phone or tablet.\r\n\r\nThe campaign performed well and has just come to a close. I\'ll update this post with some stats once they\'re available.', 'Holiday Replay', 'Holiday Replay was a unique project with a lot of technical aspects to work through. I was the lead developer on this project, I built the API behind it and guided the other two developers, ensuring their work pieced together into the final product.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '823-revision-41', '', '', '2014-05-29 22:08:50', '2014-05-29 10:08:50', '', '823', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/823-revision-41/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1028', '1', '2014-05-29 21:57:57', '2014-05-29 09:57:57', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in Flash with the API built on the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 for prizes up for grabs it was important to stop any cheating.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nIll post the solutions to the security challenges once the campaign ends.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nCannes 2013: Bronze Lion.\r\n\r\nAxis: 2014: Silver - Digital &amp; Interactive.', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-18', '', '', '2014-05-29 21:57:57', '2014-05-29 09:57:57', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-18/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1029', '1', '2014-05-29 22:26:48', '2014-05-29 10:26:48', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-537\" alt=\"vrobbers-1\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users would use their v.co.nz login to sign in through a CRM\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-538\" alt=\"vrobbers-2\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-2-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The user would make a profile picture and could enter can codes onto their account to get game Action Points\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-539\" alt=\"vrobbers-3\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-3-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The richest robbers are featured on the most wanted list\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-540\" alt=\"vrobbers-4\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-4-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Suburbs on the map would randomly open as the others became over 75% full\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-541\" alt=\"vrobbers-5\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-5-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Amongst the users we hid gang members with large amounts of money to be stolen from\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-542\" alt=\"vrobbers7\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers7-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"To steal money off other people the users had to win a mini game\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThe front end of this project was built in Flash on top of an API I wrote in the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 cash up for grabs through the game mechanic it was important to stop any cheating. Apart from that, the mechanic itself was quite sprawling with a lot of maps and suburbs to fill out. Spreading out the new users, dropping cash to the right secret locations and keeping the whole thing running while under heavy load was definitely difficult.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThere were a few main security issues which arose during this campaign. I put a lot of effort into the robbing mechanic being as bulletproof as possible. We had no problems at all in regards to people being able to steal cash off someone when they were\'nt supposed to.\r\n\r\nThe main issue we has was that someone performed a denial of service attack on our infrastructure at one point in the game. They were using our API to retrieve information about the different maps as if they were a user entering a new map and getting all the locations and dollar values. The information itself was benign, but they spammed these requests to the point of it choking the server. Presumably, they wanted to rob someone and didn\'t want anyone else attacking that user and hence missing their chance to rob them. So they DDOS attacked the server for a couple minutes around the time the user became vulnerable, stopped the attack, robbed the person and then resumed the attack until they were able to put them selves on protection so they couldn\'t get robbed. This is all conjecture, we could not track down the user who was performing the attack, it came from an IP address which was not associated with any of the players. We stopped this by banning the IP which was attacking us and also implemented in some rate limiting on the number of API requests that could be performed by a single IP address within a given time frame.\r\n\r\nThe only other notable things which happened was peoples ingenuity at exploiting the rules of the game which are not technically hacks. Some users reportedly set their mouse to only move on the X or Y axis, rather than in any direction on the X,Y plane. This enabled them to clip the wires faster as they had less chance of hitting the sides of the alarm and hence steal more money. The other thing was poeople would get their friend to setup an account with no money on it and when the main account was vulnerable to attack, they would attack the user but not attempt to steal any money. This would simply tie up the account with a current robbery and since a user could only be robbed by one person at a time, this chewed up their time until they could protect their stash again. Neither of these tactics were technically against the rules, and just showed peoples ingenuity.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nDespite everyone\'s attempts to get as much cash as they could, our game was designed to be hard to hold onto cash, so the money was spread out across a large number of users. I think the top prize claimed was about $2000 out of a possible $100,000 so it seems like our mechanic did what it was designed to do. And despite all the bumps along the way with people trying to exploit the game and attack our servers, the game held up well and was thoroughly enjoyed by V\'s  consumer base. The average time on site was something like 25minutes per visit, so it was super engaging and a great success for the brand.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nCannes 2013: Bronze Lion.\r\n\r\nAxis: 2014: Silver - Digital &amp; Interactive.', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-19', '', '', '2014-05-29 22:26:48', '2014-05-29 10:26:48', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-19/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1030', '1', '2014-05-29 22:27:26', '2014-05-29 10:27:26', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Users could look around the site and watch news clips without signing in\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-1.jpg\" rel=\"gal