l wp-image-543\" alt=\"vrobbers-6\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-6-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The mini game was disarming the alarm within a certain time period by clipping wires in the right order\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-544\" alt=\"vrobbers-8\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/vrobbers-8-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThe aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThe front end of this project was built in Flash on top of an API I wrote in the Zend Framework.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge around this project was security. Given the fact that there was $100,000 cash up for grabs through the game mechanic it was important to stop any cheating. Apart from that, the mechanic itself was quite sprawling with a lot of maps and suburbs to fill out. Spreading out the new users, dropping cash to the right secret locations and keeping the whole thing running while under heavy load was definitely difficult.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nThere were a few main security issues which arose during this campaign. I put a lot of effort into the robbing mechanic being as bulletproof as possible. We had no problems at all in regards to people being able to steal cash off someone when they were\'nt supposed to or defrauding the system for more money than they were supposed to get.\r\n\r\nThe main issue we has was that someone performed a denial of service attack on our infrastructure at one point in the game. They were using our API to retrieve information about the different maps as if they were a user entering a new map and getting all the locations and dollar values. The information itself was benign, but they spammed these requests to the point of it choking the server. Presumably, they wanted to rob someone and didn\'t want anyone else attacking that user and hence missing their chance to rob them. So they DDOS attacked the server for a couple minutes around the time the user became vulnerable, stopped the attack, robbed the person and then resumed the attack until they were able to put them selves on protection so they couldn\'t get robbed. This is all conjecture, we could not track down the user who was performing the attack, it came from an IP address which was not associated with any of the players. We stopped this by banning the IP which was attacking us and also implemented in some rate limiting on the number of API requests that could be performed by a single IP address within a given time frame.\r\n\r\nThe only other notable things which happened was peoples ingenuity at exploiting the rules of the game which are not technically hacks. Some users reportedly set their mouse to only move on the X or Y axis, rather than in any direction on the X,Y plane. This enabled them to clip the wires faster as they had less chance of hitting the sides of the alarm and hence steal more money. The other thing was poeople would get their friend to setup an account with no money on it and when the main account was vulnerable to attack, they would attack the user but not attempt to steal any money. This would simply tie up the account with a current robbery and since a user could only be robbed by one person at a time, this chewed up their time until they could protect their stash again. Neither of these tactics were technically against the rules, and really showed the engagement level we had achieved in the user base.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nDespite everyone\'s attempts to get as much cash as they could, our game was designed to be hard to hold onto cash, so the money was spread out across a large number of users. I think the top prize claimed was about $2000 out of a possible $100,000 so it seems like our mechanic did what it was designed to do. And despite all the bumps along the way with people trying to exploit the game and attack our servers, the game held up well and was thoroughly enjoyed by V\'s  consumer base. The average time on site was something like 25minutes per visit, so it was super engaging and a great success for the brand.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nCannes 2013: Bronze Lion.\r\n\r\nAxis: 2014: Silver - Digital &amp; Interactive.', 'V Robbers', 'The aim of this project was to increase sales by creating a fun game to drive prize giveaways rather than a simple entry mechanic. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '533-revision-21', '', '', '2014-05-29 22:29:20', '2014-05-29 10:29:20', '', '533', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/533-revision-21/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1039', '1', '2014-06-07 16:49:12', '2014-06-07 04:49:12', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">quick start guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to prattle on about how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'re up and running, there\'s a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. You\'ll want to update the OS and install the updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update, some of the modules were failing to install, i kept getting the error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n\r\n[/code]', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-6', '', '', '2014-06-07 16:49:12', '2014-06-07 04:49:12', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1040', '1', '2014-06-07 16:55:47', '2014-06-07 04:55:47', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">quick start guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to prattle on about how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'re up and running, there\'s a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. You\'ll want to update the OS and install the updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update, some of the modules were failing to install, i kept getting the error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Just open the file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line looks like this\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-7', '', '', '2014-06-07 16:55:47', '2014-06-07 04:55:47', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1041', '1', '2014-06-07 17:10:19', '2014-06-07 05:10:19', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">quick start guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to prattle on about how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'re up and running, there\'s a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. You\'ll want to update the OS and install the updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update, some of the modules were failing to install, i kept getting the error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Just open the file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we were getting and we can now update the system:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still ran into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nOnce this is complete, you now have a fully updated Raspberry Pi that is throwing no errors which you can put to work.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a  gridseed miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover everything you need to get your Raspberry Pi running autonomously.\r\n\r\nWe will look at how to:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-8', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:10:19', '2014-06-07 05:10:19', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1042', '1', '2014-06-07 17:12:07', '2014-06-07 05:12:07', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">quick start guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to prattle on about how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'re up and running, there\'s a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. You\'ll want to update the OS and install the updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update, some of the modules were failing to install, i kept getting the error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Just open the file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we were getting and we can now update the system:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still ran into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nOnce this is complete, you now have a fully updated Raspberry Pi that is throwing no errors which you can put to work.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, this is a work in progress, so sometimes they do run into issues and need rebooting.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover everything you need to get your Raspberry Pi running the programs you want autonomously and with minimal down time.\r\n\r\nWe will look at how to:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-9', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:12:07', '2014-06-07 05:12:07', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1043', '1', '2014-06-07 17:20:16', '2014-06-07 05:20:16', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out. If you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\n\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>. I installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\n\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\n\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\n\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\n\n[code]\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\n[/code]\n\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\n\n[code]\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\n[/code]\n\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\n\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\n\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\n\n[code]\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\n# Provides:          mathkernel\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\n### END INIT INFO\n[/code]\n\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we were getting and we can now update the system:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\n\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\n\nIf you still ran into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again:\n\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\n\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\n\nOnce this is complete, you now have a fully updated Raspberry Pi that is throwing no errors which you can now put to work.\n\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, this is a work in progress, so sometimes they do run into issues and need rebooting. For the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there which you can look up.\n\nTo check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\n\nI just have mine setup to use DHCP like this:\n\n[code]\n\n&amp;nbsp;\n\n[/code]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMy next articles will cover everything you need to get your Raspberry Pi running the programs you want autonomously and with minimal down time.\n\nWe will look at how to:\n<ul>\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\n</ul>', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-10', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:20:16', '2014-06-07 05:20:16', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1044', '1', '2014-06-07 17:21:17', '2014-06-07 05:21:17', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out. If you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\n\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>. I installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\n\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\n\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\n\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\n\n[code]\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\n[/code]\n\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\n\n[code]\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\n[/code]\n\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\n\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\n\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\n\n[code]\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\n# Provides:          mathkernel\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\n### END INIT INFO\n[/code]\n\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we were getting and we can now update the system:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\n\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\n\nIf you still ran into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again:\n\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\n\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\n\nOnce this is complete, you now have a fully updated Raspberry Pi that is throwing no errors which you can now put to work.\n\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, this is a work in progress, so sometimes they do run into issues and need rebooting. For the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there which you can look up.\n\nTo check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\n\nI just have mine setup to use DHCP like this:\n\n[code]\n\nauto lo\n\niface lo inet loopback\n\n&amp;nbsp;\n\nauto etho0\n\niface eth0 inet dhcp\n\n[/code]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMy next articles will cover everything you need to get your Raspberry Pi running the programs you want autonomously and with minimal down time.\n\nWe will look at how to:\n<ul>\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\n</ul>', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-11', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:21:17', '2014-06-07 05:21:17', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-11/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('1045', '1', '2014-06-07 17:21:27', '2014-06-07 05:21:27', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out. If you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>. I installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we were getting and we can now update the system:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still ran into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nOnce this is complete, you now have a fully updated Raspberry Pi that is throwing no errors which you can now put to work.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, this is a work in progress, so sometimes they do run into issues and need rebooting. For the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there which you can look up.\r\n\r\nTo check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nI just have mine setup to use DHCP like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover everything you need to get your Raspberry Pi running the programs you want autonomously and with minimal down time.\r\n\r\nWe will look at how to:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-12', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:21:27', '2014-06-07 05:21:27', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1046', '1', '2014-06-07 17:37:24', '2014-06-07 05:37:24', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out. If you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>. I installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections\r\n\r\nTo check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully, try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still ran into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully updated Raspberry Pi that is throwing no errors which you can now put to work.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, this is a work in progress, so sometimes they do run into issues and need rebooting.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover everything you need to get your Raspberry Pi running the programs you want autonomously and with minimal down time.\r\n\r\nWe will look at how to:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-13', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:37:24', '2014-06-07 05:37:24', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-13/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1047', '1', '2014-06-07 17:50:15', '2014-06-07 05:50:15', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out. If you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>. I installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or static means, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the command, pressing ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still ran into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully updated Raspberry Pi that is throwing no errors which you can now put to work.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, this is a work in progress, so sometimes they do run into issues and need rebooting.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover everything you need to get your Raspberry Pi running the programs you want autonomously and with minimal down time.\r\n\r\nWe will look at how to:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-14', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:50:15', '2014-06-07 05:50:15', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-14/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1053', '1', '2014-06-07 18:02:52', '2014-06-07 06:02:52', '', '1095310_62999162', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1095310_62999162', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:02:52', '2014-06-07 06:02:52', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/1095310_62999162.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1050', '1', '2014-06-07 17:59:12', '2014-06-07 05:59:12', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi? They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out. If you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>. I installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-17', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:59:12', '2014-06-07 05:59:12', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-17/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1048', '1', '2014-06-07 17:58:01', '2014-06-07 05:58:01', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out. If you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>. I installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-15', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:58:01', '2014-06-07 05:58:01', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-15/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1049', '1', '2014-06-07 17:58:05', '2014-06-07 05:58:05', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi. They\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out. If you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get stuck with the same problems which took me over a week and 3 image wipes to finally get to where I wanted to be.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>. I installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-16', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:58:05', '2014-06-07 05:58:05', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-16/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1051', '1', '2014-06-07 17:59:57', '2014-06-07 05:59:57', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nObviously the first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>. I installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-18', '', '', '2014-06-07 17:59:57', '2014-06-07 05:59:57', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-18/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1052', '1', '2014-06-07 18:00:29', '2014-06-07 06:00:29', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nBasically, all that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. This is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-19', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:00:29', '2014-06-07 06:00:29', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-19/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1054', '1', '2014-06-07 18:02:26', '2014-06-07 06:02:26', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\n\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\n\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\n\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\n\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\n\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\n\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\n\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\n\n[code]\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\n[/code]\n\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\n\n[code]\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\n[/code]\n\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\n\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\n\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\n\n[code]\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\n# Provides:          mathkernel\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\n### END INIT INFO\n[/code]\n\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\n\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\n\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\n\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\n\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\n\nIt should look like this:\n\n[code]\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\nauto etho0\niface eth0 inet dhcp\n[/code]\n\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\n\n[code]\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\nauto etho0\niface eth0 inet static\naddress 192.168.1.100\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\ngateway 192.168.1.1\n[/code]\n\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\n\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\n\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\n\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\n\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\n\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\n\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\n\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\n\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\n\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\n\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nIf you see responses like theses:\n\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\n\nIf you however see something more like this:\n\n[code]\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\n[/code]\n\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\n\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\n\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\n\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\n\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\n\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\n\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\n\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\n\nMy next articles will cover:\n<ul>\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\n</ul>\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-20', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:02:26', '2014-06-07 06:02:26', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-20/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('1056', '1', '2014-06-07 18:04:51', '2014-06-07 06:04:51', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\n\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\n\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\n\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\n\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\n\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\n\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\n\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\n\n[code]\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\n[/code]\n\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\n\n[code]\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\n[/code]\n\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\n\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\n\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\n\n[code]\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\n# Provides:          mathkernel\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\n### END INIT INFO\n[/code]\n\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\n\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\n\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\n\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\n\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\n\nIt should look like this:\n\n[code]\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\nauto etho0\niface eth0 inet dhcp\n[/code]\n\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\n\n[code]\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\nauto etho0\niface eth0 inet static\naddress 192.168.1.100\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\ngateway 192.168.1.1\n[/code]\n\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\n\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\n\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\n\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\n\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\n\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\n\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\n\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\n\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\n\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\n\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nIf you see responses like theses:\n\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\n\nIf you however see something more like this:\n\n[code]\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\n[/code]\n\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\n\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\n\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\n\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\n\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\n\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\n\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\n\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\n\nMy next articles will cover:\n<ul>\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\n</ul>\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-22', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:04:51', '2014-06-07 06:04:51', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-22/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1055', '1', '2014-06-07 18:03:10', '2014-06-07 06:03:10', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out.  The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install, I kept getting this error thrown:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-21', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:03:10', '2014-06-07 06:03:10', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-21/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1058', '1', '2014-06-07 18:17:09', '2014-06-07 06:17:09', '', 'raspberry-pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'raspberry-pi', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:17:09', '2014-06-07 06:17:09', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/raspberry-pi.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1057', '1', '2014-06-07 18:06:07', '2014-06-07 06:06:07', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-23', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:06:07', '2014-06-07 06:06:07', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-23/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1059', '1', '2014-06-07 18:07:35', '2014-06-07 06:07:35', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\n\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\n\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\n\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\n\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\n\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\n\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\n\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\n\n[code]\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\n[/code]\n\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\n\n[code]\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\n[/code]\n\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\n\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\n\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\n\n[code]\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\n# Provides:          mathkernel\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\n### END INIT INFO\n[/code]\n\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\n\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\n\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\n\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\n\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\n\nIt should look like this:\n\n[code]\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\nauto etho0\niface eth0 inet dhcp\n[/code]\n\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\n\n[code]\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\nauto etho0\niface eth0 inet static\naddress 192.168.1.100\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\ngateway 192.168.1.1\n[/code]\n\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\n\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\n\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\n\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\n\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\n\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\n\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\n\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\n\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\n\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\n\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nIf you see responses like theses:\n\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\n\nIf you however see something more like this:\n\n[code]\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\n[/code]\n\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\n\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\n\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\n\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\n\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\n\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\n\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\n\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\n\nMy next articles will cover:\n<ul>\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\n</ul>\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-24', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:07:35', '2014-06-07 06:07:35', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-24/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1068', '1', '2014-06-07 18:46:09', '2014-06-07 06:46:09', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\n\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\n\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\n\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\n\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\n\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\n\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\n\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\n\n[code]\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\n[/code]\n\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\n\n[code]\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\n[/code]\n\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\n\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\n\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\n\n[code]\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\n# Provides:          mathkernel\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\n### END INIT INFO\n[/code]\n\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\n\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\n\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\n\nFor the 