, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\n\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nIf you see responses like theses:\n\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\n\nIf you however see something more like this:\n\n[code]\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\n[/code]\n\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\n\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\n\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\n\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\n\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\n\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\n\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\n\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\n\nMy next articles will cover:\n<ul>\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\n</ul>\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-31', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:46:09', '2014-06-07 06:46:09', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-31/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1060', '1', '2014-06-08 09:44:01', '2014-06-07 21:44:01', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\n\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\n\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\n\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\n\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\n\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\n\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\n\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\n\n[code]\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\n[/code]\n\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\n\n[code]\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\n[/code]\n\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\n\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\n\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\n\n[code]\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\n# Provides:          mathkernel\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\n### END INIT INFO\n[/code]\n\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\n\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\n\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\n\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\n\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\n\nIt should look like this:\n\n[code]\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\nauto etho0\niface eth0 inet dhcp\n[/code]\n\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\n\n[code]\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\nauto etho0\niface eth0 inet static\naddress 192.168.1.100\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\ngateway 192.168.1.1\n[/code]\n\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\n\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\n\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\n\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\n\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\n\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\n\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\n\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\n\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\n\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\n\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nIf you see responses like theses:\n\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\n\nIf you however see something more like this:\n\n[code]\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\n[/code]\n\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\n\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\n\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\n\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\n\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\n\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\n\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\n\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\n\nMy next articles will cover:\n<ul>\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\n</ul>\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-autosave', '', '', '2014-06-08 09:44:01', '2014-06-07 21:44:01', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1061', '1', '2014-06-07 18:24:45', '2014-06-07 06:24:45', '', 'raspberry-pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'raspberry-pi-2', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:24:45', '2014-06-07 06:24:45', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/raspberry-pi1.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1062', '1', '2014-06-07 18:18:17', '2014-06-07 06:18:17', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-25', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:18:17', '2014-06-07 06:18:17', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-25/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), (