r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Getting Started with Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-26', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:24:52', '2014-06-07 06:24:52', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-26/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('1064', '1', '2014-06-07 18:27:30', '2014-06-07 06:27:30', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'Introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-27', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:27:30', '2014-06-07 06:27:30', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-27/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1065', '1', '2014-06-07 18:27:45', '2014-06-07 06:27:45', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-28', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:27:45', '2014-06-07 06:27:45', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-28/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1066', '1', '2014-06-07 18:44:36', '2014-06-07 06:44:36', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-29', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:44:36', '2014-06-07 06:44:36', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-29/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1067', '1', '2014-06-07 18:44:59', '2014-06-07 06:44:59', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-30', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:44:59', '2014-06-07 06:44:59', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-30/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1069', '1', '2014-06-07 18:49:54', '2014-06-07 06:49:54', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\n\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\n\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\n\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\n\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\n\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\n\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\n\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\n\n[code]\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\n[/code]\n\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\n\n[code]\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\n[/code]\n\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\n\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\n\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\n\n[code]\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\n# Provides:          mathkernel\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\n### END INIT INFO\n[/code]\n\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\n\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\n\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\n\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\n\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\n\nIt should look like this:\n\n[code]\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\nauto etho0\niface eth0 inet dhcp\n[/code]\n\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\n\n[code]\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\nauto etho0\niface eth0 inet static\naddress 192.168.1.100\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\ngateway 192.168.1.1\n[/code]\n\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\n\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\n\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\n\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\n\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\n\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\n\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\n\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\n\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\n\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\n\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nIf you see responses like theses:\n\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\n\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\n\nIf you however see something more like this:\n\n[code]\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\n[/code]\n\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\n\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\n\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\n\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\n\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\n\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\n\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\n\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\n\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\n\nMy next articles will cover:\n<ul>\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\n</ul>\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-32', '', '', '2014-06-07 18:49:54', '2014-06-07 06:49:54', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-32/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1070', '1', '2014-06-07 19:12:54', '2014-06-07 07:12:54', '', 'raspberry-pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'raspberry-pi-3', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:12:54', '2014-06-07 07:12:54', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/raspberry-pi2.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1071', '1', '2014-06-07 19:12:21', '2014-06-07 07:12:21', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-33', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:12:21', '2014-06-07 07:12:21', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-33/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1072', '1', '2014-06-07 19:13:24', '2014-06-07 07:13:24', '', 'kinetic-js', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'kinetic-js', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:13:24', '2014-06-07 07:13:24', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/kinetic-js.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1073', '1', '2014-04-17 10:03:00', '2014-04-16 22:03:00', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\r\n\r\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to implement a state change on the element requires the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework.\r\n\r\nKinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could fit my needs. However, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which weren\'t so obvious to me when I started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. If you follow the <a title=\"Image Object example\" href=\"http://www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-kineticjs-image-tutorial/\" target=\"_blank\">Kinetic JS Image object example</a>, the image gets added to the stage on the callback of its load function. This is fine if you\'re only loading one image, but if you want to draw a shape after the image which overlays the image, you\'ll have a problem.\r\n\r\nThe image will always sit on top of the shape because it will always take longer for the image to load than the shape drawing code takes to execute. Unless you pre-load your images, they will always end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in your script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that got me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-49', '', '', '2014-04-17 10:03:00', '2014-04-16 22:03:00', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-49/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1074', '1', '2014-06-07 19:13:57', '2014-06-07 07:13:57', '', 'facebook-login1', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'facebook-login1', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:13:57', '2014-06-07 07:13:57', '', '759', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/facebook-login1.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1075', '1', '2013-07-03 12:10:16', '2013-07-03 00:10:16', 'The first step is to initialize the SDK. The best way to do this is to follow the instructions in the official <a title=\"Getting Started with the Facebook JavaScript SDK\" href=\"https://developers.facebook.com/docs/javascript/gettingstarted/\" target=\"_blank\">documentation</a> since it changes fairly often.\r\n\r\nThen you need to run check if the user is logged in using FB.getLoginStatus\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nFB.getLoginStatus(function(response) {\r\n\r\n     if (response.status === \'connected\') {\r\n           // connected\r\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED\');\r\n      } else if (response.status === \'not_authorized\') {\r\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED, NOT AUTORIZED\');\r\n           login();\r\n      } else {\r\n           console.log(\'NOT CONNECTED\');\r\n           login();\r\n      }\r\n\r\n});\r\n\r\nfunction login(){\r\n\r\n      FB.login(function(response) {\r\n           if (response.authResponse) {\r\n                     console.log(\'LOGGED IN\');\r\n                } else {\r\n                     console.log(\'CANCELLED\');\r\n                }\r\n            },\r\n      {scope: \'publish_actions\'});\r\n\r\n}//login\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIf they\'re not logged in, ask them to login by using FB.login. I\'ve made FB.login contained in its own function to stop code repetition since its called in two situations.\r\n\r\nThe login call is where we ask for permissions, so it will get called when the user is logged in but has not given permissions as well as when the user is not logged in.\r\n\r\nThe second variable parsed to FB.login is the scope of the app. The scope defines the required permissions of the app. The scope documentation can be found <a title=\"Facebook Scope Documentation\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/docs/reference/login/#permissions\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. Multiple scope parameters can be simply a comma separated list.\r\n\r\nWe get two responses from the login function, this is so we can differentiate between the user cancelling out of the login process and actually logging in.\r\n\r\nI\'ve just put console logs through the code to show what happens when, its up to you and the needs of your app to define what you need to do when each of these circumstances occur.', 'Login with the Facebook JavaScript SDK', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '759-revision-7', '', '', '2013-07-03 12:10:16', '2013-07-03 00:10:16', '', '759', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/759-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1076', '1', '2014-06-07 19:15:03', '2014-06-07 07:15:03', '', 'facebook-login2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'facebook-login2', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:15:03', '2014-06-07 07:15:03', '', '798', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/facebook-login2.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1077', '1', '2013-08-12 19:50:25', '2013-08-12 07:50:25', 'The JS SDK for facebook launches the login screen as a popup window and not a modal frame. This means that in some browsers if the user has popups blocked, the window will never show. Safari for example doesn\'t even display a message to say it blocked a popup if you have the blocker turned on. This is a major problem, especially for mobile users whom it seems to haphazardly effect on various browsers, no matter what their popup blocker settings are.\r\n\r\nThe best way around this is to detect if the user is on moblie and use the PHP SDK for login if they are. It gives the same user journey as the popup on mobile since the browser tabs are always full screen but since its redirecting within the same window, it doesnt trigger the popup blocker.\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n require_once(\'facebook.php\');\r\n\r\n  $config = array();\r\n  $config[\'appId\'] = \'YOUR_APP_ID\';\r\n  $config[\'secret\'] = \'YOUR_APP_SECRET\';\r\n  $config[\'cookie\'] = true;\r\n\r\n  $facebook = new Facebook($config);\r\n\r\n  $me = null;\r\n\r\n  try {\r\n    $me = $facebook-&gt;api(\'/me\');\r\n  } catch (FacebookApiException $e) {\r\n    error_log($e);\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  if($me){\r\n    //do whatever you need to do with the PHP SDK\r\n  }else{\r\n    $params = array(\r\n      \'scope\' =&gt; \'read_stream, friends_likes\',\r\n      \'redirect_uri\' =&gt; \'https://www.myapp.com/post_login_page\'\r\n    );\r\n    $loginURL = $facebook-&gt;getLoginUrl($params);\r\n    //redirect them to the above login URL or make it the href on an a tag.\r\n  }\r\n\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\nLogging in with the PHP SDK and then trying to interact with the JS SDKs FB.ui features used to be a real nightmare. Even when you had cookies enabled, the session never really seemed to share properly and I\'d always have to write custom scripts to read and write the token to the cookie manually. If you\'re having this problem, try upgrading your PHP SDK to version 3. All the bugs to do with sharing the logged in session between the client and the server seem to be resolved in this version.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re worried about it happening on desktop as well, you could implement a javascript timer which will instruct the user to turn off their popup blocker if you didn\'t get the callback from the login window within a certain time frame. Or you could present a custom popup which has a link that would log them in with the PHP SDK if you dont want the user to have to tinker with their browser settings.', 'Facebook login popup never appearing', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '798-revision-5', '', '', '2013-08-12 19:50:25', '2013-08-12 07:50:25', '', '798', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/798-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1078', '1', '2014-06-07 19:13:02', '2014-06-07 07:13:02', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-34', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:13:02', '2014-06-07 07:13:02', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-34/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('1079', '1', '2014-06-07 19:13:31', '2014-06-07 07:13:31', 'Anyone working with canvas will know how arduous it is to get running without using a framework. Mouse events can\'t be bound natively to drawn objects meaning you have to invoke a lot of math to determine if the cursor is hovering over a shape. The math becomes increasingly difficult working with complex shapes like wedges and would be mind numbingly hard on an irregular shape.\r\n\r\nThen once you\'ve finally figured which shape your cursor is over, to implement a state change on the element requires the entire canvas to be manually redrawn. This high level of complexity to implement a simple hover state stopped me in my tracks and I quickly moved from trying to natively code in Canvas to using a framework.\r\n\r\nKinetic JS is the first one I came across that looked like it could fit my needs. However, even when using a decent framework, there\'s a few things which weren\'t so obvious to me when I started out.\r\n\r\nFirstly, you\'ll want to code your canvas to redraw on page resize rather than just on page load which can be achieved with the following code snippet:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n//event handler for window resize\r\nwindow.addEventListener(\'resize\', resizeCanvas, false);\r\n\r\n//resize calculates dimensions then calls draw canvas\r\nfunction resizeCanvas() {\r\n\r\n    var canvasWidth = window.innerWidth;\r\n    var canvasHeight = window.innerHeight;\r\n    drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight);\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n//this initializes the canvas for the first time\r\nresizeCanvas();\r\n\r\nfunction drawCanvas(canvasWidth,canvasHeight) {\r\n\r\n//draw your canvas elements here\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe next thing to note is that images are added to the canvas asynchronously. If you follow the <a title=\"Image Object example\" href=\"http://www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-kineticjs-image-tutorial/\" target=\"_blank\">Kinetic JS Image object example</a>, the image gets added to the stage on the callback of its load function. This is fine if you\'re only loading one image, but if you want to draw a shape after the image which overlays the image, you\'ll have a problem.\r\n\r\nThe image will always sit on top of the shape because it will always take longer for the image to load than the shape drawing code takes to execute. Unless you pre-load your images, they will always end up being on top of any other elements you draw or write on the canvas no matter what z-index you give them or where in your script they are.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll want to use an image preloading function and run it before your canvas draws for the first time.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\n\r\n//make an object containing the image sources you want to preload\r\n var imageSources = {\r\n    image1: \'/images/image1.svg\',\r\n    image2: \'/images/image2.svg\'\r\n }\r\n\r\n//function to preload the images into the canvas\r\nfunction loadImages(sources, callback) {\r\n    var images = {};\r\n    var loadedImages = 0;\r\n    var numImages = 0;\r\n    // get num of sources\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        numImages++;\r\n    }\r\n    for(var src in sources) {\r\n        images[src] = new Image();\r\n        images[src].onload = function() {\r\n            if(++loadedImages &gt;= numImages) {\r\n                callback(images);\r\n            }\r\n        };\r\n        images[src].src = sources[src];\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n//call the preloader function and on callback, init your canvas for the first time\r\nloadImages(imageSources, function(){\r\n    resizeCanvas();\r\n});\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nSo this code would be combined with the other snippet above to give you a page which resizes dynamically to the page and also preloads the images so they\'re drawn to the correct layers in the canvas.\r\n\r\nThe last thing that got me was adding items to the stage within a loop. If you don\'t wrap some of the object types in an anonymous function to restrict variable scope you\'ll find that only the last one in the loop will actually draw to the stage as the variables keep getting overwritten each time through the loop.\r\n\r\nI was primarily having this issue with the Image and Kinetic.Shape objects. Higher level shape objects like Circles or Wedges which extend the Kinetic.Shape object seemed to work fine when not wrapped in an anonymous function, but the lower level Shape object needed this scope restriction added.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nfor(var i; i&lt;2; i++){ (\r\n    function(){\r\n        var tempImage = new Image();\r\n        tempImage.src = imageSources[\'image\'+i];\r\n        var kineticImage = new Kinetic.Image({\r\n            x: 100,\r\n            y: 100,\r\n            image: tempImage,\r\n            width: 100,\r\n            height: 100,\r\n            id: \'image\'+i\r\n        });\r\n        layer.add(kineticImage);\r\n        stage.add(layer);\r\n    })();\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could break this out into a named function outside the loop or have the anonymous function return to a variable inside the loop if you need to further manipulate it.\r\n\r\nThese were the major things which took me a while to figure out the answers for, so hopefully these tips save someone out there a bit of head scratching.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re interested in checking out Kinetic JS, you can visit their <a title=\"website\" href=\"http://kineticjs.com/\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>. They have a heap of <a title=\"tutorials\" href=\"www.html5canvastutorials.com/kineticjs/html5-canvas-events-tutorials-introduction-with-kineticjs/\" target=\"_blank\">tutorials</a> and you can even fork the project on <a title=\"Github\" href=\"https://github.com/ericdrowell/KineticJS/\" target=\"_blank\">Github</a>.', 'Getting started with Kinetic JS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '842-revision-50', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:13:31', '2014-06-07 07:13:31', '', '842', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/842-revision-50/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1080', '1', '2014-06-07 19:14:41', '2014-06-07 07:14:41', 'The first step is to initialize the SDK. The best way to do this is to follow the instructions in the official <a title=\"Getting Started with the Facebook JavaScript SDK\" href=\"https://developers.facebook.com/docs/javascript/gettingstarted/\" target=\"_blank\">documentation</a> since it changes fairly often.\r\n\r\nThen you need to run check if the user is logged in using FB.getLoginStatus\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nFB.getLoginStatus(function(response) {\r\n\r\n     if (response.status === \'connected\') {\r\n           // connected\r\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED\');\r\n      } else if (response.status === \'not_authorized\') {\r\n           console.log(\'CONNECTED, NOT AUTORIZED\');\r\n           login();\r\n      } else {\r\n           console.log(\'NOT CONNECTED\');\r\n           login();\r\n      }\r\n\r\n});\r\n\r\nfunction login(){\r\n\r\n      FB.login(function(response) {\r\n           if (response.authResponse) {\r\n                     console.log(\'LOGGED IN\');\r\n                } else {\r\n                     console.log(\'CANCELLED\');\r\n                }\r\n            },\r\n      {scope: \'publish_actions\'});\r\n\r\n}//login\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIf they\'re not logged in, ask them to login by using FB.login. I\'ve made FB.login contained in its own function to stop code repetition since its called in two situations.\r\n\r\nThe login call is where we ask for permissions, so it will get called when the user is logged in but has not given permissions as well as when the user is not logged in.\r\n\r\nThe second variable parsed to FB.login is the scope of the app. The scope defines the required permissions of the app. The scope documentation can be found <a title=\"Facebook Scope Documentation\" href=\"http://developers.facebook.com/docs/reference/login/#permissions\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>. Multiple scope parameters can be simply a comma separated list.\r\n\r\nWe get two responses from the login function, this is so we can differentiate between the user cancelling out of the login process and actually logging in.\r\n\r\nI\'ve just put console logs through the code to show what happens when, its up to you and the needs of your app to define what you need to do when each of these circumstances occur.', 'Login with the Facebook JavaScript SDK', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '759-revision-8', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:14:41', '2014-06-07 07:14:41', '', '759', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/759-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1081', '1', '2014-06-07 19:15:14', '2014-06-07 07:15:14', 'The JS SDK for facebook launches the login screen as a popup window and not a modal frame. This means that in some browsers if the user has popups blocked, the window will never show. Safari for example doesn\'t even display a message to say it blocked a popup if you have the blocker turned on. This is a major problem, especially for mobile users whom it seems to haphazardly effect on various browsers, no matter what their popup blocker settings are.\r\n\r\nThe best way around this is to detect if the user is on moblie and use the PHP SDK for login if they are. It gives the same user journey as the popup on mobile since the browser tabs are always full screen but since its redirecting within the same window, it doesnt trigger the popup blocker.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"php\"]\r\n require_once(\'facebook.php\');\r\n\r\n  $config = array();\r\n  $config[\'appId\'] = \'YOUR_APP_ID\';\r\n  $config[\'secret\'] = \'YOUR_APP_SECRET\';\r\n  $config[\'cookie\'] = true;\r\n\r\n  $facebook = new Facebook($config);\r\n\r\n  $me = null;\r\n\r\n  try {\r\n    $me = $facebook-&gt;api(\'/me\');\r\n  } catch (FacebookApiException $e) {\r\n    error_log($e);\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  if($me){\r\n    //do whatever you need to do with the PHP SDK\r\n  }else{\r\n    $params = array(\r\n      \'scope\' =&gt; \'read_stream, friends_likes\',\r\n      \'redirect_uri\' =&gt; \'https://www.myapp.com/post_login_page\'\r\n    );\r\n    $loginURL = $facebook-&gt;getLoginUrl($params);\r\n    //redirect them to the above login URL or make it the href on an a tag.\r\n  }\r\n\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n\r\nLogging in with the PHP SDK and then trying to interact with the JS SDKs FB.ui features used to be a real nightmare. Even when you had cookies enabled, the session never really seemed to share properly and I\'d always have to write custom scripts to read and write the token to the cookie manually. If you\'re having this problem, try upgrading your PHP SDK to version 3. All the bugs to do with sharing the logged in session between the client and the server seem to be resolved in this version.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re worried about it happening on desktop as well, you could implement a javascript timer which will instruct the user to turn off their popup blocker if you didn\'t get the callback from the login window within a certain time frame. Or you could present a custom popup which has a link that would log them in with the PHP SDK if you dont want the user to have to tinker with their browser settings.', 'Facebook login popup never appearing', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '798-revision-6', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:15:14', '2014-06-07 07:15:14', '', '798', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/798-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1082', '1', '2014-06-07 19:30:30', '2014-06-07 07:30:30', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-35', '', '', '2014-06-07 19:30:30', '2014-06-07 07:30:30', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-35/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1083', '1', '2014-06-08 09:44:07', '2014-06-07 21:44:07', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-36', '', '', '2014-06-08 09:44:07', '2014-06-07 21:44:07', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-36/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1085', '1', '2013-07-05 16:06:28', '2013-07-05 04:06:28', 'Javascript timers are pretty useful for any web app which requires the client machine to poll the server for updates.\r\n\r\nInitializing a javascript timer is pretty straight forward.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nsetInterval(function(){console.log(&quot;Hello World&quot;)},1000);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThe first argument is the function to run when the timer triggers and the second is the timer interval in milliseconds.\r\n\r\nThis will set the timer running but with this method you have no way to stop the timer. Its best practice to bind the timer to a variable so you can stop it if you want to and also to separate the function from the initilaization.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nvar counter = 1;\r\nvar myTimer = setInterval(timerFunction,1000);\r\n\r\nfunction timerFunction(){\r\n     if(counter &gt; 5){\r\n          clearInterval(myTimer);\r\n          console.log(\'timer stopped\');\r\n     }else{\r\n          console.log(\'timer triggered \'+counter+\' times\');\r\n          counter++;\r\n     }\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis example starts the timer and loops through 5 times logging to the console each time with the number of times it has looped, then stops the timer after its logged to the console 5 times.\r\n\r\nThe timer is stopped with the clearInterval command, passing in the timer object as a variable in its first argument\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"javascript\"]\r\nclearInterval(myTimer);\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nIts important to remember that in situations when you\'re polling the server for content updates not to run these too often if your server is expected to be busy or you will overload your server.', 'Javascript timers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '603-revision-12', '', '', '2013-07-05 16:06:28', '2013-07-05 04:06:28', '', '603', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/603-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1086', '1', '2014-05-29 21:57:24', '2014-05-29 09:57:24', '<div class=\"gallery\">\r\n<div class=\"topRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your position in the queue determined the prize you won\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-773\" alt=\"gs4_0000\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0000-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"You could choose your avatar for the queue and it would put your facebook profile picture on as the head.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-774\" alt=\"gs4_0001\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0001-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Your queue position was determined by your social influence i.e. shares, likes, comments, re-tweets etc.\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-775\" alt=\"gs4_0002\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0002-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Each day new content was revealed to share on facebook and twitter\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-776\" alt=\"gs4_0003\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0003-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n<div class=\"bottomRow\"><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"The content consisted of different types of media\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-777\" alt=\"gs4_0004\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0004-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There were even quizzes\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-778\" alt=\"gs4_005\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_005-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"There was usually 3 pieces of content per day\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-779\" alt=\"gs4_0006\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0006-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a><a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Peoples comments would be pulled through to their avatar in the queue\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007.jpg\" rel=\"gallery1\"><img class=\"alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-780\" alt=\"gs4_0007\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/gs4_0007-200x200.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. New Zealand was the first place in the world to sell the S4 due to the fact it was a \'same day\' global launch. We created a virtual queue where people could line up to get their hands on the new phone first. Our goal was to showcase the phone\'s features, while capitalizing on social media to extend the campaign reach.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built in HTML on top of the Zend Framework with Facebook &amp; Twitter integration, timed page releases and a JavaScript controlled virtual queue. The queue was also replicated in real life on a 150m long LED screen which was erected in Aotea Square. The queue took live facebook comments and tweets and placed them in speech bubbles next to the users selected avatar and profile picture both on the website and in real time in Aotea Square.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was how to maximize social influence and reduce point loading. Each day for 12 days we released new pieces of sharable content. Each time that content was liked, re-shared, commented or re-tweeted by a unique user, the person would receive points and be moved up the queue. The queue itself was a pretty complex piece of work with over 10,000 people projected to join the queue and it having to dynamically update.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nEach time the user shared a piece of content, we recorded the post\'s ID against their user. Each time the user logged in to the site, we would look up their posts and calculate their social influence by various means. Their points were then stored against the user and determined their position in the queue. This was done on login rather than as a scheduled task to reduce point loading on the server. The queue it self was coded largely in JavaScript. The queue would only load avatars of people in your actual view to reduce load. Each time the user scrolled, the visible section of the queue would be calculated and loaded in.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis site looked great and held together well, even with the high traffic we experienced. We over shot our expected users by 50%, with 15,000 people signing up. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign. The site got a lot of media attention and a segment on 7sharp. For the spend, this project over achieved and was a major success.\r\n<h3>Awards</h3>\r\nFacebook Studio 2014: Silver\r\n\r\nAxis 2014:  Grand Prix - Out of home,  Gold - Digital and Interactive, Gold - Integrated, Silver - Social', 'The Smart Phoneline', 'This was the flagship site for the NZ launch of the Galaxy S4. The site attained over 50,000 content pieces published to Facebook which created over 3 Million story impressions throughout the campaign.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '755-revision-25', '', '', '2014-05-29 21:57:24', '2014-05-29 09:57:24', '', '755', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/755-revision-25/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1191', '1', '2015-04-04 15:29:14', '2015-04-04 03:29:14', 'Writing server scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet can seem like a daunting task, but its actually reasonably simple to get up and running.\r\n\r\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ Graphical User Interface wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-22', '', '', '2015-04-04 15:29:14', '2015-04-04 03:29:14', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-22/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1091', '1', '2015-04-03 12:13:01', '2015-04-03 00:13:01', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable fully anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\r\n\r\nAs shown in the above gallery, on the \"Send Coins\" page, there is a tick box to \"Send Coins Anonymously\". When this box is checked, instead of sending the coins directly to the recipient you\'ve specified, the transaction will be routed through the servers we\'ve setup and the Navajo Subchain.\r\n\r\nThe way this works is quite complex and is best outlined by this network diagram:\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #eee; border: 1px solid #DDD; padding: 2px; text-align: center;\"><a class=\"fancybox\" style=\"width: 200px;\" title=\"Navajo Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png\" rel=\"galleryDiagram\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1099\" alt=\"Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Untitled-2.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\nWhat sets Navajocoin apart from other alternative coins and indeed Bitcoin itself, is this capacity to process fully anonymous value transactions between users through its use of our cutting edge subchain technology.\r\n\r\nMost anonymous cryptocurrencies simply use coin mixing networks which rely on centralised databases to process transactions. Navajocoin on the other hand uses a decentralised and separate subchain, making it less vulnerable to attack and breakdown. Routing instructions through the private subchain literally breaks the link on the main block chain between sender and receiver, making it impossible to trace the received coins origins.\r\n\r\nI have been solely responsible for architecting and writing the code which powers the Incoming and Outgoing Anonymous Gateways as well as the API which chooses an active entry point to the subchian.\r\n\r\nThis has been a complex task and a rewarding challenge.\r\n\r\nThe next major step for the Navajo Anonymous Transaction system is to bundle this code into a re-distributable package so anyone running a web server can setup their own Anonymous Gateway. This would make the autonomous processing of the anonymous transactions truly decentralised and almost impossible to shut down.\r\n\r\nThe system is fully operational and released to the public.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajo Anonymous Transactions', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'navajocoin-anonymous-transactions', '', '', '2015-04-04 14:35:53', '2015-04-04 02:35:53', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=1091', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('1101', '1', '2015-04-03 12:33:01', '2015-04-03 00:33:01', '', 'The address is changed to one of our nodes and the destination is encrypted as the Transaction Comment', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'screen3', '', '', '2015-04-03 12:33:01', '2015-04-03 00:33:01', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/screen3.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1102', '1', '2015-04-03 12:33:02', '2015-04-03 00:33:02', '', 'Sending an anonymous transaction', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'screen2', '', '', '2015-04-03 12:33:02', '2015-04-03 00:33:02', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/screen2.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1103', '1', '2015-04-03 12:33:02', '2015-04-03 00:33:02', '', 'Coins are received after passing through the subchain in random amounts', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'screen4', '', '', '2015-04-03 12:33:02', '2015-04-03 00:33:02', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/screen4.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1104', '1', '2015-04-03 12:33:03', '2015-04-03 00:33:03', '', 'Overview with Market Ticker', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'screen1', '', '', '2015-04-03 12:33:03', '2015-04-03 00:33:03', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/screen1.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1096', '1', '2015-04-03 12:11:29', '2015-04-03 00:11:29', '', 'Navajocoin Anonymous Transactions', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision', '', '', '2015-04-03 12:11:29', '2015-04-03 00:11:29', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1097', '1', '2015-04-03 12:25:45', '2015-04-03 00:25:45', '', 'navajo-blog', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'navajo-blog', '', '', '2015-04-03 12:25:45', '2015-04-03 00:25:45', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/navajo-blog.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1098', '1', '2015-04-04 14:30:10', '2015-04-04 02:30:10', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable fully anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.\n\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\n\nAs shown in the above gallery, on the \"Send Coins\" page, there is a tick box to \"Send Coins Anonymously\". When this box is checked, instead of sending the coins directly to the recipient you\'ve specified, the transaction will be routed through the servers we\'ve setup and the Navajo Subchain.\n\nThe way this works is quite complex and is best outlined by this network diagram:\n<div style=\"background-color: #eee; border: 1px solid #DDD; padding: 2px; text-align: center;\"><a class=\"fancybox\" style=\"width: 200px;\" title=\"Navajo Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png\" rel=\"galleryDiagram\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1099\" alt=\"Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Untitled-2.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\nWhat sets Navajocoin apart from other alternative coins and indeed Bitcoin itself, is this capacity to process fully anonymous value transactions between users through its use of our cutting edge subchain technology.\n\nMost anonymous cryptocurrencies simply use coin mixing networks which rely on centralised databases to process transactions. Navajocoin on the other hand uses a decentralised and separate subchain, making it less vulnerable to attack and breakdown. Routing instructions through the private subchain literally breaks the link on the main block chain between sender and receiver, making it impossible to trace the received coins origins.\n\nI have been solely responsible for architecting and writing the code which powers the Incoming and Outgoing Anonymous Gateways as well as the API which chooses an active entry point to the subchian.\n\nThis has been a complex task and a rewarding challenge.\n\nThe next major step for the Navajo Anonymous Transaction system is to bundle this code into a re-distributable package so anyone running a web server can setup their own Anonymous Gateway. This would make the autonomous processing of the anonymous transactions truly decentralised and almost impossible to shut down.\n\nThe system is fully operational and released to the public.\n\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajo Anonymous Transactions', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-autosave', '', '', '2015-04-04 14:30:10', '2015-04-04 02:30:10', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1099', '1', '2015-04-03 12:29:22', '2015-04-03 00:29:22', '', 'Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'nsk1axl-1', '', '', '2015-04-03 12:29:22', '2015-04-03 00:29:22', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png', '0', 'attachment', 'image/png', '0'), ('1100', '1', '2015-04-03 12:13:01', '2015-04-03 00:13:01', '[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1095,1093,1094,1092\"]', 'Navajocoin Anonymous Transactions', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision-2', '', '', '2015-04-03 12:13:01', '2015-04-03 00:13:01', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1110', '1', '2015-04-03 12:37:24', '2015-04-03 00:37:24', '[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\r\n\r\nNavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of