y community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision-13', '', '', '2015-04-03 12:56:13', '2015-04-03 00:56:13', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision-13/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1118', '1', '2015-04-03 13:02:35', '2015-04-03 01:02:35', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\r\n\r\nAs shown in the above gallery, on the \"Send Coins\" page, there is a tick box to \"Send Coins Anonymously\". When this box is checked, instead of sending the coins directly to the recipient you\'ve specified, the transaction will be routed through the servers we\'ve setup and the Navajo Subchain.\r\n\r\nThe way this works is quite complex and is best outlined by this network diagram:\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Navajo Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png\" rel=\"galleryDiagram\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1099\" alt=\"Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Untitled-2.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWhat sets Navajocoin apart from other alternative coins and indeed Bitcoin itself, is its capacity to process fully anonymous value transactions between users through its use of its cutting edge subchain technology.\r\n\r\nMost anonymous cryptocurrencies simply use coin mixing networks which rely on centralised databases to process transactions. Navajocoin on the other hand uses a decentralised and separate subchain, making it less vulnerable to attack and breakdown. Routing instructions through the private subchain literally breaks the link on the main block chain between sender and receiver, making it impossible to trace the received coins origins.\r\n\r\nI have been solely responsible for architecting and writing the code which powers the Incoming and Outgoing anonymous nodes as well as the API which chooses an active entry point to the subchian.\r\n\r\nThis has been a complex task and a rewarding challenge.\r\n\r\nThe system is fully operational and released to the public. For more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the website: http://www.navajocoin.org\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Navajocoin Anonymous Transactions', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision-14', '', '', '2015-04-03 13:02:35', '2015-04-03 01:02:35', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision-14/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('1119', '1', '2015-04-03 13:03:45', '2015-04-03 01:03:45', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\r\n\r\nAs shown in the above gallery, on the \"Send Coins\" page, there is a tick box to \"Send Coins Anonymously\". When this box is checked, instead of sending the coins directly to the recipient you\'ve specified, the transaction will be routed through the servers we\'ve setup and the Navajo Subchain.\r\n\r\nThe way this works is quite complex and is best outlined by this network diagram:\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Navajo Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png\" rel=\"galleryDiagram\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1099\" alt=\"Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Untitled-2.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWhat sets Navajocoin apart from other alternative coins and indeed Bitcoin itself, is its capacity to process fully anonymous value transactions between users through its use of its cutting edge subchain technology.\r\n\r\nMost anonymous cryptocurrencies simply use coin mixing networks which rely on centralised databases to process transactions. Navajocoin on the other hand uses a decentralised and separate subchain, making it less vulnerable to attack and breakdown. Routing instructions through the private subchain literally breaks the link on the main block chain between sender and receiver, making it impossible to trace the received coins origins.\r\n\r\nI have been solely responsible for architecting and writing the code which powers the Incoming and Outgoing anonymous nodes as well as the API which chooses an active entry point to the subchian.\r\n\r\nThis has been a complex task and a rewarding challenge.\r\n\r\nThe system is fully operational and released to the public. For more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajocoin Anonymous Transactions', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision-15', '', '', '2015-04-03 13:03:45', '2015-04-03 01:03:45', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision-15/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1120', '1', '2015-04-03 13:06:07', '2015-04-03 01:06:07', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\r\n\r\nAs shown in the above gallery, on the \"Send Coins\" page, there is a tick box to \"Send Coins Anonymously\". When this box is checked, instead of sending the coins directly to the recipient you\'ve specified, the transaction will be routed through the servers we\'ve setup and the Navajo Subchain.\r\n\r\nThe way this works is quite complex and is best outlined by this network diagram:\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" title=\"Navajo Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png\" rel=\"galleryDiagram\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1099\" alt=\"Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Untitled-2.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWhat sets Navajocoin apart from other alternative coins and indeed Bitcoin itself, is this capacity to process fully anonymous value transactions between users through its use of our cutting edge subchain technology.\r\n\r\nMost anonymous cryptocurrencies simply use coin mixing networks which rely on centralised databases to process transactions. Navajocoin on the other hand uses a decentralised and separate subchain, making it less vulnerable to attack and breakdown. Routing instructions through the private subchain literally breaks the link on the main block chain between sender and receiver, making it impossible to trace the received coins origins.\r\n\r\nI have been solely responsible for architecting and writing the code which powers the Incoming and Outgoing anonymous nodes as well as the API which chooses an active entry point to the subchian.\r\n\r\nThis has been a complex task and a rewarding challenge.\r\n\r\nThe next major step for the Navajo Anonymous Transaction system is to bundle this code into a re-distributable package so anyone running a web server can setup their own Anonymous Gateway. This would make the autonomous processing of the anonymous transactions truly decentralised and almost impossible to shut down.\r\n\r\nThe system is fully operational and released to the public.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajocoin Anonymous Transactions', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision-16', '', '', '2015-04-03 13:06:07', '2015-04-03 01:06:07', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision-16/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1121', '1', '2015-04-03 13:07:36', '2015-04-03 01:07:36', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\r\n\r\nAs shown in the above gallery, on the \"Send Coins\" page, there is a tick box to \"Send Coins Anonymously\". When this box is checked, instead of sending the coins directly to the recipient you\'ve specified, the transaction will be routed through the servers we\'ve setup and the Navajo Subchain.\r\n\r\nThe way this works is quite complex and is best outlined by this network diagram:\r\n\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" style=\"width:200px\" title=\"Navajo Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png\" rel=\"galleryDiagram\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1099\" alt=\"Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Untitled-2.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n\r\nWhat sets Navajocoin apart from other alternative coins and indeed Bitcoin itself, is this capacity to process fully anonymous value transactions between users through its use of our cutting edge subchain technology.\r\n\r\nMost anonymous cryptocurrencies simply use coin mixing networks which rely on centralised databases to process transactions. Navajocoin on the other hand uses a decentralised and separate subchain, making it less vulnerable to attack and breakdown. Routing instructions through the private subchain literally breaks the link on the main block chain between sender and receiver, making it impossible to trace the received coins origins.\r\n\r\nI have been solely responsible for architecting and writing the code which powers the Incoming and Outgoing anonymous nodes as well as the API which chooses an active entry point to the subchian.\r\n\r\nThis has been a complex task and a rewarding challenge.\r\n\r\nThe next major step for the Navajo Anonymous Transaction system is to bundle this code into a re-distributable package so anyone running a web server can setup their own Anonymous Gateway. This would make the autonomous processing of the anonymous transactions truly decentralised and almost impossible to shut down.\r\n\r\nThe system is fully operational and released to the public.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajocoin Anonymous Transactions', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision-17', '', '', '2015-04-03 13:07:36', '2015-04-03 01:07:36', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision-17/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1122', '1', '2015-04-03 13:10:09', '2015-04-03 01:10:09', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\r\n\r\nAs shown in the above gallery, on the \"Send Coins\" page, there is a tick box to \"Send Coins Anonymously\". When this box is checked, instead of sending the coins directly to the recipient you\'ve specified, the transaction will be routed through the servers we\'ve setup and the Navajo Subchain.\r\n\r\nThe way this works is quite complex and is best outlined by this network diagram:\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #EEE; border: 1px solid #DDD; padding: 5px; text-align: center;\">\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" style=\"width:200px\" title=\"Navajo Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png\" rel=\"galleryDiagram\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1099\" alt=\"Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Untitled-2.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n</div>\r\nWhat sets Navajocoin apart from other alternative coins and indeed Bitcoin itself, is this capacity to process fully anonymous value transactions between users through its use of our cutting edge subchain technology.\r\n\r\nMost anonymous cryptocurrencies simply use coin mixing networks which rely on centralised databases to process transactions. Navajocoin on the other hand uses a decentralised and separate subchain, making it less vulnerable to attack and breakdown. Routing instructions through the private subchain literally breaks the link on the main block chain between sender and receiver, making it impossible to trace the received coins origins.\r\n\r\nI have been solely responsible for architecting and writing the code which powers the Incoming and Outgoing anonymous nodes as well as the API which chooses an active entry point to the subchian.\r\n\r\nThis has been a complex task and a rewarding challenge.\r\n\r\nThe next major step for the Navajo Anonymous Transaction system is to bundle this code into a re-distributable package so anyone running a web server can setup their own Anonymous Gateway. This would make the autonomous processing of the anonymous transactions truly decentralised and almost impossible to shut down.\r\n\r\nThe system is fully operational and released to the public.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajocoin Anonymous Transactions', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision-18', '', '', '2015-04-03 13:10:09', '2015-04-03 01:10:09', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision-18/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1123', '1', '2015-04-03 13:10:28', '2015-04-03 01:10:28', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\r\n\r\nAs shown in the above gallery, on the \"Send Coins\" page, there is a tick box to \"Send Coins Anonymously\". When this box is checked, instead of sending the coins directly to the recipient you\'ve specified, the transaction will be routed through the servers we\'ve setup and the Navajo Subchain.\r\n\r\nThe way this works is quite complex and is best outlined by this network diagram:\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #EEE; border: 1px solid #DDD; padding: 2px; text-align: center;\">\r\n<a class=\"fancybox\" style=\"width:200px\" title=\"Navajo Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png\" rel=\"galleryDiagram\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1099\" alt=\"Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Untitled-2.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>\r\n</div>\r\nWhat sets Navajocoin apart from other alternative coins and indeed Bitcoin itself, is this capacity to process fully anonymous value transactions between users through its use of our cutting edge subchain technology.\r\n\r\nMost anonymous cryptocurrencies simply use coin mixing networks which rely on centralised databases to process transactions. Navajocoin on the other hand uses a decentralised and separate subchain, making it less vulnerable to attack and breakdown. Routing instructions through the private subchain literally breaks the link on the main block chain between sender and receiver, making it impossible to trace the received coins origins.\r\n\r\nI have been solely responsible for architecting and writing the code which powers the Incoming and Outgoing anonymous nodes as well as the API which chooses an active entry point to the subchian.\r\n\r\nThis has been a complex task and a rewarding challenge.\r\n\r\nThe next major step for the Navajo Anonymous Transaction system is to bundle this code into a re-distributable package so anyone running a web server can setup their own Anonymous Gateway. This would make the autonomous processing of the anonymous transactions truly decentralised and almost impossible to shut down.\r\n\r\nThe system is fully operational and released to the public.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajocoin Anonymous Transactions', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision-19', '', '', '2015-04-03 13:10:28', '2015-04-03 01:10:28', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision-19/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1125', '1', '2015-03-03 14:03:25', '2015-03-03 02:03:25', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All communications are encrypted by the wallet before being sent. There is a main chat room for everyone who is logged on and also the ability to start a private chat between users. The wallet will also notify you if you have unread messages waiting while you\'re not focused on the chat tab.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1136,1138,1137,1139\"]\r\n\r\nSome of the more complex features of the chat system are outlined in the gallery above.\r\n\r\nThe login screen gives you the option to login anonymously or register your username. If you tick the anonymous box, it will skip the registration process and you can use whatever username you like as long as it is not already registered by another user. This allows people to freely use the chat feature without any strings attached.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to register your username, you can click the register button. This will take you to a screen where you type your username, select a wallet address you want to link it to, then an optional email address which is used for recovery purposes. The way the system works is that your wallet address is your unique identifier so you don\'t need a password. Once you\'ve registered your username, only a wallet that contains the registered address can login using that username.\r\n\r\nIf you want to transfer the username to another wallet address within your wallet, you can use the transfer page. This must be done before deleting the wallet address which is associated with the username.\r\n\r\nIf you have deleted the wallet associated with your username, there is a recovery option. This will only work if you submitted your email when registering. If you have done that, then you will receive an email containing a one use token that can be entered into the wallet to recover your username and assign it to one of your new wallet addresses.\r\n\r\nThis register, login, transfer &amp; recovery system which is all based on linking wallet addresses to usernames was a real challenge. It was one of the biggest features which I have personally built inside a C++ Cryptocurrency wallet.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajo Encrypted Chat', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'navajo-encrypted-chat', '', '', '2015-04-04 14:41:33', '2015-04-04 02:41:33', '', '6', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?page_id=1125', '0', 'page', '', '0'), ('1126', '1', '2015-04-03 13:21:17', '2015-04-03 01:21:17', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\r\n\r\nAs shown in the above gallery, on the \"Send Coins\" page, there is a tick box to \"Send Coins Anonymously\". When this box is checked, instead of sending the coins directly to the recipient you\'ve specified, the transaction will be routed through the servers we\'ve setup and the Navajo Subchain.\r\n\r\nThe way this works is quite complex and is best outlined by this network diagram:\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #eee; border: 1px solid #DDD; padding: 2px; text-align: center;\"><a class=\"fancybox\" style=\"width: 200px;\" title=\"Navajo Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png\" rel=\"galleryDiagram\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1099\" alt=\"Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Untitled-2.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\nWhat sets Navajocoin apart from other alternative coins and indeed Bitcoin itself, is this capacity to process fully anonymous value transactions between users through its use of our cutting edge subchain technology.\r\n\r\nMost anonymous cryptocurrencies simply use coin mixing networks which rely on centralised databases to process transactions. Navajocoin on the other hand uses a decentralised and separate subchain, making it less vulnerable to attack and breakdown. Routing instructions through the private subchain literally breaks the link on the main block chain between sender and receiver, making it impossible to trace the received coins origins.\r\n\r\nI have been solely responsible for architecting and writing the code which powers the Incoming and Outgoing Anonymous Gateways as well as the API which chooses an active entry point to the subchian.\r\n\r\nThis has been a complex task and a rewarding challenge.\r\n\r\nThe next major step for the Navajo Anonymous Transaction system is to bundle this code into a re-distributable package so anyone running a web server can setup their own Anonymous Gateway. This would make the autonomous processing of the anonymous transactions truly decentralised and almost impossible to shut down.\r\n\r\nThe system is fully operational and released to the public.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajocoin Anonymous Transactions', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision-20', '', '', '2015-04-03 13:21:17', '2015-04-03 01:21:17', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision-20/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1127', '1', '2015-04-03 13:35:05', '2015-04-03 01:35:05', '', 'navajo-chat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'navajo-chat', '', '', '2015-04-03 13:35:05', '2015-04-03 01:35:05', '', '1125', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/navajo-chat.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1137', '1', '2015-04-03 20:57:10', '2015-04-03 08:57:10', '', 'Recover Username', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'recover', '', '', '2015-04-03 20:57:10', '2015-04-03 08:57:10', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/recover.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1138', '1', '2015-04-03 20:57:11', '2015-04-03 08:57:11', '', 'Register Username', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'register', '', '', '2015-04-03 20:57:11', '2015-04-03 08:57:11', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/register.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1139', '1', '2015-04-03 20:57:12', '2015-04-03 08:57:12', '', 'Transfer Username', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'transfer', '', '', '2015-04-03 20:57:12', '2015-04-03 08:57:12', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/transfer.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1140', '1', '2015-04-03 14:04:09', '2015-04-03 02:04:09', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. There is a main chat room for everyone who is logged on and also the ability to start a private chat between users. The wallet will also notify you if you have unread chat messages waiting while you\'re not focused on the chat tab.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1131,1129,1128,1130\"]\r\n\r\nSome of the more complex features of the chat system are outlined in the gallery above.\r\n\r\nThe login screen gives you the option to login anonymously or register your username. If you tick the anonymous box, it will skip the registration process and you can use whatever username you like as long as it is not already registered by another user. This allows people to freely use the chat feature without any strings attached.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to register your username, you can click the register button. This will take you to a screen where you type your username, select a wallet address you want to link it to, then an optional email address which is used for recovery purposes. The way the system works is your wallet address is your unique identifier, so you don\'t need a password. Once you\'ve registered your username, only a wallet with your address can login using that name.\r\n\r\nIf you want to transfer the username to another wallet address within your wallet, you can use the transfer page. This must be done before deleting the wallet address which is associated with the username.\r\n\r\nIf you have accidentally deleted the wallet associated with your username, there is a recovery option. This will only work if you submitted your email when registering. If you have done that, then you will receive an email containing a once use token that can be entered into the wallet to recover your username and assign it to one of your new wallet addresses.\r\n\r\nThis register, login, transfer &amp; recover system which is all based on linking wallet addresses to usernames was a real challenge. It was one of the biggest features which I have personally built inside a C++ Cryptocurrency wallet.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajo Encrypted Chat', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1125-revision-4', '', '', '2015-04-03 14:04:09', '2015-04-03 02:04:09', '', '1125', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1125-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1136', '1', '2015-04-03 20:57:07', '2015-04-03 08:57:07', '', 'Login Screen', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'main', '', '', '2015-04-03 20:57:07', '2015-04-03 08:57:07', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/main.jpg', '0', 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', '0'), ('1132', '1', '2015-04-03 14:03:11', '2015-04-03 02:03:11', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conte. There is a main chat room for everyone who is logged on and also the ability to start a private chat between users. The wallet will also notify you if you have unread chat messages waiting while you\'re not focused on the chat tab.\n\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1131,1129,1128,1130\"]\n\nSome of the more complex features of the chat system are outlined in the gallery above.\n\nThe login screen gives you the option to login anonymously or register your username. If you tick the anonymous box, it will skip the registration process and you can use whatever username you like as long as it is not already registered by another user. This allows people to freely use the chat feature without any strings attached.\n\nIf you would like to register your username, you can click the register button. This will take you to a screen where you type your username, select a wallet address you want to link it to, then an optional email address which is used for recovery purposes. The way the system works is your wallet address is your unique identifier, so you don\'t need a password. Once you\'ve registered your username, only a wallet with your address can login using that name.\n\nIf you want to transfer the username to another wallet address within your wallet, you can use the transfer page. This must be done before deleting the wallet address which is associated with the username.\n\nIf you have accidentally deleted the wallet associated with your username, there is a recovery option. This will only work if you submitted your email when registering. If you have done that, then you will receive an email containing a once use token that can be entered into the wallet to recover your username and assign it to one of your new wallet addresses.\n\nThis register, login, transfer &amp; recover system which is all based on linking wallet addresses to usernames was a real challenge. It was one of the biggest features which I have personally built inside a C++ Cryptocurrency wallet.\n\n&nbsp;', 'Navajo Encrypted Chat', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1125-revision', '', '', '2015-04-03 14:03:11', '2015-04-03 02:03:11', '', '1125', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1125-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1133', '1', '2015-04-03 14:03:25', '2015-04-03 02:03:25', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. There is a main chat room for everyone who is logged on and also the ability to start a private chat between users. The wallet will also notify you if you have unread chat messages waiting while you\'re not focused on the chat tab.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1131,1129,1128,1130\"]\r\n\r\nSome of the more complex features of the chat system are outlined in the gallery above.\r\n\r\nThe login screen gives you the option to login anonymously or register your username. If you tick the anonymous box, it will skip the registr