ables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. There is a main chat room for everyone who is logged on and also the ability to start a private chat between users. The wallet will also notify you if you have unread chat messages waiting while you\'re not focused on the chat tab.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1131,1129,1128,1130\"]\r\n\r\nSome of the more complex features of the chat system are outlined in the gallery above.\r\n\r\nThe login screen gives you the option to login anonymously or register your username. If you tick the anonymous box, it will skip the registration process and you can use whatever username you like as long as it is not already registered by another user. This allows people to freely use the chat feature without any strings attached.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to register your username, you can click the register button. This will take you to a screen where you type your username, select a wallet address you want to link it to, then an optional email address which is used for recovery purposes. The way the system works is your wallet address is your unique identifier, so you don\'t need a password. Once you\'ve registered your username, only a wallet with your address can login using that name.\r\n\r\nIf you want to transfer the username to another wallet address within your wallet, you can use the transfer page. This must be done before deleting the wallet address which is associated with the username.\r\n\r\nIf you have accidentally deleted the wallet associated with your username, there is a recovery option. This will only work if you submitted your email when registering. If you have done that, then you will receive an email containing a once use token that can be entered into the wallet to recover your username and assign it to one of your new wallet addresses.\r\n\r\nThis register, login, transfer &amp; recover system which is all based on linking wallet addresses to usernames was a real challenge. It was one of the biggest features which I have personally built inside a C++ Cryptocurrency wallet.', 'Navajo Encrypted Chat', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1125-revision-3', '', '', '2015-04-03 14:03:43', '2015-04-03 02:03:43', '', '1125', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1125-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1135', '1', '2015-04-04 14:41:01', '2015-04-04 02:41:01', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All communications are encrypted by the wallet before being sent. There is a main chat room for everyone who is logged on and also the ability to start a private chat between users. The wallet will also notify you if you have unread chat messages waiting while you\'re not focused on the chat tab.\n\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1136,1138,1137,1139\"]\n\nSome of the more complex features of the chat system are outlined in the gallery above.\n\nThe login screen gives you the option to login anonymously or register your username. If you tick the anonymous box, it will skip the registration process and you can use whatever username you like as long as it is not already registered by another user. This allows people to freely use the chat feature without any strings attached.\n\nIf you would like to register your username, you can click the register button. This will take you to a screen where you type your username, select a wallet address you want to link it to, then an optional email address which is used for recovery purposes. The way the system works is that your wallet address is your unique identifier so you don\'t need a password. Once you\'ve registered your username, only a wallet that contains the registered address can login using that username.\n\nIf you want to transfer the username to another wallet address within your wallet, you can use the transfer page. This must be done before deleting the wallet address which is associated with the username.\n\nIf you have deleted the wallet associated with your username, there is a recovery option. This will only work if you submitted your email when registering. If you have done that, then you will receive an email containing a one use token that can be entered into the wallet to recover your username and assign it to one of your new wallet addresses.\n\nThis register, login, transfer &amp; recovery system which is all based on linking wallet addresses to usernames was a real challenge. It was one of the biggest features which I have personally built inside a C++ Cryptocurrency wallet.\n\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajo Encrypted Chat', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1125-autosave', '', '', '2015-04-04 14:41:01', '2015-04-04 02:41:01', '', '1125', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1125-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1141', '1', '2015-04-03 20:58:18', '2015-04-03 08:58:18', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. There is a main chat room for everyone who is logged on and also the ability to start a private chat between users. The wallet will also notify you if you have unread chat messages waiting while you\'re not focused on the chat tab.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1136,1138,1137,1139\"]\r\n\r\nSome of the more complex features of the chat system are outlined in the gallery above.\r\n\r\nThe login screen gives you the option to login anonymously or register your username. If you tick the anonymous box, it will skip the registration process and you can use whatever username you like as long as it is not already registered by another user. This allows people to freely use the chat feature without any strings attached.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to register your username, you can click the register button. This will take you to a screen where you type your username, select a wallet address you want to link it to, then an optional email address which is used for recovery purposes. The way the system works is your wallet address is your unique identifier, so you don\'t need a password. Once you\'ve registered your username, only a wallet with your address can login using that name.\r\n\r\nIf you want to transfer the username to another wallet address within your wallet, you can use the transfer page. This must be done before deleting the wallet address which is associated with the username.\r\n\r\nIf you have accidentally deleted the wallet associated with your username, there is a recovery option. This will only work if you submitted your email when registering. If you have done that, then you will receive an email containing a once use token that can be entered into the wallet to recover your username and assign it to one of your new wallet addresses.\r\n\r\nThis register, login, transfer &amp; recover system which is all based on linking wallet addresses to usernames was a real challenge. It was one of the biggest features which I have personally built inside a C++ Cryptocurrency wallet.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajo Encrypted Chat', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1125-revision-5', '', '', '2015-04-03 20:58:18', '2015-04-03 08:58:18', '', '1125', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1125-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1142', '1', '2015-04-03 20:58:48', '2015-04-03 08:58:48', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. There is a main chat room for everyone who is logged on and also the ability to start a private chat between users. The wallet will also notify you if you have unread chat messages waiting while you\'re not focused on the chat tab.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1136,1138,1137,1139\"]\r\n\r\nSome of the more complex features of the chat system are outlined in the gallery above.\r\n\r\nThe login screen gives you the option to login anonymously or register your username. If you tick the anonymous box, it will skip the registration process and you can use whatever username you like as long as it is not already registered by another user. This allows people to freely use the chat feature without any strings attached.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to register your username, you can click the register button. This will take you to a screen where you type your username, select a wallet address you want to link it to, then an optional email address which is used for recovery purposes. The way the system works is your wallet address is your unique identifier, so you don\'t need a password. Once you\'ve registered your username, only a wallet with your address can login using that name.\r\n\r\nIf you want to transfer the username to another wallet address within your wallet, you can use the transfer page. This must be done before deleting the wallet address which is associated with the username.\r\n\r\nIf you have accidentally deleted the wallet associated with your username, there is a recovery option. This will only work if you submitted your email when registering. If you have done that, then you will receive an email containing a once use token that can be entered into the wallet to recover your username and assign it to one of your new wallet addresses.\r\n\r\nThis register, login, transfer &amp; recover system which is all based on linking wallet addresses to usernames was a real challenge. It was one of the biggest features which I have personally built inside a C++ Cryptocurrency wallet.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajo Encrypted Chat', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1125-revision-6', '', '', '2015-04-03 20:58:48', '2015-04-03 08:58:48', '', '1125', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1125-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1143', '1', '2015-02-16 13:54:15', '2015-02-16 01:54:15', 'Writing server scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet can seem like a daunting task, but its actually reasonably simple to get up and running.\r\n\r\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ Graphical User Interface wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands with PHP', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bitcoin-rcp-commands-with-php', '', '', '2015-04-12 18:44:54', '2015-04-12 06:44:54', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=1143', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('1144', '1', '2015-04-04 13:28:01', '2015-04-04 01:28:01', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\n\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\n\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Bitcoin RCP Calls with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:28:01', '2015-04-04 01:28:01', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1145', '1', '2015-04-04 13:29:01', '2015-04-04 01:29:01', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\n\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\n\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\n\nStart the daemon:\n\n[code]\n\n./bitcoind\n\n[/code]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Bitcoin RCP Calls with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-2', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:29:01', '2015-04-04 01:29:01', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1146', '1', '2015-04-04 13:30:04', '2015-04-04 01:30:04', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[code language=\"bash\"]\r\n\r\n./bitcoind\r\n\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', '', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-3', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:30:04', '2015-04-04 01:30:04', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1147', '1', '2015-04-04 13:31:15', '2015-04-04 01:31:15', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"][/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n./bitcoind\r\n\r\n[/code]&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', '', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-4', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:31:15', '2015-04-04 01:31:15', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1148', '1', '2015-04-04 13:31:48', '2015-04-04 01:31:48', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n\r\n./bitcoind\r\n\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n', '', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-5', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:31:48', '2015-04-04 01:31:48', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1149', '1', '2015-04-04 13:33:01', '2015-04-04 01:33:01', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-6', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:33:01', '2015-04-04 01:33:01', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1150', '1', '2015-04-04 13:34:06', '2015-04-04 01:34:06', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...', '', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-7', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:34:06', '2015-04-04 01:34:06', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1151', '1', '2015-04-04 13:49:24', '2015-04-04 01:49:24', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]', '', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-8', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:49:24', '2015-04-04 01:49:24', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1152', '1', '2015-04-04 13:51:03', '2015-04-04 01:51:03', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nThat\'s about as far as I am going to take this introduction, stay tuned for more ', '', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-9', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:51:03', '2015-04-04 01:51:03', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('1153', '1', '2015-04-04 13:54:15', '2015-04-04 01:54:15', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', '', 'Want to write your own scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet using PHP? Look no further, here\'s a quickstart guide which should be able to get you up and running in no time.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-10', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:54:15', '2015-04-04 01:54:15', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1161', '1', '2015-04-04 13:59:34', '2015-04-04 01:59:34', 'Writing server scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency can seem like a daunting task, but its actually reasonably simple to get up and running.\r\n\r\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-16', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:59:34', '2015-04-04 01:59:34', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-16/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1154', '1', '2015-04-04 13:54:32', '2015-04-04 01:54:32', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', 'Want to write your own scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet using PHP? Look no further, here\'s a quickstart guide which should be able to get you up and running in no time.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-11', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:54:32', '2015-04-04 01:54:32', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-11/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1155', '1', '2015-04-04 13:55:26', '2015-04-04 01:55:26', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', 'Want to write your own scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet using PHP? Look no further, here\'s a quickstart guide which should be able to get you up and running in no time.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-12', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:55:26', '2015-04-04 01:55:26', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1156', '1', '2015-04-04 13:56:03', '2015-04-04 01:56:03', 'As an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', 'Want to write your own scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet using PHP? Look no further, here\'s a quickstart guide which should be able to get you up and running in no time.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-13', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:56:03', '2015-04-04 01:56:03', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-13/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1158', '1', '2014-06-08 09:47:18', '2014-06-07 21:47:18', 'So you\'re wanting to explore the world of Raspberry Pi?\r\n\r\nThey\'re fascinating little devices and have great potential, however as with a lot of new technology, there are some teething problems which can take a while to figure out.\r\n\r\nIf you follow this guide, hopefully you won\'t get caught out by the same issues I did.\r\n\r\nThe first thing to do is to download a copy of the Raspberry Pi OS from <a title=\"Raspberry Pi Website\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">Raspberry Pi Website</a>.\r\n\r\nI installed Raspian - Debian Wheezy 2014-01-07 and from here on, this is the version which I will be discussing.\r\n\r\nThey have a great <a title=\"Quick Start Guide\" href=\"http://www.raspberrypi.org/help/quick-start-guide/\" target=\"_blank\">Quick Start Guide</a> on the website, so I\'m not going to walk you through how to plug your Raspberry Pi in and how to flash the OS to the card.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got it up and running, there are a few wrinkles that need to be ironed out. The first thing you\'ll want to do is to download and install any pending OS updates to make sure everything is running on the latest available version.\r\n\r\nI found that when I tried to run the update commands, some of the modules were failing to install. I kept getting this error:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\ninsserv: warning: script \'mathkernel\' missing LSB tags and overrides\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThis is a known issue with the Raspbian build and thankfully it\'s a relatively simple fix.  All that is happening here is that the tags which identify this file\'s purpose and dependencies are missing. I would recommend fixing this before anything else, so we can get the updates to install correctly. Open the mathkernel file using the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n$ sudo nano /etc/init.d/mathkernel\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYou should see that the first line is the shebang denoting that this is a  Bash script.\r\n\r\n[code]#!/bin/sh[/code]\r\n\r\nInsert the following lines into the file, directly after the first line:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n### BEGIN INIT INFO\r\n# Provides:          mathkernel\r\n# Required-Start:    $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Required-Stop:     $remote_fs $syslog\r\n# Default-Start:     2 3 4 5\r\n# Default-Stop:      0 1 6\r\n# Short-Description: Start mathkernel at boot\r\n# Description:       Enable mathkernel service provided by daemon.\r\n### END INIT INFO\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nPress ctrl+o to save the file and ctrl+x to exit.\r\n\r\nThis will identify the service that the script provides, when it should start and stop and what its requirements are. Adding these lines fixes the error we would have got when we tried to update the system.\r\n\r\nNext, we want to make sure that the network is setup correctly as we will need to have internet access to update the device.\r\n\r\nFor the sake of stability, i found the Ethernet port much more stable than the Wireless USB dongle I purchased, so I won\'t talk about how to set up your WiFi, there\'s plenty of guides out there <a title=\"Google: Setting up Raspberry Pi WiFi\" href=\"https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&amp;ion=1&amp;espv=2&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=setting+up+raspberry+pi+wifi\" target=\"_blank\">you can look up</a>.\r\n\r\nYour Ethernet should be set up by default and set to use a dynamic IP address. To check your Network settings, you can type the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces[/code]\r\n\r\nIt should look like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet dhcp\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you want to set it up to use a static IP, you can change it to the following:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\nauto lo\r\niface lo inet loopback\r\n\r\nauto etho0\r\niface eth0 inet static\r\naddress 192.168.1.100\r\nnetmask 255.255.255.0\r\ngateway 192.168.1.1\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nYour exact IP address settings will vary depending on your network configuration. Dont forget to save the file before exiting by pressing ctrl+o.\r\n\r\nYou can check your network settings have been applied by running the command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ifconfig[/code]\r\n\r\nThis should show you all the relevant information about your available connections. If you can\'t see eth0 in the result, or it doesnt have a line similar to this:\r\n\r\n[code]inet addr:192.168.2.2 Bcast:192.168.2.255 Mask:255.255.255.0[/code]\r\n\r\nYou may need to restart your network device with the following command\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo /etc/init.d/network restart[/code]\r\n\r\nRun the ifconfig command again and hopefully now you should be seeing your IP address in the results. If not, restart your Raspberry Pi and try again.\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo reboot[/code]\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve successfully setup your IP through either DHCP or a static configuration, you\'ll want to check that you\'re connected to the internet successfully. Try pinging Google\'s DNS server with the following command, remembering you can press ctrl+c to break from the ping cycle after a few attempts:\r\n\r\n[code]$ ping 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you see responses like theses:\r\n\r\n[code]ping: unknown host 8.8.8.8[/code]\r\n\r\nThen something has gone wrong with your network configuration. Try pinging your gateway/router, confirming that you have put in the correct settings into the network interface file and that if you used a static IP, that it is not already in use on the network and troubleshoot the connection from there.\r\n\r\nIf you however see something more like this:\r\n\r\n[code]\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=72 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=68 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=84 ms\r\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=70 ms\r\n[/code]\r\n\r\nThat means your Raspberry Pi is successfully connected to the internet and is able to contact Google.\r\n\r\nOnce you\'ve got your connection configured correctly, you\'ll want to proceed with updating the device by running:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get update[/code]\r\n\r\nThis downloads all of the updates that are available from the repository. Then to install these updates run the following command:\r\n\r\n[code]$ sudo apt-get upgrade[/code]\r\n\r\nIf you still run into the mathkernel error, then I would suggest restarting the device and running the update/upgrade commands again.\r\n\r\nOnce running, these will take some time to finish. I think it took me about 20 minutes to update everything, so go make a cup of coffee, watch a couple YouTube video\'s and come back when you\'re done.\r\n\r\nWhen  this is complete, you now have a fully working and up to date Raspberry Pi that is on the internet and can now put to work however you please.\r\n\r\nI am using my Raspberry Pi to mine crypto-currencies using a Gridseed ASIC miner. So the next things which were really important for me and will be important for a lot of Raspberry Pi projects is stability. Raspberry Pi\'s are often set up as headless devices or are in remote locations, so if they crash or the network card stops working on them, it can be a real pain to hard reboot them. As mentioned, these devices are new and sometimes they do run into issues. The easiest way to resolve a crashed device or component is simply to reboot the device.\r\n\r\nRather than jam this all into one monstrous article, I thought I would do your eyes a favour and split the topics out.\r\n\r\nMy next articles will cover:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Set up a watchdog daemon to monitor system resources and reboot the device if it crashes.</li>\r\n	<li>Set up a cron job to ping the google DNS server every 10 minutes to check for connectivity and reboot if it fails.</li>\r\n	<li>Write our own daemon to load any applications we want to run on start up and send them to the background.</li>\r\n	<li>Save this configuration to an image file so we can restore back to this point if we break anything or the SD card becomes corrupted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOnce these things are done, our Raspberry Pi should be humming along nicely with minimal down time.', 'An introduction to Raspberry Pi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1033-revision-37', '', '', '2014-06-08 09:47:18', '2014-06-07 21:47:18', '', '1033', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1033-revision-37/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1157', '1', '2015-04-04 13:56:19', '2015-04-04 01:56:19', 'Want to write your own scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet using PHP? Here’s a quickstart guide which should be able to get you up and running in no time.\r\n\r\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', 'Want to write your own scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet using PHP? Look no further, here\'s a quickstart guide which should be able to get you up and running in no time.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-14', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:56:19', '2015-04-04 01:56:19', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-14/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1160', '1', '2015-04-04 13:56:40', '2015-04-04 01:56:40', 'Want to write your own scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet using PHP? Here’s a quickstart guide which should be able to get you up and running in no time.\r\n\r\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-15', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:56:40', '2015-04-04 01:56:40', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-15/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1162', '1', '2015-04-04 13:59:57', '2015-04-04 01:59:57', 'Writing server scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet can seem like a daunting task, but its actually reasonably simple to get up and running.\r\n\r\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-17', '', '', '2015-04-04 13:59:57', '2015-04-04 01:59:57', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-17/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1163', '1', '2015-04-04 14:00:20', '2015-04-04 02:00:20', 'Writing server scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet can seem like a daunting task, but its actually reasonably simple to get up and running.\r\n\r\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-18', '', '', '2015-04-04 14:00:20', '2015-04-04 02:00:20', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-18/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1164', '1', '2015-04-03 13:31:32', '2015-04-03 01:31:32', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1104,1102,1101,1103\"]\r\n\r\nAs shown in the above gallery, on the \"Send Coins\" page, there is a tick box to \"Send Coins Anonymously\". When this box is checked, instead of sending the coins directly to the recipient you\'ve specified, the transaction will be routed through the servers we\'ve setup and the Navajo Subchain.\r\n\r\nThe way this works is quite complex and is best outlined by this network diagram:\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #eee; border: 1px solid #DDD; padding: 2px; text-align: center;\"><a class=\"fancybox\" style=\"width: 200px;\" title=\"Navajo Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/nsk1AXl-1.png\" rel=\"galleryDiagram\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1099\" alt=\"Anonymous Transaction Network Diagram\" src=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Untitled-2.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a></div>\r\nWhat sets Navajocoin apart from other alternative coins and indeed Bitcoin itself, is this capacity to process fully anonymous value transactions between users through its use of our cutting edge subchain technology.\r\n\r\nMost anonymous cryptocurrencies simply use coin mixing networks which rely on centralised databases to process transactions. Navajocoin on the other hand uses a decentralised and separate subchain, making it less vulnerable to attack and breakdown. Routing instructions through the private subchain literally breaks the link on the main block chain between sender and receiver, making it impossible to trace the received coins origins.\r\n\r\nI have been solely responsible for architecting and writing the code which powers the Incoming and Outgoing Anonymous Gateways as well as the API which chooses an active entry point to the subchian.\r\n\r\nThis has been a complex task and a rewarding challenge.\r\n\r\nThe next major step for the Navajo Anonymous Transaction system is to bundle this code into a re-distributable package so anyone running a web server can setup their own Anonymous Gateway. This would make the autonomous processing of the anonymous transactions truly decentralised and almost impossible to shut down.\r\n\r\nThe system is fully operational and released to the public.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajo Anonymous Transactions', 'NavajoCoin is a cryptocurrency developed by community contributors, which in March 2015 has added optional anonymous transactions through the Navajo double encrypted subchain. It is the first cryptocurrency to enable truly anonymous transactions through the use of subchain technology.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1091-revision-21', '', '', '2015-04-03 13:31:32', '2015-04-03 01:31:32', '', '1091', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1091-revision-21/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1165', '1', '2015-04-03 20:58:55', '2015-04-03 08:58:55', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. There is a main chat room for everyone who is logged on and also the ability to start a private chat between users. The wallet will also notify you if you have unread chat messages waiting while you\'re not focused on the chat tab.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1136,1138,1137,1139\"]\r\n\r\nSome of the more complex features of the chat system are outlined in the gallery above.\r\n\r\nThe login screen gives you the option to login anonymously or register your username. If you tick the anonymous box, it will skip the registration process and you can use whatever username you like as long as it is not already registered by another user. This allows people to freely use the chat feature without any strings attached.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to register your username, you can click the register button. This will take you to a screen where you type your username, select a wallet address you want to link it to, then an optional email address which is used for recovery purposes. The way the system works is your wallet address is your unique identifier, so you don\'t need a password. Once you\'ve registered your username, only a wallet with your address can login using that name.\r\n\r\nIf you want to transfer the username to another wallet address within your wallet, you can use the transfer page. This must be done before deleting the wallet address which is associated with the username.\r\n\r\nIf you have accidentally deleted the wallet associated with your username, there is a recovery option. This will only work if you submitted your email when registering. If you have done that, then you will receive an email containing a once use token that can be entered into the wallet to recover your username and assign it to one of your new wallet addresses.\r\n\r\nThis register, login, transfer &amp; recover system which is all based on linking wallet addresses to usernames was a real challenge. It was one of the biggest features which I have personally built inside a C++ Cryptocurrency wallet.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajo Encrypted Chat', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1125-revision-7', '', '', '2015-04-03 20:58:55', '2015-04-03 08:58:55', '', '1125', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1125-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1166', '1', '2015-04-04 14:41:10', '2015-04-04 02:41:10', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All communications are encrypted by the wallet before being sent. There is a main chat room for everyone who is logged on and also the ability to start a private chat between users. The wallet will also notify you if you have unread chat messages waiting while you\'re not focused on the chat tab.\r\n\r\n[gallery link=\"file\" ids=\"1136,1138,1137,1139\"]\r\n\r\nSome of the more complex features of the chat system are outlined in the gallery above.\r\n\r\nThe login screen gives you the option to login anonymously or register your username. If you tick the anonymous box, it will skip the registration process and you can use whatever username you like as long as it is not already registered by another user. This allows people to freely use the chat feature without any strings attached.\r\n\r\nIf you would like to register your username, you can click the register button. This will take you to a screen where you type your username, select a wallet address you want to link it to, then an optional email address which is used for recovery purposes. The way the system works is that your wallet address is your unique identifier so you don\'t need a password. Once you\'ve registered your username, only a wallet that contains the registered address can login using that username.\r\n\r\nIf you want to transfer the username to another wallet address within your wallet, you can use the transfer page. This must be done before deleting the wallet address which is associated with the username.\r\n\r\nIf you have deleted the wallet associated with your username, there is a recovery option. This will only work if you submitted your email when registering. If you have done that, then you will receive an email containing a one use token that can be entered into the wallet to recover your username and assign it to one of your new wallet addresses.\r\n\r\nThis register, login, transfer &amp; recovery system which is all based on linking wallet addresses to usernames was a real challenge. It was one of the biggest features which I have personally built inside a C++ Cryptocurrency wallet.\r\n\r\nFor more information and to download your Navajocoin wallet, visit the official <a title=\"Navajocoin Website\" href=\"http://www.navajocoin.org\" target=\"_blank\">Navajocoin Website</a>.', 'Navajo Encrypted Chat', 'The Navajocoin wallet enables users to chat with each other from inside the wallet itself. All messages sent are encrypted by the wallet to protect the conversations from prying eyes. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1125-revision-8', '', '', '2015-04-04 14:41:10', '2015-04-04 02:41:10', '', '1125', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1125-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1167', '1', '2015-03-02 15:27:52', '2015-03-02 03:27:52', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-with-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands with PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands with PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either the sendrawtransaction or sendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is what I will outline below.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs stated, this is very simple. It accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or \"tx-id\". If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\r\n\r\nThe most common reasons for this command failing is the address was invalid or there were insufficient funds. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n\r\n$amount = 10;\r\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\r\n\r\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\r\n$amount = (double) $amount;\r\n\r\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\n\r\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\r\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\r\n\r\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress($address, $amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction command in my next article.\r\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'sending-bitcoin-transactions-with-php', '', '', '2015-04-05 09:33:19', '2015-04-04 21:33:19', '', '0', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/?p=1167', '0', 'post', '', '0'), ('1168', '1', '2015-04-04 14:01:47', '2015-04-04 02:01:47', 'Writing server scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet can seem like a daunting task, but its actually reasonably simple to get up and running.\r\n\r\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ GUI wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-19', '', '', '2015-04-04 14:01:47', '2015-04-04 02:01:47', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-19/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1169', '1', '2015-04-04 15:10:26', '2015-04-04 03:10:26', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\n\nThere are two main ways to send coins, the simplest way is by using the RCP command sendtoaddress.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\n\n//include the easybitcoin source\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\n\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\n\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string, float)\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\n[/sourcecode]', 'Sending raw Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision', '', '', '2015-04-04 15:10:26', '2015-04-04 03:10:26', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1170', '1', '2015-04-04 15:11:03', '2015-04-04 03:11:03', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins, the simplest way is by using the RCP command sendtoaddress.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string, float)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n\r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nThis is very easy and', 'Sending raw Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-2', '', '', '2015-04-04 15:11:03', '2015-04-04 03:11:03', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-2/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1171', '1', '2015-04-04 15:03:59', '2015-04-04 03:03:59', 'Writing server scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet can seem like a daunting task, but its actually reasonably simple to get up and running.\r\n\r\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ Graphical User Interface wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-20', '', '', '2015-04-04 15:03:59', '2015-04-04 03:03:59', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-20/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1172', '1', '2015-04-04 15:27:06', '2015-04-04 03:27:06', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\n\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either sendrawtransaction or thesendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is the one I will address below.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\n//include the easybitcoin source\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\n\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\n\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\n\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or tx-id. If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\n\nThe most common reasons for this failing is that reason for it failing is that the address is invalid or the amount was wrong. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\n\n$amount = 10;\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\n\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\n$amount = (double) $amount;\n\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\n\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\n    //return false, log an error etc..\n    return false;\n}\n\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\n\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\n    //return false, log an error etc..\n    return false;\n}\n\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\n\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-3', '', '', '2015-04-04 15:27:06', '2015-04-04 03:27:06', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-3/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES ('1173', '1', '2015-04-04 15:27:52', '2015-04-04 03:27:52', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either sendrawtransaction or thesendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is the one I will address below.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or tx-id. If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\r\n\r\nThe most common reasons for this failing is that reason for it failing is that the address is invalid or the amount was wrong. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n\r\n$amount = 10;\r\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\r\n\r\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\r\n$amount = (double) $amount;\r\n\r\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\n\r\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\r\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\r\n\r\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\r\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-4', '', '', '2015-04-04 15:27:52', '2015-04-04 03:27:52', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-4/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1174', '1', '2015-04-04 15:19:14', '2015-04-04 03:19:14', 'Writing server scripts to control a bitcoin or other cryptocurrency wallet can seem like a daunting task, but its actually reasonably simple to get up and running.\r\n\r\nAs an introduction to the topic, most cryptocurrencies are based on the opensource Bitcoin core code. This code allows itself to be operated either as C++ Graphical User Interface wallet like what you\'re probably used to running on your desktop, or as a headless service known as a daemon. These daemons are usually run on a linux environment and are controlled by text commands rather than mouse clicks.\r\n\r\nTo get a bitcoin (or similar) daemon running on your linux environment, you will first need to download the source code of the project and compile it for your particular environment. I will not get into the specifics of this here as the process differs from coin to coin and is largely dependant on which libraries the developers have required for their project. For support compiling a cryptocurrency daemon on your linux environment, its probably best you refer to the specific coins FAQ or talk to it\'s developers directly.\r\n\r\nOnce you have compiled the daemon, it\'s quite simple to control it with text commands. Here is the list of the <a title=\"Original Bitcoin RCP Commands\" href=\"https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Original_Bitcoin_client/API_calls_list\" target=\"_blank\">Original Bitcoin RCP Commands</a>, these should still be applicable to any coin cloned from bitcoin unless the developer has disabled them. It is also possible that a developer has extended on these capabilities for which you\'ll need to consult their documentation.\r\n\r\nStart the daemon:\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nCreate a new address\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getnewaddress\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\ncheck the balance of the wallet\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"bash\"]\r\n~$ ./bitcoind getbalance\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\netc...\r\n\r\nThese commands can also be accessed via PHP through an interface called RCP or <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_client_platform\" title=\"RCP Definition\" target=\"_blank\">Rich Client Platform</a> commands.\r\n\r\nThe simplest way to call these RCP commands from a PHP script is to use <a href=\"https://github.com/aceat64/EasyBitcoin-PHP\" title=\"Easybitcoin php on Github\" target=\"_blank\">Easybitcoin</a>. This is a pretty simple script that aceat64 has put together to handle the RCP commands. It is very easy to use, it\'s explained on the github page but here\'s some examples.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//start making RCP calls\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\necho &quot;Your wallets balance is: &quot; . $balance;\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nHost and port are not required when creating the bitcoin object, but if you\'re running multiple daemons, you will need to specify a port for each otherwise they will both be listening on the default port and conflict with eachother.\r\n\r\nFrom here, you can simply perform all the same operations as you would from the command line. Use the Original RCP Commands list as your reference and give it a try!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to get you up and running. I will post more specific tutorials on some of the advanced features soon.', 'Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1143-revision-21', '', '', '2015-04-04 15:19:14', '2015-04-04 03:19:14', '', '1143', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1143-revision-21/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1175', '1', '2015-04-04 15:28:43', '2015-04-04 03:28:43', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either sendrawtransaction or thesendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is the one I will address below.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or tx-id. If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\r\n\r\nThe most common reasons for this failing is that reason for it failing is that the address is invalid or the amount was wrong. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n\r\n$amount = 10;\r\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\r\n\r\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\r\n$amount = (double) $amount;\r\n\r\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\n\r\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\r\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\r\n\r\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\r\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-5', '', '', '2015-04-04 15:28:43', '2015-04-04 03:28:43', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-5/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1176', '1', '2015-04-04 21:19:36', '2015-04-04 09:19:36', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either the sendrawtransaction or sendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is the one I will address below.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or tx-id. If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\r\n\r\nThe most common reasons for this failing is that reason for it failing is that the address is invalid or the amount was wrong. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n\r\n$amount = 10;\r\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\r\n\r\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\r\n$amount = (double) $amount;\r\n\r\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\n\r\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\r\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\r\n\r\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\r\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-6', '', '', '2015-04-04 21:19:36', '2015-04-04 09:19:36', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-6/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1177', '1', '2015-04-04 21:20:33', '2015-04-04 09:20:33', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either the sendrawtransaction or sendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is what I will address below.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or tx-id. If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\r\n\r\nThe most common reasons for this failing is that reason for it failing is that the address is invalid or the amount was wrong. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n\r\n$amount = 10;\r\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\r\n\r\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\r\n$amount = (double) $amount;\r\n\r\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\n\r\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\r\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\r\n\r\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\r\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-7', '', '', '2015-04-04 21:20:33', '2015-04-04 09:20:33', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-7/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1178', '1', '2015-04-04 21:20:56', '2015-04-04 09:20:56', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either the sendrawtransaction or sendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is what I will outline below.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or tx-id. If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\r\n\r\nThe most common reasons for this failing is that reason for it failing is that the address is invalid or the amount was wrong. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n\r\n$amount = 10;\r\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\r\n\r\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\r\n$amount = (double) $amount;\r\n\r\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\n\r\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\r\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\r\n\r\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\r\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-8', '', '', '2015-04-04 21:20:56', '2015-04-04 09:20:56', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-8/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1179', '1', '2015-04-04 21:21:34', '2015-04-04 09:21:34', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either the sendrawtransaction or sendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is what I will outline below.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or \"tx-id\". If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\r\n\r\nThe most common reasons for this failing is that reason for it failing is that the address is invalid or the amount was wrong. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n\r\n$amount = 10;\r\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\r\n\r\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\r\n$amount = (double) $amount;\r\n\r\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\n\r\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\r\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\r\n\r\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\r\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-9', '', '', '2015-04-04 21:21:34', '2015-04-04 09:21:34', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-9/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1180', '1', '2015-04-04 21:22:29', '2015-04-04 09:22:29', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either the sendrawtransaction or sendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is what I will outline below.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or \"tx-id\". If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\r\n\r\nThe most common reasons for this command failing is the address is invalid or the amount was wrong. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n\r\n$amount = 10;\r\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\r\n\r\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\r\n$amount = (double) $amount;\r\n\r\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\n\r\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\r\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\r\n\r\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\r\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-10', '', '', '2015-04-04 21:22:29', '2015-04-04 09:22:29', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-10/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1181', '1', '2015-04-04 21:22:43', '2015-04-04 09:22:43', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either the sendrawtransaction or sendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is what I will outline below.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or \"tx-id\". If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\r\n\r\nThe most common reasons for this command failing is the address is invalid or there were insufficient funds. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n\r\n$amount = 10;\r\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\r\n\r\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\r\n$amount = (double) $amount;\r\n\r\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\n\r\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\r\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\r\n\r\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\r\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-11', '', '', '2015-04-04 21:22:43', '2015-04-04 09:22:43', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-11/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1182', '1', '2015-04-04 21:24:05', '2015-04-04 09:24:05', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\n\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either the sendrawtransaction or sendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is what I will outline below.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\n//include the easybitcoin source\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\n\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\n\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\n\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or \"tx-id\". If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\n\nThe most common reasons for this command failing is the address was invalid or there were insufficient funds. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\n\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\n\n$amount = 10;\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\n\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\n$amount = (double) $amount;\n\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\n\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\n    //return false, log an error etc..\n    return false;\n}\n\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\n\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\n    //return false, log an error etc..\n    return false;\n}\n\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress($address, $amount);\n\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \n}\n[/sourcecode]\n\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-autosave', '', '', '2015-04-04 21:24:05', '2015-04-04 09:24:05', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-autosave/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1183', '1', '2015-04-04 21:23:03', '2015-04-04 09:23:03', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-commands-in-php/\" title=\"Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP\" target=\"_blank\">Bitcoin RCP Commands in PHP</a>. Once you are able to interact with your bitcoin daemon using the easybitcoin interface, the natural progression would be to start sending coins using the commands.\r\n\r\nThere are two main ways to send coins; using either the sendrawtransaction or sendtoaddress RCP commands. Both have their purpose, the simplest way is using sendtoaddress which is what I will outline below.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n//include the easybitcoin source\r\nrequire_once(\'easybitcoin.php\');\r\n\r\n//make a new bitcoin object with username, password, host, port\r\n$bitcoin = new Bitcoin(\'username\',\'password\',\'127.0.0.1\',\'12345\');\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs stated, this is very simple. It simply accepts the bitcoin address and an amount. If the transaction is successful the function will return the transaction id or \"tx-id\". If the transaction was unsuccessful, it will return false and you will also get a bitcoin error which you can read out to the screen or log to a database.\r\n\r\nThe most common reasons for this command failing is the address was invalid or there were insufficient funds. There are a few checks and balances we can do before sending the coins to try and eliminate some of these errors.\r\n\r\n[sourcecode language=\"PHP\"]\r\n\r\n$amount = 10;\r\n$address = &quot;1PtvmBGQSuTzfgt4dBaYUz18jg4yzg5Bzu&quot;;\r\n\r\n//type cast the amount to be of type double\r\n$amount = (double) $amount;\r\n\r\n//check the amount we\'re sending is smaller than the wallets balance\r\n$balance = $bitcoin-&gt;getbalance();\r\n\r\nif($amount &gt; $balance){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//verify that the wallet address is valid\r\n$isValid = $bitcoin-&gt;validateaddress($address);\r\n\r\nif(!$validate[&quot;isvalid&quot;]){\r\n    //return false, log an error etc..\r\n    return false;\r\n}\r\n\r\n//send coins using sendtoaddress(string address, float amount)\r\n$transactionId = $bitcoin-&gt;sendtoaddress(&quot;bitcoin_address&quot;, amount);\r\n\r\nif($bitcoin-&gt;error){\r\n    echo &quot;ERROR: &quot; . $bitcoin-&gt;error; \r\n}\r\n[/sourcecode]\r\n\r\nAs you can see we\'ve validated the address and we\'ve also checked that the amount is less than the wallet balance. These two checks should eliminate most of the issues you\'ll encounter using this RCP command to send Bitcoin. I will cover the sendrawtransaction method in my next article.\r\n', 'Sending Bitcoin transactions with PHP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1167-revision-12', '', '', '2015-04-04 21:23:03', '2015-04-04 09:23:03', '', '1167', 'http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/1167-revision-12/', '0', 'revision', '', '0'), ('1184', '1', '2015-04-04 21:24:19', '2015-04-04 09:24:19', 'This article follows on from my introduction to making <a href=\"http://www.geekspeak.co.nz/articles/bitcoin-rcp-command